{"title_page": "Joseph Geurts", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Joseph Geurts\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      =\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1939|7|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Hasselt]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Geurts''' (born 6 July 1939) is a former Belgian [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|individual road race]] at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ge/joseph-geurts-1.html |title=Joseph Geurts Olympic Results |accessdate=31 July 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geurts, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hasselt]]\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Joseph Geurts\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      =\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1939|7|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Hasselt]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Geurts''' (born 6 July 1939) is a former Belgian [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|individual road race]] at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ge/joseph-geurts-1.html |title=Joseph Geurts Olympic Results |accessdate=31 July 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geurts, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hasselt]]\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Geurts"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n<!--Please do not add template current to this article, per discussion: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia_talk:WikiProject_COVID-19#When_should_articles_have_the_Current_template?-->\n{{infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak UK case counts.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases by country and NHS region in the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Countries |url=https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=a51606bdfb824d65a63ef0ca65aac90f |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320213943/https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=a51606bdfb824d65a63ef0ca65aac90f |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live |publisher=ArcGis Feature Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=NHS Regions |url=https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=90f3893ff60e43c9ad785c8a9073c516 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320213934/https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=90f3893ff60e43c9ad785c8a9073c516 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = United Kingdom\n| first_case      = [[York]], [[North Yorkshire]], England\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| arrival_date    = 31 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=31|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| recovery_cases  = 135 (as of 22 March)<ref name=ArcGISUK>{{cite web |url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/f94c3c90da5b4e9f9a0b19484dd4bb14 |title=Total UK cases COVID-19 Cases Update |website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com |publisher=[[Public Health England]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 25,150<!--Please do not update this value with anything other than data from GOV.UK or ArcGIS--><ref name=ArcGISUK />\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| deaths          = 1,789<!--Please do not update this value with anything other than data from GOV.UK or ArcGIS--><ref group=\"nb\" name=\"nb01\">Not included in this data is the death of one British citizen on board the [[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]] cruise ship on 28 February \u2013 see the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships]] article for more information on this case. Also not included is the death of one British citizen in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of the [[Cayman Islands]] \u2013 see the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Cayman Islands]] article for more information on this case.</ref><ref name=ArcGISUK />\n| website         = [https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public 'Coronavirus (COVID-19): latest information and advice' at www.gov.uk]<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"nb02\">Daily updates occur around 2&nbsp;pm UTC.</ref>\n}}\n\nThe ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global pandemic]] of [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2), which causes [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), spread to the [[United Kingdom]] in January 2020.<ref name=Ball31Jan2020>{{Cite news |last=Ball |first=Tom |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k |title=Hunt for contacts of coronavirus-stricken pair in York |date=31 January 2020 |work=[[The Times]]|access-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live |last2=Wace |first2=Charlotte |issn=0140-0460|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204105559/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/hunt-for-contacts-of-coronavirus-stricken-pair-in-york-dh363qf8k|archive-date=4 February 2020}}</ref> Transmission within the UK was confirmed in February,<ref name=\"BBC.co.uk\"/> leading to an epidemic with a rapid increase in cases in March.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\" /> As of 30 March, there have been 22,141 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the UK,{{refn|group=\"nb\"|name=\"nb03\"|In addition to this figure, there have been eight confirmed cases in the [[British Overseas Territories]] (including in [[Gibraltar]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theolivepress.es/spain-news/2020/03/04/covid-19-politicians-respond-to-coronavirus-case-in-gibraltar/ |title=COVID-19: Politicians respond to Coronavirus case in Gibraltar |last=Thomas |first=Diexter |date=4 March 2020 |website=Olive Press News Spain |access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305135905/https://www.theolivepress.es/spain-news/2020/03/04/covid-19-politicians-respond-to-coronavirus-case-in-gibraltar/|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Akrotiri and Dhekelia]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan |title=Army likely to embed medics in NHS hospitals to help fight coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/army-likely-to-embed-medics-in-nhs-hospitals-to-help-fight-coronavirus-operation-broadshare |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318093507/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/army-likely-to-embed-medics-in-nhs-hospitals-to-help-fight-coronavirus-operation-broadshare |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Bermuda]],<ref>[http://www.royalgazette.com/editorials/article/20200320/time-to-work-together A time to work together] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320122653/http://www.royalgazette.com/editorials/article/20200320/time-to-work-together |date=20 March 2020 }} 20 March 2020 ''www.royalgazette.com'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref> the [[Cayman Islands]],<ref>[https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/19/two-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed/ Two new coronavirus cases confirmed] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320122702/https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/19/two-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed/ |date=20 March 2020 }} 20 March 2020 ''www.caymancompass.com'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref> and [[Montserrat]]).<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Montserrat_registers_first_case_of_coronavirus?profile=1228 Montserrat registers first case of coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318144959/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Montserrat_registers_first_case_of_coronavirus?profile=1228 |date=18 March 2020 }} ''www.jamaicaobserver.com'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref>}}<ref name=ArcGISUK /> and 1,801 people with confirmed infection have died.<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"nb01\" /><ref name=ArcGISUK />\n\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] had caused a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei|Hubei Province]], China, which had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=gov.uk2Update>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): latest information and advice |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004037/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public|archive-date=8 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The UK subsequently developed a [[COVID-19 testing|prototype specific laboratory test]] for the new disease.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> The four UK [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officers]] (CMOs) raised the UK risk level from low to moderate on 30 January, upon the WHO's announcement of the disease as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern|Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC)]].<ref name=Russell13Feb2020>{{cite web |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/924664 |title=New Coronavirus: UK Public Health Campaign Launched |last=Russell |first=Peter |date=3 February 2020 |website=[[Medscape]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301185825/https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/924664|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> After cases appeared in the UK on 31 January a [[public health]] information campaign was launched to advise people how to lessen the risk of spreading the virus.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Further cases in early February prompted the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], to introduce the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]] [[statutory instrument]].<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> Guidance on [[infection control|infection prevention and control]], how to detect and diagnose COVID-19, and daily updates, including advice to travellers, have been published by the UK's [[Department of Health and Social Care]] (DHSC) and [[Public Health England]] (PHE).<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> In addition, the [[NHS]] set up COVID-19 drive-through screening centres at some hospitals.<ref name=\"clch29Feb2020\"/><ref name=\"BBCSct29Feb2020\"/> The Chief Medical Officer for England, [[Chris Whitty]], explained a four-pronged strategy to tackle the outbreak: contain, delay, research and mitigate.<ref name=Kobie/>\n\nThe earliest documented transmission within the UK appeared on 28 February 2020; all of the cases detected previously had been infected abroad.<ref name=\"BBC.co.uk\"/> By 1 March, cases had been detected in England, Wales, Northern Ireland and Scotland.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/><ref name=gov.scotCOVID-19>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Coronavirusin Scotland - gov.scot |last= |first= |date= |website=www.gov.scot|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305145636/https://www.gov.scot/coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=5 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] unveiled the Coronavirus Action Plan,<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> and the government declared the outbreak a \"level 4 incident\".<ref name=Discombe3March2020/> On 11 March, the WHO declared the outbreak a [[pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\">{{cite web |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11&nbsp;March 2020 |url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311212521/https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other responses included some schools in England choosing to close.<ref name=Bedingfield/> Airlines announced a number of flight cancellations,<ref name=BBCNews2March2020/> and some online retailers reported consumers placing unusually large orders.<ref name=guardi/> On 12 March, the UK risk level was raised from moderate to high.<ref name=Gov.UK12March2020/> Four days later, following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|outbreak in Italy]],<ref name=avoid/> whose health system shares similar values and organisation to the NHS,<ref name=Remuzzi13March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Remuzzi |first=Andrea |last2=Remuzzi |first2=Giuseppe |date=13 March 2020 |title=COVID-19 and Italy: what next? |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930627-9 |journal=[[The Lancet]] |language=English |volume=0 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30627-9 |pmid=32178769 |issn=0140-6736}}</ref> and based on evidence including forecasting by epidemiologists at [[Imperial College London]],<ref name=\"Imperial16March2020\">{{cite web |last1=Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team |title=Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID19 mortality and healthcare demand |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf |website=Imperial College London |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316223332/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> the government advised on further measures on [[social distancing]] and advised people in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70, and those with certain health conditions were urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and were asked to [[Self-isolation|self-isolate]].<ref name=avoid/>\n\nOn 18 March, it was announced that the UK would close schools to most pupils, with children of key workers and vulnerable children still able to attend.<ref name=bbcnews18March2020>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |title=Coronavirus: UK schools to close from Friday |date=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318174202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314|archive-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March, all restaurants, pubs, clubs and indoor sport and leisure facilities were ordered to close, though delivery and take-out chains were allowed to remain open.<ref name=2020_327_pdfs>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/327/pdfs/uksi_20200327_en.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323004800/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/327/pdfs/uksi_20200327_en.pdf|url-status=dead |title=The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Business Closure) (England) Regulations 2020 |archivedate=23 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, the government announced that these measures were to be tightened further, with wide-ranging restrictions made on freedom of movement, enforceable in law,<ref name=lockdown-2020-03-23>\n{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52012432 |title=PM announces strict new curbs on life in UK |date=23 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=23 March 2020}}\n</ref>\nresulting in the [[Coronavirus Act 2020]], the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020]] and other similar [[statutory instrument]]s covering other home nations.\n\n==Background==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City. However, some of those first cases with laboratory confirmed results had no link to the market, and the source of the epidemic is unknown.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/> COVID-19 typically appears with about seven days of [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] followed by some people progressing to symptoms of a [[viral pneumonia]] requiring admission to hospital.<ref name=Imperial13March2020/> From 19 March COVID-19 was no longer classified as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Kingdom medical cases chart}}\n\n===Late January 2020 \u2013 First cases===\nOn 22 January, following a confirmed [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|case of COVID-19 in the United States]] the previous day, in a man returning to Washington from Wuhan, China, where there were 440 confirmed cases at the time, the DHSC and PHE raised the risk level from \"very low\" to \"low\". As a result, [[Heathrow Airport]] received additional clinical support and tightened surveillance of the three direct flights that it receives from Wuhan every week; each were to be met by a Port Health team. In addition, all airports in the UK were to make written guidance (in English, Mandarin, and Cantonese) available for unwell travellers.<ref name=\"Mahase22Jan2020\">{{Cite journal |last=Mahase |first=Elisabeth |date=22 January 2020 |title=Coronavirus: UK screens direct flights from Wuhan after US case |url=http://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m265 |journal=British Medical Journal |volume=368 |pages=m265 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m265 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=31969317|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222041142/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m265|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"PHE23Jan2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-and-avian-flu-advice-for-travel-to-china |title=Wuhan novel coronavirus and avian flu: advice for travel to China |date=23 January 2020 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120181905/http://www.gov.uk/government/news/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-and-avian-flu-advice-for-travel-to-china|archive-date=20 January 2020|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> Simultaneously, efforts to trace 2,000 people who had flown into the UK from Wuhan over the previous 14 days were made.<ref name=BBC24Jan2020>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51232163 |title=China coronavirus: UK tracing up to 2,000 Wuhan visitors |date=24 January 2020 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=24 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124064253/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51232163|archive-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, two members of a family of Chinese nationals staying in a hotel in [[York]], one of whom studied at the [[University of York]], became the first confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the UK. Upon confirmation, they were transferred from [[Hull University Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust|Hull University Teaching Hospital]] to a specialist isolation facility, a designated High Consequence Infectious Diseases Unit in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]].<ref name=Ball31Jan2020/><ref name=Lancet14March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Moss |first=Peter |last2=Barlow |first2=Gavin |last3=Easom |first3=Nicholas |last4=Lillie |first4=Patrick |last5=Samson |first5=Anda |date=14 March 2020 |title=Lessons for managing high-consequence infections from first COVID-19 cases in the UK |url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2820%2930463-3 |journal=The Lancet |volume=395 |issue=10227 |pages=e46 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30463-3 |issn=0140-6736 |pmid=32113507}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, an [[evacuations related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|evacuation flight]] from Wuhan landed at [[RAF Brize Norton]] and the passengers, none of whom were showing symptoms, were taken to quarantine, in a staff residential block at [[Arrowe Park Hospital]] on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]].<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\">{{cite web |title=Britons in Wuhan to return home on Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131024212/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51318691 |archive-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> There had previously been contention over whether the government should assist the repatriation of UK passport holders from the most affected areas in China, or restrict travel from affected regions altogether.<ref name=\"Standard27Jan2020\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html |title=Ministers came under growing pressure today to evacuate Britons from the Chinese region shut down by the killer coronavirus. |date=27 January 2020 |work=London Evening Standard|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222145256/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/coronavirus-evacuate-britons-china-virus-hubei-warning-boris-johnson-a4345571.html|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"McHutchon25Jan2020\">{{Cite news |last=McHutchon |first=David |url=https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/ |title=Too Weak, Too Slow: The UK Government's Dithering Response to the Wuhan Coronavirus Increases the Risk of Major Loss of Life |date=25 January 2020 |work=|access-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222131735/https://www.technicalpolitics.com/articles/too-weak-too-slow-the-uk-governments-dithering-response-to-the-wuhan-coronavirus-increases-the-risk-of-major-loss-of-life/|archive-date=22 February 2020 |publisher=Technical Politics}}</ref> Some British nationals in Wuhan had been informed that they could be evacuated but any spouses or children with mainland Chinese passports could not.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350 |title=British mum told to leave son behind in Wuhan |date=30 January 2020 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219182030/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-51302350|archive-date=19 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This was later overturned, but the delay meant that some people missed the flight.<ref name=\"BBC-51318691\" />\n\n===February 2020 \u2013 Early spread===\nOn 6 February, a third confirmed case, a man who had recently travelled to Singapore prior to visiting a ski resort in the [[Haute-Savoie]], France, was reported in [[Brighton]]. He had been the source of infection to six of his relatives during a stay in France, before returning to the UK on 28 January.<ref name=\"Bosley26Feb2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus |title=First British national to contract coronavirus had been in Singapore |first1=Sarah |last1=Boseley |first2=Denis |last2=Campbell |first3=Simon |last3=Murphy |date=6 February 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=26 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207020202/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/06/third-person-in-uk-confirmed-as-having-coronavirus|archive-date=7 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Mohdin>{{Cite news |last=Mohdin |first=Kim Willsher Aamna |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals |title=Coronavirus: British nine-year-old in hospital in France |date=8 February 2020 |work=The Observer|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live |last2=Madrid |first2=and Sam Jones in |issn=0029-7712|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226161959/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/08/coronavirus-five-new-cases-in-france-are-british-nationals|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> Following confirmation of his result, the UK's CMOs expanded the number of countries where a history of previous travel associated with flu-like symptoms \u2013 such as fever, cough and difficulty breathing \u2013 in the previous 14 days would require self-isolation and calling [[NHS 111]]. These countries included China, Hong Kong, Japan, Macau, Malaysia, Republic of Korea, Singapore, Taiwan and Thailand.<ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector |title=COVID-19: guidance for staff in the transport sector |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=15 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220133756/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector/covid-19-guidance-for-staff-in-the-transport-sector|archive-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the total number of cases in the UK reached eight as four further cases were confirmed in people linked to the affected man from Brighton.<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761 |title=Coronavirus closes Brighton GP practice |date=11 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210204845/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51447761|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=PHE10Feb2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases |title=Chief Medical Officer for England announces four further coronavirus cases |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210223522/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chief-medical-officer-for-england-announces-four-further-coronavirus-cases|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Globally, the virus had spread to 28 countries.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> On the morning of 10 February, the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], announced the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]], to give public health professionals \"strengthened powers\" to keep affected people and those believed to be a possible risk of having the virus, in isolation.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> That day, the [[Arrowe Park Hospital]], Merseyside, and the Kents Hill Park hotel and conference centre, [[Milton Keynes]] became designated isolation units.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/><ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> The following day, two of the eight confirmed cases in the UK were reported by BBC News to be [[general practitioners]] (GPs).<ref name=BBCNews11Feb2020/> A ninth case was confirmed in London on 11 February.<ref name=BBC12Feb2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469 |title=Ninth coronavirus case found in UK |date=12 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=12 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212193433/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51481469|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February, the DHSC confirmed a total of 13 cases in the UK as four new cases in passengers on the cruise ship ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' were detected. Two were transferred to the [[Royal Hallamshire Hospital]] in [[Sheffield]], one to the [[Royal Liverpool University Hospital]] and one to the [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51606368 |title=Four new UK coronavirus cases among ship evacuees |date=23 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223210057/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51606368 |archive-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, the total number of confirmed cases in the UK were reported as 16, including the first case in Northern Ireland \u2013 a woman who had travelled from the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|outbreak area in northern Italy]], having also stopped in Dublin.<ref name=EveningStandard>{{Cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/coronavirus-news-live-covid19-europe-uk-latest-a4372836.html |title=Coronavirus news LIVE: Number of UK patients hits 16 as Northern Ireland confirms first case |date=27 February 2020 |work=standard.co.uk|access-date=27 February 2020 |issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227203043/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/coronavirus-news-live-covid19-europe-uk-latest-a4372836.html|archive-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Independent.ie>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/world-news/coronavirus/coronavirus-ireland-passengers-who-travelled-with-northern-irish-patient-traced-in-bid-to-prevent-outbreak-38997601.html |title=Coronavirus Ireland: Passengers who travelled with Northern Irish patient traced in bid to prevent outbreak |date=27 February 2020 |work=independent.ie|access-date=28 February 2020 |issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228202902/https://www.independent.ie/world-news/coronavirus/coronavirus-ireland-passengers-who-travelled-with-northern-irish-patient-traced-in-bid-to-prevent-outbreak-38997601.html|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, the first case in Wales was confirmed in a person who had returned from Northern Italy, who was transferred to a specialist NHS infection centre at the [[Royal Free Hospital]] in London.<ref name=BBC>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068 |title=First case confirmed in Wales |date=28 February 2020 |work=BBC|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228153606/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Shankar4March2020>{{cite web |url=https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/ |title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel coronavirus pandemic in China \u2013 Public Health Wales |last=Shankar |first=Giri |date= |website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304175055/https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|archive-date=4 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=PublicHealthWales>{{cite web |url=https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Latest information on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) \u2013 Public Health Wales |last= |first= |date= |website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229190227/https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=29 February 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, two further cases were confirmed in England, one of whom was a man who was taken to Guy's and St Thomas' and who became the 20th case of COVID-19 in the UK and the first case who did not contract the disease from abroad. He was a resident in Surrey and registered at the Haslemere Health Centre, which had previously been closed for \"deep cleaning\".<ref name=\"BBC.co.uk\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51683428.html |title=Coronavirus: Latest patient was first to be infected in UK |date=28 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=28 February 2020 |issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229001409/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51683428.html|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February, three further cases of the virus were confirmed bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 23, after 10,483 people had been tested.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The three cases were from [[Gloucestershire]], [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Berkshire]]. Two of the three affected people had recently returned from Italy while the third had come back from Asia.<ref name=\"BBC29Feb2020\">{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51684624 |title=Three more cases of coronavirus in England |date=29 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229024922/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51684624|archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Scottish CMO, [[Catherine Calderwood]] announced that surveillance would begin at some hospitals and 41 GP surgeries in Scotland.<ref name=BBC1Mar2020>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51690868 |title=Surveillance testing system for Covid-19 begins |date=1 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301034710/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51690868|archive-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> Around 442,675 calls were made to the [[NHS 111|non-emergency line 111]] in the last week of February.<ref name=Discombe5March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/acute-care/medical-students-and-new-doctors-could-be-drafted-in-to-fight-coronavirus/7027060.article |title=Medical students and new doctors could be drafted in to fight coronavirus |last=Discombe |first=Matt |website=Health Service Journal |access-date=6 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Early to Mid March 2020===\n[[File:Looking for soap, Sainsbury's, north London 12_March_2020.jpg|thumb|upright|Soap almost sold out, London, 12 March]]\n[[File:CoViD-19 GB.svg|thumb|left|upright=2|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]].]]\nOn 1 March, a further 13 cases were reported, adding [[Greater Manchester]] and Scotland to the list of areas affected and bringing the total to 36, three of which are believed to be contacts of the case in Surrey who had no history of travel abroad.<ref name=\"ITV1Mar2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/ |title=Twelve more people test positive for coronavirus bringing UK Covid-19 total to 35 |last= |first= |date=1 March 2020 |website=ITV News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301144252/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-01/twelve-more-people-test-positive-for-coronavirus-bringing-uk-covid-19-total-to-35/|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBCNews1March2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html |title=Coronavirus: Twelve more cases confirmed in England |last= |first= |date=1 March 2020 |website=bbc.co.uk/news|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160446/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51697991.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, four further people in England tested positive. All four had recently travelled from Italy; they are from Hertfordshire, Devon and Kent.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The total number of UK cases was reported as having reached 40, though this was revised to 39 after additional testing.<ref name=BBCNews2March2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550 |title=Coronavirus could spread 'significantly' \u2013 PM |date=2 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150239/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, when the total number of confirmed cases in the UK stood at 51, the UK Government unveiled their ''Coronavirus Action Plan'', which outlines what the UK has done already and what it plans to do next.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/>\n\nOn 4 March, the total number of confirmed cases increased to 85.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> Local press announced that an affected person was being treated at the [[Royal Stoke University Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/royal-stoke-university-hospital-coronavirus-3915717 |title=Coronavirus live updates: Royal Stoke treating patient with Coronavirus |last=Jackson |first=Matt |date=4 March 2020 |website=stokesentinel|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305174510/https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/royal-stoke-university-hospital-coronavirus-3915717|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, a case was confirmed in [[Gibraltar]] in a person who had travelled from [[Northern Italy]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> On 5 March, three further cases were announced by the CMO for Scotland [[Catherine Calderwood]], located in the areas of Forth Valley, [[Grampian Mountains|Grampian]] and [[Greater Glasgow]] and Clyde.<ref name=gov.scotCOVID-19/> That day, the total number of confirmed cases in the UK were reported by officials as 115,<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> and a woman in her 70s with an existing medical condition, was reported to be the first fatality within the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602 |title=Coronavirus: Woman in 70s becomes first virus fatality in UK' |date=5 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305174247/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51759602|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> A further 48 cases were confirmed on 6 March,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-47-new-cases-confirmed-taking-uk-total-to-163-11950718 |title=Coronavirus: 48 new cases confirmed in UK's biggest daily jump \u2013 taking total to 164 |website=Sky News|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307191328/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-47-new-cases-confirmed-taking-uk-total-to-163-11950718|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with the total being over 200 the next day,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-cases-number-206-locations-latest-a9384586.html |title=Coronavirus cases in UK rise to 206 today |date=7 March 2020 |website=The Independent|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308153244/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-cases-number-206-locations-latest-a9384586.html|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and adding a further 64 new cases on 8 March, the biggest increase in cases until that day.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-uk-latest-news-cases-update-covid-19-death-toll/ |title=Coronavirus latest news: UK case count rises by 64 as 273 test positive for the disease |first1=Verity |last1=Bowman |first2=Jordan |last2=Kelly-Linden |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=8 March 2020 |via=www.telegraph.co.uk|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308121935/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-uk-latest-news-cases-update-covid-19-death-toll/|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, three cases were discovered in [[Dorset]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/18291277.coronavirus-dorset-live-updates/ |title=Coronavirus live updates as three cases confirmed in Dorset |website=Bournemouth Echo |access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Rationing notice, Sainsbury's north London.jpg|thumb|Some supermarkets began to limit purchases of items in high demand. 12 March.]]\nOn 10 March, [[Evangelos Marinakis]], owner of football clubs [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] and [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]], announced on his Instagram feed that he had been infected with the virus.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Media |first=P. A. |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/10/nottingham-forest-and-olympiakos-owner-evangelos-marinakis-reveals-he-has-coronavirus |title=Nottingham Forest and Olympiakos owner reveals he has coronavirus |date=10 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=10 March 2020 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> It was announced the same day that mental health minister [[Nadine Dorries|Nadine Dorries MP]] had tested positive for the virus and was self isolating.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51827356 |title=Coronavirus: Health minister Nadine Dorries tests positive |date=10 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311153820/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51827356|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=HJ12March2020/><!-- This needs updating if/when a larger increase occurs.--> Nine more cases were also discovered in Wales bringing the total to 15.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Nine new cases in Wales brings total to 15 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51827012 |work=BBC News |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, 83 more cases were discovered in the UK bringing the total to 456. It was announced later that day that four new cases in Wales had been discovered, bringing the total to 19.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-11/four-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-wales-bringing-total-to-19/ |title=Four new coronavirus cases confirmed in Wales bringing the total to 19 |date=11 March 2020 |work=ITV News|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312133743/https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-11/four-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-wales-bringing-total-to-19/|archive-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the WHO declared the outbreak a [[pandemic]],<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\"/> and it was discussed in the [[Budget of the United Kingdom|UK government's annual budget]].<ref name=HJ12March2020/>\n\nOn 12 March, the first confirmed case was found in [[Sheffield]], [[South Yorkshire]], where previously a man was isolated, raising the number of cases in South Yorkshire to 12. Later that day 6 new cases were discovered in Wales, bringing the total to 25. Meanwhile, the total of cases in the UK was reported to be 590.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> On the same day, the UK CMOs raised the risk to the UK from moderate to high.<ref name=Gov.UK12March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/covid-19-government-announces-moving-out-of-contain-phase-and-into-delay |title=COVID-19: government announces moving out of contain phase and into delay |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316093859/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/covid-19-government-announces-moving-out-of-contain-phase-and-into-delay|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> The government advised that anyone with a new continuous cough or a fever should self-isolate for seven days. Schools were asked to cancel trips abroad, and people over 70 and those with pre-existing medical conditions were advised to avoid cruises.<ref name=BBCNews12March2020/><ref name=Mahase13March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Mahase |first=Elisabeth |date=13 March 2020 |title=Covid-19: UK holds off closing schools and restricts testing to people in hospital |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1060 |journal=British Medical Journal |language=en |volume=368 |pages=m1060 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m1060 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=32169967 |via=|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317052257/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m1060|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Shopping in rubber gloves and a face mask Sainsbury's north Finchley London 15 March 2020 coronavirus COVID 19 scare.jpg|thumb|upright|Shopping in rubber gloves and a face mask, London, 15 March 2020]]\n\nOn 13 March, the number of confirmed cases rose by 208 to 798 confirmed cases,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roberts |first=Lizzie |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-news-uk-cases-delay-phase-self-isolate-latest-live/ |title=Coronavirus latest news: UK cases rise to 798, as Foreign Office tells Britons not to travel to Spain unless it is essential |date=12 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph|access-date=13 March 2020 |last2=Davies |first2=Gareth |issn=0307-1235 |last3=Gartner |first3=Annelies |last4=Team |first4=Global Health Security|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313073312/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-news-uk-cases-delay-phase-self-isolate-latest-live/|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with the first death from Coronavirus being reported in Scotland.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899 |title=Coronavirus: Death of first Scottish patient with Covid-19 confirmed |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140926/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51874899|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many sporting fixtures including the [[London Marathon]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313171937/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] Wales vs Scotland fixture,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907 |title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313141835/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and all [[Premier League]] and [[English Football League|EFL]] football games<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended in England \u2013 Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland halt games |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313111939/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> were postponed and the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections]] were postponed for a year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=English local elections postponed over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313194513/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51876269|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, the [[C2C: Country to Country|Country to Country music festival]] due to take place between 13\u201315 March at London's [[O2 Arena London|O2 Arena]] was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Freeman |first=Jon |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/c2c-festival-postponed-coronavirus-966263/ |title=C2C Festival Postponed Over Coronavirus Pandemic |work=Rolling Stone |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321171800/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/c2c-festival-postponed-coronavirus-966263/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The UK Government restricted the export of three drugs being administered to COVID-19 patients in clinical trials in China: Kaletra, Chloroquine Phosphate, and Hydroxychloroquine <ref>{{cite web |first=Healthcare |last=GlobalData |url=https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/comment/parallel-export-covid-19/ |title=UK bans parallel export and hoarding of three Covid-19 drugs |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316203117/https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/comment/parallel-export-covid-19/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, the number of confirmed cases rose to 1,140 and the total number of people who had died in the UK had increased to 21.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51889957 |title=Coronavirus: UK deaths double in 24 hours |work=BBC News |date=14 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143746/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51889957|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]] announced that everyone in Britain over the age of 70 would be told to self-isolate \"within the coming weeks\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873 |title=Coronavirus: Isolation for over-70s 'within weeks' |date=15 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020 |work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315090139/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873|archive-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> That day, the number of cases rose to 1,372 and the number of deaths increased to 35.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-15/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-rises-to-35-as-14-more-patients-die-after-testing-positive-for-covid-19/ |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 35 and cases of Covid-19 hits 1,372 as elderly face four months of self-isolation |work=ITV News |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315164212/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-15/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-rises-to-35-as-14-more-patients-die-after-testing-positive-for-covid-19/ |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the UK death toll rose to 55, with the number of cases of the illness passing 1,500.<ref name=avoid>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |title=Coronavirus: PM says everyone should avoid office, pubs and travelling |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316182658/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The deaths included the first to be reported in Wales.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |title=Coronavirus in Wales: First Covid-19 death confirmed |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316140423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Also on 16 March, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] advised everyone in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions were urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and would be asked to self-isolate within days.<ref name=avoid/> On the same day, the second [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] was diagnosed with the virus. The new [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP for [[Jarrow (UK Parliament constituency)|Jarrow]], [[Kate Osborne]] tested positive after a period of self-isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-51906813 |title=Second MP diagnosed with coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=18 March 2020 |language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317213024/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-51906813|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/kate-osborne-coronavirus-labour-mp-second-nadine-dorries-a9403786.html |title=Labour MP is second to test positive for coronavirus |date=16 March 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013631/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/kate-osborne-coronavirus-labour-mp-second-nadine-dorries-a9403786.html|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-labour-mp-kate-osborne-reveals-she-is-infected-with-call-to-band-together-11958194 |title=Coronavirus: Labour MP Kate Osborne reveals she is infected with call to 'band together' |website=Sky News |language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013631/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-labour-mp-kate-osborne-reveals-she-is-infected-with-call-to-band-together-11958194|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/labours-kate-osborne-becomes-second-mp-to-test-positive-for-coronavirus |title=Labour's Kate Osborne becomes second MP to test positive for coronavirus |date=17 March 2020 |website=Politics Home |language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318013631/https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/labours-kate-osborne-becomes-second-mp-to-test-positive-for-coronavirus|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Elderly shopping hour at New Barnet Sainsbury's.jpg|thumb|Supermarkets introduced early shopping hours for the elderly and vulnerable]]\nOn 17 March, [[NHS England]] announced that all non-urgent operations in England would be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317152225/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Also on 17 March, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Rishi Sunak]] announced that \u00a3330bn would be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |title=Coronavirus: Chancellor unveils \u00a3330bn lifeline for economy |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317174307/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On that day the UK death toll rose to 71, while the number of confirmed cases increased to 1,950.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jane |last=Dalton |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 71 |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317203339/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/uk-coronavirus-cases-reach-1-950-up-407-in-24-hours-11958875 |title=Coronavirus: 14 more deaths in England \u2013 UK total now 71 |publisher=Sky UK |work=Sky News |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317173124/https://news.sky.com/story/uk-coronavirus-cases-reach-1-950-up-407-in-24-hours-11958875 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the government provided a \u00a33.2million emergency support package to help rough sleepers into accommodation.<ref name=homeless>{{cite news |last=Faleiro |first=Sonia |title=How do you self-isolate when you live on the street? |newspaper=politico.eu |location=United Kingdom |pages= |language=English |publisher=politico |date=22 March 2020 |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-homeless-self-isolation/| access-date = 26 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=homeless2>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-guidance-for-local-government |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): guidance for local government |last= |first= |date=17 March 2020 |website=gov.co.uk}}</ref> With complex physical and mental health needs, in general, [[Homelessness in the United Kingdom|homeless people]] are at a significant risk of catching the virus;<ref name=homeless/> as such it was argued that this fund was not satisfactory.<ref name=homeless/>\n\nOn 18 March, [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP for [[Brighton Kemptown (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Kemptown]] [[Lloyd Russell-Moyle]] announced that he had tested positive for with the virus, becoming the third MP to be diagnosed with the disease.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-51952997 |title=Coronavirus: MP Lloyd Russell-Moyle tests positive for Covid-19 |date=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318230404/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-51952997|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the first death was confirmed in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.itv.com/news/utv/2020-03-19/first-coronavirus-death-in-northern-ireland/ |title=First coronavirus death in Northern Ireland |work=ITV News |date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319201706/https://www.itv.com/news/utv/2020-03-19/first-coronavirus-death-in-northern-ireland/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Ministry of Defence also announced the formation of the COVID Support Force, enabling the military to support public services and civilian authorities in tackling the outbreak.<ref name=\"Rescript1\">{{cite news |title=Military stands up COVID Support Force |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/military-stands-up-covid-support-force |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=GOV.UK |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160303/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/military-stands-up-covid-support-force |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Two military operations were also announced; [[Operation Rescript]], which focuses on the outbreak in the United Kingdom, and Operation Broadshare, which focuses on British military activities overseas.<ref name=\"Rescript2\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Up to 20,000 troops on standby to help deal with COVID-19 outbreak |url= https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-up-to-20-000-troops-on-standby-to-help-deal-with-covid-19-outbreak-11959977 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=Sky News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319234118/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-up-to-20-000-troops-on-standby-to-help-deal-with-covid-19-outbreak-11959977 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, on that day COVID-19 was removed from the \"High consequence infectious disease\" list.<ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef />\n[[File:NEXT Enfield still trading during the Coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|Next closed its 700 stores on 23 March, having previously traded with warning notices about the virus]]\nConfirmed cases in Sheffield rose to 36 by 20 March, the highest for a UK city outside of [[London]] at that point.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.thestar.co.uk/health/coronavirus/sheffield-now-has-36-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-which-most-outside-london-and-south-2501810 |title=Sheffield now has 36 confirmed coronavirus cases, which is the most outside London and the south |last=Cumber |first=Robert |date=19 March 2020 |website=Sheffield Star |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200320160329/https://www.thestar.co.uk/health/coronavirus/sheffield-now-has-36-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-which-most-outside-london-and-south-2501810|archive-date=20 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the [[Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency]] announced that all pending practical and driving theory tests were to be postponed, for at least 3 months in the case of practical tests, and up to and including 20 April for theory tests. All candidates were to receive notification of when their tests were rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-driving-tests-and-theory-tests |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): driving tests and theory tests |website=GOV.UK |language=en|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200321011055/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-driving-tests-and-theory-tests|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.motoringresearch.com/car-news/driving-tests-cancelled-coronavirus/ |title=Driving tests CANCELLED due to coronavirus |last=Braithwaite-Smith |first=Gavin |date=20 March 2020 |website=Motoring Research |language=en-GB|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200321011100/https://www.motoringresearch.com/car-news/driving-tests-cancelled-coronavirus/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the UK death toll reached 281, including what was reported to be the virus's youngest British victim so far, an eighteen-year-old with underlying health problems.<ref name=\"tougher measures\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51998559 |title=Coronavirus: Follow virus advice or 'tougher measures' likely, says PM |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[Next (retailer)|Next]] was the latest retailer to announce that it was temporarily closing its 700 stores due to the pandemic. It predicted a \u00a31bn loss in revenue due to the virus.<ref>[https://www.marketingweek.com/morrisons-next-coronavirus-5-things-that-mattered-this-week-and-why/ Morrisons, Next, coronavirus: 5 things that mattered this week and why] ''www.marketingweek.com'' accessed 25 March 2020</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/19/next-facing-unprecedented-crisis-as-firms-warn-of-coronavirus-fallout |title=Next warns of unprecedented high street crisis over coronavirus |work=The Guardian |date=}}</ref> On the same day, [[Downing Street]] confirmed [[Foreign Secretary of the United Kingdom|Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] is the \"designated survivor\" to replace Prime Minister Boris Johnson if he becomes \"incapacitated\" due to COVID-19. The clarification came after the issue was raised by MP [[Peter Bone]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-boris-johnson-dominic-raab-prime-minister-a9418246.html |title=Dominic Raab to become acting PM if Boris Johnson incapacitated due to coronavirus |date=23 March 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Late March 2020 ===\nOn the evening of 23 March, Prime Minister Boris Johnson announced in a television broadcast that measures to mitigate the virus were to be tightened further in order to protect the NHS, with wide-ranging restrictions made on freedom of movement, enforceable in law,<ref name=lockdown-2020-03-23/> for a planned \"lockdown\" period intended to last for at least three weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-23/boris-johnson-downing-street-coronavirus-update/ |title=Boris Johnson orders three-week lockdown of UK to tackle coronavirus spread |website=ITV News |language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe government directed people to stay at home throughout this period except for essential purchases, essential work travel (if remote work is not possible), medical needs, one exercise per-day (alone or with members of their household), and providing care for others.<ref name=PM-address-in-full-2020-03-23>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/23/boris-johnsons-address-to-the-nation-in-full |title=Boris Johnson's address to the nation in full |date=23 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-23 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323204915/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/23/boris-johnsons-address-to-the-nation-in-full|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many other non-essential activities, including all public gatherings and social events except funerals, are prohibited, with many categories of retail businesses ordered to be closed.<ref name=lockdown-2020-03-23/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-businesses-and-premises-to-close |title=Further businesses and premises to close |website=GOV.UK |language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Parliament]] closed on 24 March, with plans to reconvene on 1 April to discuss emergency legislation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-52018354 |title=FMQs cancelled as Holyrood chamber shuts for a week |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] closed on the evening of 25 March.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52032188 |title=Parliament expected to close on Wednesday evening |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nAccording to official data released on 24 March, there had been 87 new coronavirus deaths in the previous 24 hours, bringing the total number of deaths to 422.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK coronavirus death toll jumps to 422 after biggest daily increase |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-24/coronavirus-deaths-uk/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=ITV News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, British diplomat [[Steven Dick]], deputy ambassador to Hungary, died in Budapest after contracting the virus.<ref name=\"Walker\">{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=British diplomat dies of coronavirus in Hungary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/25/british-diplomat-dies-of-coronavirus-in-hungary |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced the police would be given the power to use \"reasonable force\" to enforce the regulations.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Police |first=Vikram Dodd |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-lockdown-will-be-imposed-by-force-in-england |title=England: police to get power to use force to impose coronavirus lockdown |date=25 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26 |last2=correspondent |first2=crime |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Doctors Adil El Tayar ([[Consultant (medicine)|consultant]] [[surgeon]]; cousin of [[BBC News|BBC]] journalist and [[news presenter]] [[Zeinab Badawi]])<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52064450|title=Coronavirus: First working NHS surgeon dies in UK from Covid-19|first=Thomas|last=Macintosh|date=28 March 2020|website=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> and Habib Zaidi (GP)<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus: Essex GP with 'textbook symptoms' dies|URL=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-england-essex-52040991|date=27 March 2020|website=[[BBC News]]|first1=Nikki |last1=Fox| first2=Julian |last2=Sturdy}}</ref> became the first working NHS doctors to die from COVID-19.<ref name=\"Amged\">{{cite web|title=Coronavirus: Burton consultant Amged El-Hawrani dies|URL=https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/uk-england-derbyshire-52084915|date=29 March 2020|website=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, the number of UK coronavirus deaths jumped by more than 100 in a day for the first time, rising to 578, while a total of 11,568 had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52056534 |title=UK virus deaths rise by more than 100 in a day |work=BBC News |date=26 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At 8pm that evening, people from across the UK took part in a national applause in appreciation of health workers.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bowman |first=Verity |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/26/thank-nhs-tonights-clap-carers/ |title=Clap For Our Carers: How thousands of Britons thanked the NHS with a national round of applause |date=26 March 2020 |work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-03-26 |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Prime Minister Boris Johnson and Health Secretary Matt Hancock both announced that they had tested positive for the virus.<ref name=Boris>{{cite news |title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/27/health-secretary-matt-hancock-tests-positive-coronavirus-12466332/ |title=Coronavirus strikes heart of Government as PM and health secretary test positive |work=Metro |date=27 March 2020 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, Labour MP [[Angela Rayner]], the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]], confirmed she had been suffering symptoms and was self-isolating following medical advice.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-03-27/north-west-mp-angela-rayner-says-she-is-self-isolating/ |title=North West MP Angela Rayner says she is self-isolating |work=ITV News |date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Chief Medical Adviser Chris Whitty also reported suffering from symptoms and would be self-isolating, while continuing to advise the UK government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Chief medical officer Chris Whitty self-isolates with symptoms |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-chief-medical-officer-chris-whitty-self-isolates-with-symptoms-11964697 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Sky News |date=27 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> That day also saw the largest increase in the number of deaths, with the figure rising by 181 from the previous day, bringing the total to 759, while 14,579 cases had been confirmed by that point.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-cases-uk-how-many-covid-19-a9430221.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 759 |date=27 March 2020 |website=The Independent}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Royal Mint]] announced that it was manufacturing medical visors for medical staff working during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-royalmint-idUSKBN21E2XK |title=UK's Royal Mint making coronavirus protective gear for health staff |date=27 March 2020 |work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-27 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-27/royal-mint-makes-medical-visors-to-protect-nhs-staff-from-coronavirus/ |title=Royal Mint makes medical visors to help protect NHS staff from coronavirus |website=ITV News |language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The National Police Chiefs' Council said [[Law enforcement in the United Kingdom|police]] had issued their first fines for people breaking lockdown rules. The [[fixed penalty notice]]s are \u00a360 but will be reduced to \u00a330 if paid within 14 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-27/police-issue-fines-for-breach-of-coronavirus-lockdown-rules-as-visitors-warned-off-tourist-hotspots/ |title=Police issue first fines for breach of coronavirus lockdown rules as visitors warned off tourist hotspots |website=ITV News}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, the [[Scottish Secretary]] [[Alister Jack]] announced that he was self-isolating after experiencing coronavirus symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-scottish-secretary-alister-jack-self-isolating-after-showing-symptoms-11965001 |title=Coronavirus: Scottish Secretary Alister Jack self-isolating after showing symptoms |website=Sky News}}</ref> A further 260 deaths also took the number of fatalities past 1,000, with a total of 1,019 deaths having occurred so far, and 17,089 people having tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52077997 |title=Number of UK coronavirus deaths rises above 1,000 |work=BBC News |date=28 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At 11pm that evening, new regulations came into force in Northern Ireland giving authorities there the power to force businesses to close, and impose fines on them if they refused, as well as on people leaving their homes without a \"reasonable excuse\". The measures, introduced by the [[Northern Ireland Executive]], brought Northern Ireland into line with the rest of the UK<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52079959 |title=New NI Covid-19 regulations come into force |work=BBC News |date=28 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-28/new-regulations-to-enforce-coronavirus-restrictions-agreed-by-stormont/ |title=Northern Ireland imposes fines up to \u00a35,000 for those breaching social distancing rules |website=ITV News}}</ref> Dr Amged El-Hawrani ([[Otorhinolaryngology|ENT]] consultant) became the third NHS doctor to die that week from a COVID-19 infection.<ref name=\"Amged\"/>\n[[File:Social distancing queueing for the supermarket J. Sainsbury's north London Coronavirus Covid 19 pandemic - 30 March 2020.jpg|thumb|Social distancing while queueing to enter a British supermarket 30 March 2020]]\nOn 29 March it was reported that the government would send a letter to 30 million households warning that things would \"get worse before they get better\" and that tighter restrictions could be implemented if necessary. The letter would also be accompanied by a leaflet setting out the government's lockdown rules along with health information.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52079922 |title=Things to get worse, PM says in letter to Britons |work=BBC News |date=29 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> In a subsequent appearance on that day's edition of the BBC's Sunday morning politics programme ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]'', [[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Cabinet Office Minister]] [[Michael Gove]] said that the UK was facing a \"significant period\" of strict measures to deal with the outbreak, and that it was \"vitally important\" to follow social distancing rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52082781|title=Strict measures could last 'significant period'|date=29 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Speaking at the government's daily briefing later that day, Dr [[Jenny Harries]], England's deputy chief medical officer, suggested it could be six months before life could return to \"normal\", because social distancing measures would have to be reduced \"gradually\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52084517|title=Six months before UK life 'returns to normal'|date=29 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, [[Dominic Cummings]], the [[10 Downing Street|Prime Minister's Chief Adviser]], was reported to be self-isolating after experiencing coronavirus symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rajeev Syal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/30/dominic-cummings-self-isolates-after-experiencing-coronavirus-symptoms |title=Dominic Cummings self-isolates after experiencing coronavirus symptoms &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> As the number of reported deaths rose to 1,408, Sir [[Patrick Vallance]], the UK's chief scientific adviser told the government's daily briefing that there were early signs social distancing measures were \"making a difference\". Transmission of the virus within the community was thought to be decreasing, and hospital admission data suggested cases were not rising as fast as anticipated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-52096049|title=Coronavirus: UK measures 'making a difference'|first=Michelle|last=Roberts|date=30 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> At the same briefing, [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] announced an arrangement between the government and major UK airlines to fly home tens of thousands of British nationals who had been stranded abroad by the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52099252|title=Rescue flights for stranded Britons|date=30 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March it was announced that Harold Pearsall, a 97-year-old [[Normandy landings|D-Day]] [[veteran]] from [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], [[Staffordshire]] had died at the [[Good Hope Hospital]] in [[Birmingham]] after contracting the coronavirus. Pearsall received the [[L\u00e9gion d\u2019Honneur|L\u00e9gion d'Honneur]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-52102451|title=D-Day veteran dies after contracting coronavirus|date=2020-03-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-31 }}</ref> London's [[King's College Hospital]] confirmed that a 13-year-old boy who tested positive for coronavirus had died. On the same day the largest UK death toll of the outbreak was reported, with 381 deaths taking the total to 1,789.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52114476</ref> [[Matthew Gould]], chief executive of [[NHSX]], the government body responsible for policy regarding technology in the NHS, said the organisation was looking seriously at a coronavirus [[Mobile app|app]] that would alert people if they had recently been in contact with someone testing positive for the virus after scientists advising the government suggested it \"could play a critical role\" in limiting lockdowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52095331|title=UK considers virus-tracing app to ease lockdown|first=Leo|last=Kelion|date=31 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn late March, it was announced that the NHS would be establishing a network of [[NHS Nightingale Hospitals]], temporary emergency hospitals set up in major conference centres to help to deal with the large number of cases expected. The first of these hospitals, [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]] in London's [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Centre]], is due to be opened in early April.<ref name=\"ITV-2020-03-27\">{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-27/birmingham-nec-and-manchester-central-convention-complex-to-be-converted-into-coronavirus-hospitals |title=Two more UK facilities to be converted into 'NHS Nightingale' coronavirus hospitals |last= |first= |date=27 March 2020 |website=ITV News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Testing and surveillance==\n[[File:Doctor's surgery entrance north London.jpg|thumb|upright|Warning notices at a London doctor's surgery, 13 March 2020]]\nShortly after confirming that the cause of the cluster of pneumonia in Wuhan was a new coronavirus, Chinese authorities had shared its genetic sequence for international developments of diagnostic kits.<ref name=\"Mahase22Jan2020\"/> The UK subsequently developed a prototype specific laboratory test for the new disease, performed on a sample from the nose, throat, and respiratory tract and tested at PHE's Colindale laboratories in London.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/> By 3 February 326 tests had been performed in the UK.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Over the following few weeks, PHE made the test available to 12 other laboratories in the UK, making it possible to test 1,000 people a day.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020/>\n\nFollowing 300 staff being asked to work from home on 26 February 2020 in London, while a suspected person was awaiting a test result for the virus, PHE announced it was to increase surveillance by widening testing around the UK to include people with flu-like symptoms at 100 GP surgeries and eight hospitals: the [[Royal Brompton and Harefield NHS Foundation Trust|Royal Brompton and Harefield]], [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust|Guy's and St Thomas']] and [[Addenbrookes Hospital]], as well as hospitals at [[Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust|Brighton and Sussex]], [[Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust|Nottingham]], [[University Hospital of South Manchester NHS Foundation Trust|South Manchester]], [[Sheffield Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust|Sheffield]], [[University Hospitals of Leicester NHS Trust|Leicester]].<ref name=BBC26Feb2020>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51641243 |title=Hundreds of flu patients to get coronavirus tests |date=26 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227000207/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51641243|archive-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=PHE27Feb2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-surveillance-system-for-early-detection-of-covid-19 |title=New surveillance system for early detection of COVID-19 |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227080745/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-surveillance-system-for-early-detection-of-covid-19|archive-date=27 February 2020|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref> Surveillance was shortly extended to some hospitals and GP surgeries in Scotland.<ref name=BBC1Mar2020/>\n\nDrive-through screening centres were set up by Central London Community Healthcare NHS Trust at Parsons Green Health Centre on 24 February 2020,<ref name=\"clch29Feb2020\">{{cite web |url=https://clch.nhs.uk/about-us/news/parsons-green-drive-through-swabbing-hub-covid-19 |title=Central London Community Healthcare NHS Trust :: Parsons Green drive through swabbing hub for Covid-19 |website=clch.nhs.uk|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229015242/https://clch.nhs.uk/about-us/news/parsons-green-drive-through-swabbing-hub-covid-19|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and by NHS Lothian at the [[Western General Hospital]] in [[Edinburgh]].<ref name=\"BBCSct29Feb2020\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51678008 |title=Drive-through coronavirus tests begin in Scotland |date=28 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229033108/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-51678008|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further drive-through testing station was set up by the [[Sheffield Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]] at a site just off the [[A57 road|A57]] [[Sheffield Parkway]] dual-carriageway on 10 March; in this case, patients ringing NHS 111 with coronavirus-like symptoms in the [[Sheffield]] area will be told to drive, if possible, to the testing centre at an allotted time.<ref>[https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-03-10/drive-through-centre-set-up-to-test-for-coronavirus-in-sheffield/ Drive through centre set up to test for coronavirus in Sheffield] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320200915/https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2020-03-10/drive-through-centre-set-up-to-test-for-coronavirus-in-sheffield/ |date=20 March 2020 }} 10 March 2020 ''www.itv.com'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 11 March [[NHS England]] announced that testing in NHS laboratories would increase from testing 1,500 to 10,000 per day.<ref name=HJ12March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/daily-insight/daily-insight-budget-day-maths/7027096.article |title=Daily Insight: Budget day maths |last= |first= |date= |website=Health Service Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316055806/https://www.hsj.co.uk/daily-insight/daily-insight-budget-day-maths/7027096.article|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The test consists of taking a sample from the nose, throat, deeper lung samples, blood or stool, and transporting the packed samples to the listed PHE regional laboratory designated for the referring laboratory region.<ref name=Gov.ukTesting>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-guidance-for-clinical-diagnostic-laboratories/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-who-to-call-to-request-laboratory-testing |title=COVID-19: how to arrange laboratory testing |website=GOV.UK|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319215201/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-guidance-for-clinical-diagnostic-laboratories/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-who-to-call-to-request-laboratory-testing|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=nhs.ukTesting>{{cite web |url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/common-questions/ |title=Common questions about coronavirus (COVID-19) |date=24 February 2020 |website=nhs.uk|access-date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301190454/https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/common-questions/|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 12/13 March 2020, 29,764 tests had been conducted in the UK, corresponding to 450.8 tests per million people.<ref>[https://ourworldindata.org/covid-testing Esteban Ortiz-Ospina: How many tests for COVID-19 are being performed around the world?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314010612/https://ourworldindata.org/covid-testing |date=14 March 2020 }} 13 March 2020 ''ourworldindata.org'', accessed 14 March 2020</ref> As of 31 March, 143,186 people have been tested,<ref>https://www.gov.uk/guidance/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-the-public#number-of-cases</ref> which means since 11 March some 5,000 people per day were tested.\n\n==Forecasting==\n[[File:Social distancing at the pharmacy Cockfosters London 23_March_2020.jpg|thumb|[[Social distancing]] at a London pharmacy, 23 March 2020]]\nReports from the [[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)|Medical Research Council's]] Centre for Global Infectious Disease Analysis at [[Imperial College]], London have been providing mathematically calculated estimates of cases and case fatality rates.<ref name=Mahase10Feb2020>{{Cite journal |last=Mahase |first=Elisabeth |date=10 February 2020 |title=Coronavirus: NHS staff get power to keep patients in isolation as UK declares \"serious threat\" |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550 |journal=[[British Medical Journal]] |volume=368 |pages=m550 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m550 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=32041792|url-access=subscription|access-date=2 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191051/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Imperial2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/mrc-global-infectious-disease-analysis/news--wuhan-coronavirus/ |title=COVID-19 reports {{!}} Faculty of Medicine {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=www.imperial.ac.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125095230/http://www.imperial.ac.uk/mrc-global-infectious-disease-analysis/news--wuhan-coronavirus/|archive-date=25 January 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> In February, the team at Imperial, led by epidemiologist [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Neil Ferguson]], reported about two-thirds of cases in travellers from China were not detected and that some of these may have begun \"chains of transmission within the countries they entered.\"<ref name=Imperial24Feb20>{{cite web |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/195564/two-thirds-covid-19-cases-exported-from-mainland/ |title=Two thirds of COVID-19 cases exported from mainland China may be undetected {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial News |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306033332/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/195564/two-thirds-covid-19-cases-exported-from-mainland/|archive-date=6 March 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=NewSci>{{cite web |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2234967-covid-19-our-chance-to-contain-the-coronavirus-may-already-be-over/  |title=Covid-19: Our chance to contain the coronavirus may already be over |last=MacKenzie |first=Debora |date= |website=New Scientist |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200226201356/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2234967-covid-19-our-chance-to-contain-the-coronavirus-may-already-be-over/ |archive-date=26 February 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=JapanTimes26Feb20>{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/02/26/world/science-health-world/covid-19-global-monitoring/ |title=COVID-19 strains global monitoring systems to the extreme |date=26 February 2020 |work=The Japan Times|access-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live |issn=0447-5763}}</ref> This translates to only one in three cases coming into the UK being detected.<ref name=BBCNews12Feb2020>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51470342 |title=More coronavirus cases 'highly likely' in UK |date=12 February 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204121/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51470342 |archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They forecast that the new coronavirus could infect up to 60% of the UK's population, in the worst-case scenario.<ref name=\"Petter2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-valentines-day-hugging-kissing-symptoms-outbreak-a9332976.html |title=Prevent spread of coronavirus on with 'less hugging and kissing', says virologist |last=Petter |first=Olivia |date=13 February 2020 |website=[[The Independent]] |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200214165034/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-valentines-day-hugging-kissing-symptoms-outbreak-a9332976.html |archive-date=14 February 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a paper released but not yet published on 16 March, the Imperial team provided detailed forecasts of the potential impacts of the epidemic in the UK and US.<ref name=\"Imperial16March2020\" /><ref name=\"Independent200317\">{{cite news |last1=Lintern |first1=Shaun |title=World holds its breath and looks to China for clues on what coronavirus pandemic does next |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-china-imperial-college-scientists-modelling-a9405771.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |publisher=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140137/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-china-imperial-college-scientists-modelling-a9405771.html |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Their paper details the potential outcomes of an array of 'non-pharmaceutical interventions' such as contact tracing and case isolation, home self quarantine, closure of bars, social venues or schools, and social distancing. Two potential overall strategies outlined were: mitigation, in which the aim is to reduce the health impact of the epidemic but not to stop transmission completely; and suppression, where the aim is to reduce transmission rates to a point where case numbers fall. Until this point government actions had been based on a strategy of mitigation, but the modelling predicted that while this would reduce deaths by approximately 2/3, it would still lead to approximately 250,000 deaths from the disease and the health systems becoming overwhelmed.<ref name=\"Imperial16March2020\" /> On the same day as the report was released, the Prime Minister announced in a press conference significant changes to the government advice, extending self isolation to whole households, advising social distancing particularly for vulnerable groups, and indicating that further measures were likely to be required in the future.<ref name=avoid/><ref name=\"Independent200317\" /> A March 30 paper by Imperial estimates that the lockdown will reduced the number of dead from 510,000 to less than 20,000.<ref>[https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-Europe-estimates-and-NPI-impact-30-03-2020.pdf COVID19 Europe estimates and NPI impact] Neil Ferguson, Imperial College London</ref>\n\n==Response by sector==\n=== Government ===\n[[File:British Government NHS coronavirus public info poster.pdf|thumb|upright|English NHS coronavirus poster, February 2020<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.england.nhs.uk/london/2020/02/03/coronavirus-public-information-campaign-launched-across-the-uk/ |title=Coronavirus public information campaign launched across the UK |work=NHS England |date=3 February 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>]]\nGuidance has altered in line with the number of cases detected and changes in where affected people have contracted the virus, as well as with what has been happening in other countries.<ref name=\"Bosley26Feb2020\"/> In February, [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Adviser]] to the UK Government, [[Chris Whitty]] explained \"we basically have a strategy which depends upon four tactical aims: the first one is to contain; the second of these is to delay; the third of these is to do the science and the research; and the fourth is to mitigate so we can brace the NHS.\"<ref name=Kobie>{{Cite news |last=Kobie |first=Nicole |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-response |title=This is how the UK is strengthening its coronavirus defences |date=15 February 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302194615/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-response|archive-date=2 March 2020}}</ref> These aims equate to four phases; specific actions involved in each of these phases are:\n*Contain: detect early cases, follow up close contacts, and prevent the disease taking hold in this country for as long as is reasonably possible\n*Delay: slow the spread within the UK, and (if it does take hold) lower the peak impact and push it away from the winter season\n*Research: better understand the virus and the actions that will lessen its effect on the UK population; innovate responses including diagnostics, drugs and vaccines; use the evidence to inform the development of the most effective models of care\n*Mitigate: provide the best care possible for people who become ill, support hospitals to maintain essential services and ensure ongoing support for people ill in the community, to minimise the overall impact of the disease on society, public services and on the economy.<ref name=Plan2020>Department of Health and Social Care, Emergency and Health Protection Directorate, [https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/869827/Coronavirus_action_plan_-_a_guide_to_what_you_can_expect_across_the_UK.pdf Coronavirus: action plan: A guide to what you can expect across the UK] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304131952/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/869827/Coronavirus_action_plan_-_a_guide_to_what_you_can_expect_across_the_UK.pdf |date=4 March 2020 }}, published 3 March, accessed 7 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe four UK CMOs raised the UK risk level from low to moderate on 30 January 2020, upon the [[World Health Organization]]'s announcement of the disease as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]].<ref name=gov.uk2Update/><ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> As soon as cases appeared in the UK on 31 January 2020, a public health information campaign, similar to the previous \"[[Catch it, Bin it, Kill it]]\" campaign, was launched in the UK, to advise people how to lessen the risk of spreading the virus.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Travellers from Hubei province in China, including the capital Wuhan were advised to self-isolate, \"stay at home, not go to work, school or public places, not use public transport or taxis, ask friends, family members or delivery services to do errands\",<ref name=NHS.ukCOVID>{{cite web |url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/ |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) |last= |first= |date=24 January 2020 |website=nhs.uk |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302222456/https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=2 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> and call [[NHS 111]] if they had arrived in the UK in previous 14 days, regardless of whether they were unwell or not.<ref name=Russell13Feb2020/> Further cases in early February prompted the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], to announce the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]].<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> Daily updates have been published by the DHSC.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> [[NHS Digital]] in the meanwhile, have been collecting data.<ref name=RapsonHSJ>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/patient-safety/nhs-collecting-coronavirus-data-from-111-calls/7026999.article |title=NHS collecting coronavirus data from 111 calls |last=Rapson |first=Jasmine |date= |website=Health Service Journal |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n[[File:Catch it, Bin it, Kill it poster.jpg|thumb|upright|Poster for the \"Catch it, Bin it, Kill it\" slogan which has been revived in the fight against coronavirus]]\nOn 25 February 2020, the UK's CMOs advice for all travellers (unwell or not) who had returned to the UK from Hubei province in the previous 14 days, Iran, specific areas designated by the Italian government as quarantine areas in northern Italy and special care zones in South Korea since 19 February, to self-isolate and call NHS 111.<ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\"/> This advice was also advocated for any person who has flu-like symptoms with a history of travelling from Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar and areas in Italy north of Pisa, Florence and Rimini, returning to the UK since 19 February. Later, self-isolation was recommended for anyone returning from any part of Italy from 9 March.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/><ref name=\"gov.uk15Feb2020\"/>\n\nInitially Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] largely kept Britain open, resisting the kind of lockdowns seen elsewhere in Europe. On Friday 13 March, UK chief scientific adviser [[Sir Patrick Vallance]] told [[BBC Radio 4]] that one of \"the key things we need to do\" is to \"build up some kind of [[herd immunity]] so more people are immune to this disease and we reduce the transmission\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Booth |first1=William |title=U.K. resists coronavirus lockdowns, goes its own way on response |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/uk-coronavirus-herd-immunity/2020/03/16/1c9d640e-66c7-11ea-b199-3a9799c54512_story.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Washington Post |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> This involves enough people getting infected, upon which they develop [[Immunity (medical)|immunity]] to the disease.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-uk-cases-herd-immunity-covid-19/ |title=The U.K. is aiming for deliberate 'herd immunity' |website=Fortune|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314082329/https://fortune.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-uk-cases-herd-immunity-covid-19/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-herd-immunity-uk-nhs-outbreak-pandemic-government-a9399101.html |title=60% of UK population need to get coronavirus so country can build 'herd immunity', chief scientist says |date=13 March 2020 |website=The Independent|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313191522/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-herd-immunity-uk-nhs-outbreak-pandemic-government-a9399101.html|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Vallance said that 60% of the UK's population will need to become infected for herd immunity to be achieved.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mueller |first=Benjamin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/world/europe/coronavirus-britain-boris-johnson.html |title=As Europe Shuts Down, Britain Takes a Different, and Contentious, Approach |date=13 March 2020 |work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2020 |issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313232126/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/13/world/europe/coronavirus-britain-boris-johnson.html|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> This stance was criticised by experts who said that it would lead to hundreds of thousands deaths and overwhelm the NHS. Over 200 scientists urged the government to rethink the approach in an open letter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boyle |first1=Christina |title=On coronavirus containment, Britain's Johnson is less restrictive than other European leaders |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-19/british-prime-minister-boris-johnsons-coronavirus-european-leaders |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, Health Secretary Matt Hancock denied that herd immunity was a plan for the UK, although the [[Department for Health and Social Care]] said that \"herd immunity is a natural byproduct of an [[epidemic]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=What is herd immunity and is it an option for dealing with the UK coronavirus pandemic? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/coronavirus-herd-immunity-meaning-definition-what-vaccine-immune-covid-19-a9397871.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> There was also criticism over a lack of transparency around the scientific evidence being used to inform the government response, with a letter published in [[the Lancet]] on 17 March calling on the government to openly share its data and models as a matter of urgency.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alwan|first=Nisreen A|last2=Bhopal|first2=Raj|last3=Burgess|first3=Rochelle A|last4=Colburn|first4=Tim|last5=Cuevas|first5=Luis E|last6=Smith|first6=George Davey|last7=Egger|first7=Matthias|last8=Eldridge|first8=Sandra|last9=Gallo|first9=Valentina|last10=Gilthorpe|first10=Mark S|last11=Greenhalgh|first11=Trish|date=17 March 2020|title=Evidence informing the UK's COVID-19 public health response must be transparent|url=https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30667-X|journal=The Lancet|volume=395|issue=10229|pages=1036\u20131037|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(20)30667-x|issn=0140-6736|via=}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, Boris Johnson said in an interview with [[BBC News]]: \"The most important thing now is that we prepare against a possible very significant expansion of coronavirus in the UK population\". This came after the 39th case in the UK was confirmed and over a month after the first confirmed case in the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550 |title=Coronavirus could spread 'significantly' \u2013 PM |date=2 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302195801/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51708550|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, a [[BBC One]] programme ''Coronavirus: Everything You Need to Know'' addressed questions from the public on the outbreak.<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |title=BBC News Special \u2013 Coronavirus: Everything You Need to Know |date=2 March 2020 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000g80s/bbc-news-special-coronavirus-everything-you-need-to-know|access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303115141/https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000g80s/bbc-news-special-coronavirus-everything-you-need-to-know|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, the Coronavirus Action Plan was unveiled.<ref name=gov.uk2Update/> The next day, as the total number of cases in the UK stood at 51, the government declared the coronavirus pandemic as a \"level 4 incident\",<ref name=Discombe3March2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/quality-and-performance/national-incident-over-coronavirus-allows-nhse-to-command-local-resources/7027045.article |title=National incident over coronavirus allows NHSE to command local resources |last=Discombe |first=Matt |date=3 March 2020 |website=[[Health Service Journal]] |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> permitting [[NHS England]] to take command of all NHS resources.<ref name=Discombe3March2020/><ref name=Sr2020>{{Cite book |last=Warnick |first=Mark S. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gaTDDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA90&dq=nhs+Level+4+incident#v=onepage&q=nhs%20Level%204%20incident&f=false |title=Emergency Incident Management Systems: Fundamentals and Applications |last2=Sr |first2=Louis N. Molino |date=2020 |publisher=Wiley |isbn=978-1-119-26711-9 |edition=Second |location= |pages=89\u201390}}</ref> Planning has been made for [[behaviour change (public health)|behaviour changing]] publicity including good hygiene and respiratory hygiene (\"catch it, bin it, kill it\"),<ref name=Campbell3Mar2020>{{Cite news |last=Campbell |first=Denis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/explained-uk-coronavirus-action-plan |title=Explained: UK's coronavirus action plan |date=3 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live |last2=Siddique |first2=Haroon |issn=0261-3077 |last3=Weaver |first3=Matthew|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304035015/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/03/explained-uk-coronavirus-action-plan|archive-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> a simple measure which helps in delaying the peak of the infection and buys time for the testing of drugs and initial development of vaccines.<ref name=Plan2020 /> Primary care has been issued guidance.<ref name=Razai6March2020>{{Cite journal |last=Razai |first=Mohammad S. |last2=Doerholt |first2=Katja |last3=Ladhani |first3=Shamez |last4=Oakeshott |first4=Pippa |date=6 March 2020 |title=Coronavirus disease 2019 (covid-19): a guide for UK GPs |url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m800 |journal=BMJ |volume=368 |pages=m800 |doi=10.1136/bmj.m800 |issn=1756-1833 |pmid=32144127|access-date=10 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309150416/https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m800|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Public Health England]] has also been involved with efforts to support the [[British Overseas Territories]] against the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/06/public-health-england-joins-cayman-in-coronavirus-response-efforts/ |title=Public Health England joins Cayman in coronavirus response efforts |first=Reshma |last=Ragoonath |date=7 March 2020 |website=Cayman Compass|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307160127/https://www.caymancompass.com/2020/03/06/public-health-england-joins-cayman-in-coronavirus-response-efforts/|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gibraltar.gov.gi/press-releases/government-statement-on-covid-19-1412020-5647 |title=Government Statement on COVID-19 \u2013 141/2020 |website=Government of Gibraltar|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309191352/https://www.gibraltar.gov.gi/press-releases/government-statement-on-covid-19-1412020-5647|archive-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Prime Minister Boris Johnson revealed he had contracted coronavirus and self-isolated, however he stated he would continue to lead the Government's response to coronavirus through [[Videotelephony|video conference]].<ref name=Boris />\n\n==== Regulations and legislation ====\nThe government published the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]]<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/129/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303041542/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/129/contents/made |date=3 March 2020 }} Legislation.gov.uk</ref> on 10 February 2020, a [[statutory instrument (UK)|statutory instrument]] covering the legal framework behind the government's initial containment and isolation strategies and its organisation of the national reaction to the virus. Other published regulations include changes to [[Statutory sick pay|Statutory Sick Pay]] (into force on 13 March),<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/287/contents/made The Statutory Sick Pay (General) (Coronavirus Amendment) Regulations 2020] Leglisation.gov.uk</ref> and changes to [[Employment and Support Allowance]] and [[Universal Credit]] (also 13 March).<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/289/contents/made The Employment and Support Allowance and Universal Credit (Coronavirus Disease) Regulations 2020] Leglisation.gov.uk</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the government introduced the [[Coronavirus Act 2020]], which grants the government discretionary [[emergency powers]] in the areas of the NHS, social care, schools, police, the Border Force, local councils, funerals and courts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-emergency-laws-will-give-powers-to-close-airports-and-detain-and-quarantine-people-11959342 |last=Heffer |first=Greg |title=Coronavirus Bill: Emergency laws to contain spread of COVID-19 published |website=[[Sky News]] |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318201123/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-emergency-laws-will-give-powers-to-close-airports-and-detain-and-quarantine-people-11959342|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The act received [[royal assent]] on 25 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/18318799.jacob-rees-mogg-says-parliament-will-return-easter-recess/ |last=Carmichael |first=Hannah |title=Jacob Rees-Mogg says Parliament will return after Easter recess |newspaper=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319155145/https://www.thenational.scot/news/18318799.jacob-rees-mogg-says-parliament-will-return-easter-recess/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nClosures to pubs, restaurants and indoor sports and leisure facilities were imposed via the Health Protection (Coronavirus, Business Closure) (England) Regulations 2020.<ref>[https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/327/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Business Closure) (England) Regulations 2020 UK Statutory Instruments 2020 No. 327 Table of contents] ''www.legislation.gov.uk'', accessed 26 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe restrictions on movements, except for allowed purposes, in England were imposed via the [[Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020]].<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/350/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020 UK Statutory Instruments 2020 No. 350 Table of contents] ''www.legislation.gov.uk'', accessed 26 March 2020</ref> In Scotland the  '''Health Protection (Coronavirus) (Restrictions) (Scotland) Regulations 2020'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ssi/2020/103/contents/made/data.htm|title=The Health Protection (Coronavirus) (Restrictions) (Scotland) Regulations 2020|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref> apply, and in Wales the '''Health Protection (Coronavirus Restrictions) (Wales) Regulations 2020'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/wsi/2020/353/contents/made/data.htm|title=The Health Protection (Coronavirus Restrictions) (Wales) Regulations 2020|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref> apply\n\n====Communications====\n[[File:GOV.UK COVID-19 text.png|thumb|alt=GOV.UK CORONAVIRUS ALERT. New rules in force now: you must stay at home. More info and exemptions at gov.uk/coronavirus Stay at home. Protect the NHS. Save lives. |UK Government advisory SMS message, 24 March 2020]]\n\nThe government held daily evening [[press conference]]s starting on 17 March and broadcast on [[BBC One]]. These were mostly hosted by Boris Johnson with cabinet ministers (often Matt Hancock) and senior scientific advisors.<ref>Manchester Evening News [https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/uk-news/live-matt-hancock-coronavirus-press-17972794 RECAP: Matt Hancock holds daily press conference on UK's coronavirus response] ''www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk'', accessed 25 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, all major [[mobile telephony]] providers, acting upon a government request, sent out an [[SMS message]] to each of their customers, with advice on staying isolated.<ref name=\"BBC-52017451\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Mobile networks send 'stay at home' text |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52017451 |first1=Rory |last1=Cellan-Jones |website=BBC News |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref> This was the first ever use of the facility.<ref name=\"BBC-52017451\" /> Although the government in 2013 endorsed the use of [[Cell Broadcast]] to send official [[Emergency population warning|emergency messages]] to all mobile phones, and has tested such a system, it has never actually been implemented. Backer [[Toby Harris]] said that the government had not yet agreed upon who would fund and govern such a system.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Jim |last=Waterson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/government-ignored-advice-set-up-uk-emergency-alert-system |title=Government ignored advice to set up UK emergency alert system |date=23 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Sweney |first=Mark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/24/uk-mobile-firms-asked-to-alert-britons-to-heed-coronavirus-lockdown |title=UK mobile firms asked to alert Britons to heed coronavirus lockdown |date=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===National Health Service===\n[[File:Coronavirus Pod at Hull Royal Infirmary (geograph 6406192).jpg|thumb|A Coronavirus 'pod' at [[Hull Royal Infirmary]].]]\nIn March, hospitals begin to prepare for the cancellation of all non-urgent elective procedures.<ref name=\"Ilman12March2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/free-for-non-subscribers/exclusive-nhs-prepares-to-cancel-elective-ops-in-readiness-for-covid-19-surge/7027110.article |title=Exclusive: NHS prepares to cancel elective ops in readiness for covid-19 surge |last=Illman |first=James |date=12 March 2020 |website=Health Service Journal |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16 Boris Johnson met with business leaders via conference call and set them the target of delivering 30,000 [[ventilator]]s in a fortnight; the government also declined to join an emergency [[European Union]] scheme to procure ventilators and other emergency equipment like [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for hospital staff, stating that the UK was no longer part of the EU that this was area in which it was making its own efforts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elliott |first1=Francis |last2=O'Neill |first2=Sean |last3=Waterfield |first3=Bruno |last4=Courea |first4=Eleni |title=Ventilator crunch looms after snubbing EU action |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ventilator-crunch-looms-after-snubbing-eu-action-6s7tg3vnw |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=27 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327042903/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ventilator-crunch-looms-after-snubbing-eu-action-6s7tg3vnw |archivedate=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 March, it was announced that the NHS had negotiated a deal to use, at cost price, almost the entire private health system, bringing 8,000 beds, 20,000 medical staff and 1,100 ventilators into the project.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989183 |title=NHS deal will provide thousands of extra beds |work=BBC News |date=21 March 2020|access-date = 23 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200323072035/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989183|archive-date = 23 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> Existing ventilator stocks stood at 5,900 at the beginning of the outbreak, and the government had also acquired stocks from the armed forces and suppliers, buying all they can supply.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} On March 23, in an effort to meet demand and due to concerns about the rising number of medics becoming ill after exposure to the virus, the NHS asked [[Hardware store|DIY]] stores to donate PPE for use by NHS staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnelly |first1=Laura |last2=Gardner |first2=Bill |title=NHS asks DIY stores to donate protective equipment to staff on the coronavirus frontline |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/23/nhs-asks-diy-stores-donate-protective-equipment-staff-coronavirus/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=23 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331102758/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/23/nhs-asks-diy-stores-donate-protective-equipment-staff-coronavirus/ |archivedate=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government said there was enough PPE for everyone in the NHS who needed it, which was contradicted by the [[Royal College of Nursing]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Drakeford claims enough protective kit for NHS despite concerns |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52018653 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326112144/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52018653 |archivedate=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[British Medical Association]] (BMA), which said some of the PPE doctors had received were inadequate<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Minister admits PPE 'challenges and problems' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52079429 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329232522/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52079429 |archivedate=29 March 2020}}</ref> and medics were resorting to wearing DIY PPE they had purchased themselves.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Continuing issues with protective kit for NHS, says minister |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52035545 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=25 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327191643/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52035545 |archivedate=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The BMA warned that without enough PPE doctors would die.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gibbons |first1=Katie |last2=Bennett |first2=Rosemary |title=Doctors forced to buy safety gear from DIY stores |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/doctors-forced-to-buy-safety-gear-from-diy-stores-hjg9fbsgl |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |date=26 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330050416/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/doctors-forced-to-buy-safety-gear-from-diy-stores-hjg9fbsgl |archivedate=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC05602 (49675594083).jpg|thumb|People in London wear masks on 19 March 2020|alt=]]\nOn 22 March, the government announced that it would be asking about 1.5 million people (everyone in the country with certain health conditions that carry serious risk if infected) to self-isolate for 12 weeks. They were to be notified by mail or text messaged by their NHS general practitioners, and provided deliveries of [[medication]], food, and household essentials, delivered by pharmacists and local governments, and at least initially paid for by the national government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/who-million-vulnerable-self-isolate-weeks-a4394311.html |title=Who are the 1.5m vulnerable people self-isolating for 12 weeks? |date=23 March 2020 |website=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the 2.5 million masks already bought and distributed the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, Matt Hancock, said that another 1 million masks had been bought.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 24 March 2020, NHS England announced plans to open a 2-ward, 4,000-bed temporary hospital in the [[Excel London]], to be named [[NHS Nightingale Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Denis |last2=Dodd |first2=Vikram |title=NHS plans to turn ExCeL centre into coronavirus hospital |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/nhs-plans-to-turn-excel-centre-into-coronavirus-hospital?CMP=share_btn_tw |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Goodall |first1=Lewis |title=NEW: Matt Hancock announces a new temporary hospital - the ExCel centre in London is being converted into the \"Nightingale Hospital\" |url=https://twitter.com/lewis_goodall/status/1242492246605389825 |website=@lewis_goodall |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Matt Hancock announced the start of a scheme to recruit 250,000 [[volunteer]]s to support the NHS through the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 250,000 people urged to become volunteers to help NHS and fight Covid-19 |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-24/government-launches-campaign-recruit-250000-nhs-volunteers-matt-hancock/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=24 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329030238/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-24/government-launches-campaign-recruit-250000-nhs-volunteers-matt-hancock/ |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The volunteers would carry out jobs like collecting and deliver shopping, medication or \"other essential supplies\" for people in isolation; transporting equipment and medication between NHS services; transporting medically fit patients and providing telephone support to people at risk of [[loneliness]] because of self-isolation.<ref name=\"cauldield\">{{cite news |last1=Caulfield |first1=Chris |title=Call for NHS volunteers paused as 750,000 sign up |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/29/call-nhs-volunteers-paused-as750000-sign-12473430/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329125544/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/29/call-nhs-volunteers-paused-as750000-sign-12473430/ |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The target was surpassed in 24 hours and was raise to 750,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Volunteer target raised to 750,000 after more than half a million people sign up to help NHS |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-more-than-half-a-million-people-volunteer-to-help-nhs/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[ITV News]] |date=26 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329021015/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-26/coronavirus-more-than-half-a-million-people-volunteer-to-help-nhs/ |archivedate=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The scheme was paused on 29 March after the new target was reached.<ref name=\"cauldield\"/>\n\nOn 27 March it was announced that two further emergency COVID-19 hospitals were to be constructed by NHS England, at the [[National Exhibition Centre]], Birmingham and at [[Manchester Central Convention Complex]].<ref name=\"Campbell\">{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Lucy |title=UK coronavirus live: rate of infection doubling every three to four days, says Gove |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/27/uk-coronavirus-live-rough-sleepers-nhs-applause-covid-19-latest-news#block-5e7e33ce8f08af215f6fca9e |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, Boris Johnson announced that more than 20,000 former NHS staff were returning to work in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Milne |first1=Oliver |title=More than 20,000 retired NHS staff will re-join service for coronavirus fight |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-more-20000-retired-nhs-21776375 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=29 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330112554/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-more-20000-retired-nhs-21776375 |archivedate=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Defence ===\n{{main|Military aid to the civil authorities|Operation Rescript|Operation Broadshare}}\nIn March 2020, the Ministry of Defence announced the formation of the COVID Support Force, a 20,000 strong military support force to support public services and civil authorities in tackling the virus.<ref name=\"Rescript1\"/> Two military operations; [[Operation Rescript]], based in the UK, and [[Operation Broadshare]], focused on overseas defence activities, were launched.<ref name=\"Rescript2\" /> 150 military personnel began receiving training to drive oxygen tankers for the NHS.<ref name=\"Rescript1\"/> [[The Daily Telegraph|''The Telegraph'']] reported [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] [[Nick Carter (British Army officer)|Nick Carter]] had ordered the military to prepare for a \"six month\" operation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Defence Chief tells military to prepare for six-month operation whilst warning of threats from 'those who wish to undermine our way of life' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/defence-chief-tells-military-prepare-six-month-operation-whilst/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=The Telegraph |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321114808/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/defence-chief-tells-military-prepare-six-month-operation-whilst/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The armed forces had previously been used to assist the government in bringing British citizens home from affected areas, such as China and Japan.<ref name=\"MACA\">{{cite web |title=Military Aid to Civil Authorities: The COVID Support Force |url=https://medium.com/voices-of-the-armed-forces/military-aid-to-civil-authorities-the-covid-support-force-acd80ec70099 |website=medium.com |date=19 March 2020 |publisher=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321135440/https://medium.com/voices-of-the-armed-forces/military-aid-to-civil-authorities-the-covid-support-force-acd80ec70099 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 March, the Royal Air Force reportedly assisted repatriation flights of British and EU citizens from Cuba.<ref>{{cite news |title=RAF assist repatriation flight of British and EU citizens from Cuba |url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/raf-assist-repatriation-flight-of-british-and-eu-citizens-from-cuba/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=UK Defence Jorunal |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that training exercises, including those overseas in Canada and Kenya, had been cancelled to free up personnel for the COVID Support Force.<ref>{{cite news |title=10,000 extra troops to join British army's Covid support force |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/18/10000-extra-troops-to-join-british-armys-covid-support-force |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132719/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/18/10000-extra-troops-to-join-british-armys-covid-support-force |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several air shows, including the [[Royal International Air Tattoo]] at [[RAF Fairford]], were also cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Farnborough and RAF Fairford air shows cancelled |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-51978103 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Air Force began using [[Birmingham Airport]] to practise transferring Coronavirus patients to local hospitals via helicopter.<ref name=\"Irwin\">{{cite news |last1=Irwin |first1=David |title=Military helicopters training over airport amid Covid-19 crisis |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/military-helicopters-training-over-birmingham-17954008 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321180535/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/military-helicopters-training-over-birmingham-17954008 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Military on more manoeuvres around Birmingham Airport to transport coronavirus patients |url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/military-response-steps-up-to-coronavirus-with-more-raf-manoeuvres-around-birmingham-airport/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=Solihull Observer |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132723/https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/military-response-steps-up-to-coronavirus-with-more-raf-manoeuvres-around-birmingham-airport/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> A critically ill patient was also transported from the [[Gilbert Bain Hospital]] in [[Shetland]] to an intensive care ward in [[Aberdeen]] by an RAF [[Airbus A400M Atlas]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |title=Military called in to fly Covid-19 patient to intensive care |url=https://www.shetnews.co.uk/2020/03/22/military-called-in-to-fly-covid-19-patient-to-intensive-care/ |agency=shetnews.co.uk |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, it was announced that military planners helped plan a temporary hospital to be opened in the [[ExCeL London]] conference centre, to be named the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital]], which would be staffed by military medics, alongside the NHS.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Transport ===\n\n[[File:Empty M4 Motorway in Cardiff due to COVID-19 (1) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|An empty [[M4 motorway]] in [[Cardiff]] on the afternoon of Saturday 28 March 2020 due to the coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==== Aviation ====\nFrom the latter half of January, [[Heathrow Airport]] received additional clinical support and tightened surveillance of the three direct flights that it receives from Wuhan every week; each were to be met by a Port Health team.<ref name=\"Mahase22Jan2020\"/> Later, airlines including [[British Airways]] and [[Ryanair]] announced a number of flight cancellations for March.<ref name=BBCNews2March2020/>\n\nRegional airline [[Flybe]] had been brought to the brink of collapse following prior financial trouble earlier in the year. This, combined with decreased ticket sales as a result of the outbreak, caused the airline to stop ticket sales on 4 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |title=Collapsed Flybe tells passengers not to travel to airports |website=BBC News |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305000425/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51746564 |archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/flybe-news-flights-administration-collapse-coronavirus-outbreak-bust-latest-news-a9376421.html |title=Flybe collapses as coronavirus pandemic takes toll |website=The Independent |first=Simon |last=Calder |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305164758/https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/flybe-news-flights-administration-collapse-coronavirus-outbreak-bust-latest-news-a9376421.html|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The company entered [[Administration in United Kingdom law|administration]] and ceased operations the following day.<ref name=Baldwin2020>{{Cite book |last=Baldwin |first=Richard|chapter-url=https://cepr.org/sites/default/files/news/COVID-19.pdf |title=Economics in the time of COVID-19 |last2=Weder di Mauro |first2=Beatrice |publisher=CEPR Press |year=2020 |isbn=978-1-912179-28-2|editor-last=Baldwin|editor-first=Richard |location=London |page=18 |chapter=Introduction|editor-last2=Weder di Mauro|editor-first2=Beatrice}}</ref>\n\nDespite some calls for a bailout, led mainly by [[Virgin Atlantic]], the Chancellor, Rishi Sunak, said that the government would only come into the picture as \"a last resort\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/virgin-atlantic-boss-urges-boris-johnson-to-sanction-7-5bn-airline-bailout-11957708 |title=Virgin Atlantic boss urges Boris Johnson to sanction \u00a37.5bn airline bailout |website=Sky News |language=en |date=15 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52027342 |title=No extra help for airlines, chancellor says |date=24 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==== Public transport ====\nOn 20 March, [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]] became the first [[train operating company]] to announce a reduced timetable, which would come into use from 23 March.<ref>[https://www.kentlive.news/news/kent-news/kent-coronavirus-southeastern-makes-major-3966534 Kent Coronavirus southeastern makes major] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201805/https://www.kentlive.news/news/kent-news/kent-coronavirus-southeastern-makes-major-3966534 |date=20 March 2020 }} ''www.kentlive.news''</ref> On that day the government announced emergency measures to safeguard the nation's [[Rail transport in the United Kingdom|rail network]], with season ticket holders given refunds if working from home, and [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|rail franchise agreements]] nationalised for at least six months to prevent train operating companies from collapsing.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52002272 |title=Commuters to get refund on rail season tickets |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-rail-franchise-agreements-suspended-to-avoid-company-collapses-11962186 |title=Coronavirus: Rail franchise agreements suspended to avoid company collapses |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |publisher=Sky News}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[Sheffield Supertram|Stagecoach Supertram]] light rail network in [[Sheffield]] announced that they would be switching to a modified Sunday service from 23 March until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/health/coronavirus-changes-made-supertram-service-sheffield-2502449 |title=Coronavirus: changes made to the Supertram service in Sheffield |website=www.thestar.co.uk|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201755/https://www.thestar.co.uk/health/coronavirus-changes-made-supertram-service-sheffield-2502449|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Local bus operators [[First South Yorkshire]] and [[Stagecoach Yorkshire]], which operate across the same area, announced that they would also be switching to a reduced timetable from 23 March.<ref>[https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/transport/coronavirus-bus-timetables-change-sheffield-doncaster-and-south-yorkshire-2502683 Coronavirus bus timetables change Sheffield Doncaster and South Yorkshire] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201759/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/transport/coronavirus-bus-timetables-change-sheffield-doncaster-and-south-yorkshire-2502683 |date=20 March 2020 }} ''www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk'', accessed 20 March 2020</ref>\n\n[[Transport for London]] (TfL) services are being reduced in stages. All [[Night Overground]] and [[Night Tube]] services, as well as all services on the [[Waterloo & City line]], were suspended from 20 March, and 40 tube stations were closed on the same day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-london-shops-could-close-and-transport-restricted-by-weekend-whitehall-sources-11959814 |title=Coronavirus: London cuts Tube trains and warns 'don't travel unless you really have to' |website=Sky News |language=en|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321052444/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-london-shops-could-close-and-transport-restricted-by-weekend-whitehall-sources-11959814|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Mayor of London]] and TfL urged people to only use public transport if absolutely essential, so that it can be used by critical workers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2020/march/planned-services-to-support-london-s-critical-workers |title=Planned services to support London's critical workers |last=Matters |first=Transport for London {{!}} Every Journey|website=Transport for London|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201755/https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2020/march/planned-services-to-support-london-s-critical-workers|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A further reduction in service from 23 March will affect [[London Overground]], [[TfL Rail]], [[Docklands Light Railway]] and [[London Trams]] services.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} The London Underground brought in new measures on 25 March to combat the spread of the coronavirus, by slowing the flow of passengers onto platforms. This was done by various means including queuing at the ticket gates and, in the somes cases, escalators were powered down.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-52023580 |title=New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential trips |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Consumer response===\n[[File:Pasta shortage tourism at Tesco, Finchley, London.jpg|thumb|The almost empty pasta section in a London [[Tesco]], 7 March 2020]]\nIt was reported in ''[[The Guardian]]'' that British supermarkets and their suppliers had developed a plan to ensure a consistent supply of a range of basic goods if there was panic-buying by consumers. [[Tesco]], the country's largest supermarket chain, was said to have carried out simulation exercises to plan for events such as a pandemic flu outbreak which could be used to deal with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=guardi>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/02/uk-supermarkets-braced-for-stockpiling-if-coronavirus-escalates-panic-buying |title=UK supermarkets draw up plan to 'feed the nation' as coronavirus spreads |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first1=Jasper |last1=Jolly |first2=Rebecca |last2=Smith |date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303013359/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/02/uk-supermarkets-braced-for-stockpiling-if-coronavirus-escalates-panic-buying|archive-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> There were reports of hand sanitiser and anti-bacterial products selling out at some supermarkets.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thegrocer.co.uk/service-and-availability/supermarkets-sell-out-of-hand-sanitiser-amid-coronavirus-panic-buying/602551.article |title=Supermarkets sell out of hand sanitiser amid coronavirus panic-buying |website=The Grocer |publisher=William Reed Business Media |first1=Carina |last1=Perkins |first2=Ellis |last2=Hawthorne |date=4 March 2020 |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> Online retailers reported consumers placing unusually large orders while the managing director of the frozen food chain [[Iceland (retailer)|Iceland]] reported increased sales of \"multibuy deals and larger packs\".<ref name=guardi/>\n[[File:DSC05532 (49675496857).jpg|thumb|People in [[London]] were buying more canned foods and [[toilet paper]], 18 March 2020]]\nSome supermarkets and other shops responded by limiting the amount customers brought of popular items, whilst others had a blanket limit across their entire range.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/21/uk-supermarket-restrictions-grocery-shops-panic/ |title=UK supermarket restrictions: how local grocery shops are introducing rationing to fight food shortages |first=Lizzie |last=Roberts |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321193542/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/21/uk-supermarket-restrictions-grocery-shops-panic/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/national/18312957.supermarkets-place-buying-limits-items-bring-oap-only-shopping-hours/ |title=Supermarkets place buying limits on items and bring in OAP-only shopping hours |website=Sutton & Croydon Guardian |agency=Press Association|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321193541/https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/national/18312957.supermarkets-place-buying-limits-items-bring-oap-only-shopping-hours/|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sainsburys]] announced on 18 March that they would introduce a dedicated shopping hour for elderly and disabled customers, as well as giving them priority for online deliveries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/elderly-only-shopping-sainsburys-brings-17941743 |title=Elderly-only shopping as Sainsbury's brings in tough new rules |website=Wales Online |first=Neil |last=Shaw |date=18 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321194235/https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/elderly-only-shopping-sainsburys-brings-17941743|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other supermarkets, such as Iceland and Morrisons also introduced measures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/tesco-asda-sainsburys-aldi-iceland-17952371 |title=Supermarket opening time changes and new rules on what you can buy |website=Chronicle Live |first1=Michael |last1=Muncaster |first2=Elle May |last2=Rice |date=20 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213358/https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/tesco-asda-sainsburys-aldi-iceland-17952371|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Sainsbury's further announced on 21 March that they would give healthcare workers allocated shopping hours on three mornings a week, along with elderly and vulnerable customers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/sainsburys-offers-nhs-and-elderly-three-weekday-shopping-slots-224199/ |title=Coronavirus Kent: Sainsbury's offers NHS staff allocated shopping hours and extends dedicated slots for elderly |website=Kent Online |first=Joe |last=Walker |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321201312/https://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/sainsburys-offers-nhs-and-elderly-three-weekday-shopping-slots-224199/|archive-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] stopped sellers from sending non essential products to their warehouses and [[Selfridges]] closed all its stores, however customers can still buy their products from their website.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51941987 |title=Sainsbury's limits sales of all food items amid stockpiling |website=BBC News |date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074305/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51941987|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the panic buying of food, Professor [[Stephen Powis]], medical director at NHS England, said on 21 March that NHS staff were being deprived of food supplies because of the activities of some consumers, and urged people to shop responsibly. [[Helen Dickinson]], head of the [[British Retail Consortium]] said that there was enough food in the supply chain, but that the issue was getting it to retailers quick enough, suggesting the food industry was experiencing \"a peak in demand\" like at Christmas, but \"without the four-month build-up period.\" She added that that an extra \u00a31bn had been spent on food in the preceding three weeks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51989721 |title=Buy responsibly and think of others, shoppers told |work=BBC News |date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321213812/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51989721|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[George Eustice]] also urged shoppers to stop panic buying.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721 |title=Coronavirus: Shoppers told to buy responsibly |website=BBC News |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321142202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day it was reported that [[Tesco]], [[Asda]], [[Aldi]], and [[Lidl]] had begun a recruitment drive for up to 30,000 new staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075 |title=Supermarkets Tesco, Asda, Aldi and Lidl go on hiring spree |website=BBC News |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321000450/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the government announced that the [[Phase-out of lightweight plastic bags#United Kingdom|5p charge for carrier bags]] would be waived for online food deliveries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/21/plastic-bag-charge-waived-speed-supermarket-service-coronavirus-crisis-12435418/ |title=Coronavirus: Plastic bag charge waived for online deliveries to speed up service |website=Metro |publisher=DMG Media |first=James |last=Hockaday |date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Food and hospitality===\nFast food and drink outlets, [[Pret a Manger]] and [[McDonald's]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/food-and-drink/mcdonalds-closing-seating-areas-coronavirus-takeway-drive-thru-monopoly-2482763 |title=McDonald's closing all seating areas due to coronavirus to become takeaway only \u2013 and Monopoly promotion is scrapped |publisher=inews |date= |accessdate=2020-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319154309/https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/food-and-drink/mcdonalds-closing-seating-areas-coronavirus-takeway-drive-thru-monopoly-2482763 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> (among others) at first announced that they would not permit customers to sit and eat in stores, but customers could still order products to take away and consume off the premises. On 22 March McDonalds announced it would close all outlets in the UK and Ireland by 7pm on 23 March.<ref name=guardian-mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/22/mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday |title=McDonald's to close restaurants in UK and Ireland on Monday |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=22 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322224815/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/22/mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nando's]] announced later the same day they would also close their outlets.<ref name=guardian-mcdonalds-to-close-restaurants-in-uk-and-ireland-on-monday/>\n\nInitially, the pub chain [[J D Wetherspoon]] remained open, despite government advice for the public to avoid places of social activity, including pubs. The chain announced that it would keep all pubs open \"unless the government states otherwise\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/news/2020/03/covid-19 |title=Wetherspoon is to continue operating its pubs across the UK \u2013 J D Wetherspoon | access-date=19 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319170624/https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/news/2020/03/covid-19 | archive-date=19 March 2020 | url-status=live}}</ref> On 20 March, all Wetherspoon pubs were closed in line with instructions from the government.<ref>[https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/contact/faqs/uk-coronavirus-covid-19-infection Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the UK] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319154903/https://www.jdwetherspoon.com/contact/faqs/uk-coronavirus-covid-19-infection |date=19 March 2020 }} 20 March 2020 ''www.jdwetherspoon.com'' accessed 21 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nConstruction sites largely remained operational following the introduction of social distancing rules. Following criticism, [[Barratt Developments|Barratt]], [[Taylor Wimpey]], [[Mace (construction company)|Mace]] and other companies paused work on 24 March.<ref>[https://www.constructionnews.co.uk/buildings/barratt-and-taylor-wimpey-shut-all-sites-24-03-2020/ Barratt and Taylor Wimpey shut all sites] 24 March 2020 ''www.constructionnews.co.uk'', accessed 26 March 2020</ref>\n\n===Economics===\nThe governor of the Bank of England called on the British government to provide support to businesses affected by the virus<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/04/next-bank-of-england-governor-calls-for-funds-for-coronavirus-hit-firms |title=Next Bank of England governor calls for funds for coronavirus-hit firms |work=Guardian |date=4 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307100455/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/04/next-bank-of-england-governor-calls-for-funds-for-coronavirus-hit-firms|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and was reported to be working with the Treasury to provide a stimulus package to prevent the British economy falling into recession.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/05/coronavirus-could-push-uk-to-brink-of-recession-says-goldman-sachs |title=Bank of England drafts action plan to head off coronavirus recession |first1=Jasper |last1=Jolly |first2=Julia |last2=Kollewe |work=Guardian |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307100403/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/05/coronavirus-could-push-uk-to-brink-of-recession-says-goldman-sachs|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Companies listed on the London stock markets have fallen in value with commentators citing worries about the virus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51681620 |title=Coronavirus fears wipe \u00a3200bn off UK firms' value |work=BBC News |date=28 February 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302144058/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51681620|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> To stimulate the economy, the [[Bank of England]] cut interest rates from 0.75 to 0.25 percent.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Inman |first1=Phillip |last2=Partington |first2=Richard |last3=Sweney |first3=Mark |title=Coronavirus: Bank of England makes emergency interest rate cut |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/11/coronavirus-bank-of-england-makes-emergency-interest-rate-cut |accessdate=11 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March, the interest rate was again cut this time to 0.10% \u2013 the lowest rate in the bank's 325-year existence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |title=Coronavirus: UK interest rates slashed again in emergency move |date=19 March 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319152457/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nFollowing cases in Italy, the [[Cransley School]] in [[Northwich]], [[Cheshire]], and [[Trinity Catholic College, Middlesbrough|Trinity Catholic College]] in [[Middlesbrough]] closed, as some of their pupils had returned with symptoms from Italy. Fourteen schools in England had closed by 28 February.<ref name=Bedingfield>{{Cite news |last=Bedingfield |first=Will |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-schools-closed |title=Will shutting down UK schools stop coronavirus? It's complicated |date=28 February 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=3 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302194619/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/coronavirus-uk-schools-closed|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Loughborough University]] reported a student confirmed to have the virus after recent travel to Italy, and indicated that several staff members and students began self-isolation.<ref name=LboroUni>{{Cite news |last=Fagan |first=Ciaran |URL=https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/news/local-news/leicestershires-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-3925980 |title=Leicestershire's first Coronavirus case is confirmed as a university student |work=Leicester Mercury|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308024036/https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/news/local-news/leicestershires-first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-3925980|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]] was heavily criticised for their incoherent response to the pandemic which forced international students and staff to scramble to make arrangements to return home with only two days' notice. On 13 March, students and staff were advised that international travel was discouraged and university facilities would stay open at reduced capacity. However, on 18 March, Vice Chancellor [[Stephen Toope]] announced a sudden U-turn and all university buildings would be indefinitely shut from all staff and students from the afternoon of Friday 20 March onwards, and all students are strongly encouraged to leave Cambridge.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-colleges-criticised-for-asking-students-to-leave-over-coronavirus |title=Cambridge colleges criticised for asking students to leave over coronavirus |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |language=en|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319153851/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-colleges-criticised-for-asking-students-to-leave-over-coronavirus|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The president of Cambridge [[University and College Union|UCU]] criticised that this sudden shutdown will exacerbate the pandemic as students from countries with weaker healthcare provisions are forced to return home.<ref name=\":0\" /> Over a thousand Cambridge students signed an open letter requesting to have multiple assessment options in lieu of the cancelled examinations in Cambridge, including the option to retake part or all of the academic year in 2020\u201321.<ref>{{cite news |last=Batty |first=David |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-students-urge-university-to-cancel-final-exams-over-coronavirus |title=Cambridge students urge university to let them retake the final year |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Guardian|access-date=20 March 2020 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319154023/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2020/mar/18/cambridge-students-urge-university-to-cancel-final-exams-over-coronavirus|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Coventry University]] first suspended all graduation ceremonies due to be held in March and April,<ref name=\"Layton\">{{cite news |last1=Layton |first1=Josh |url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/coventry-university-cancels-graduation-ceremonies-17905226 |title=Coventry University suspends graduation ceremonies to guard against coronavirus |date=11 March 2020 |work=[[Coventry Telegraph]] |accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312175516/https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/coventry-university-cancels-graduation-ceremonies-17905226|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and from 20 March, suspended all face-to-face teaching, in favour of on-line delivery.<ref name=\"CU\">{{cite web |title=Our response to COVID-19. |url=https://www.coventry.ac.uk/the-university/key-information/health-and-safety-information/our-response-to-covid-19/ |publisher=Coventry University |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> Many other higher education institutions took similar steps at around the same time.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/education-51880355 |title=More universities halt teaching and exams |date=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-19 |language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318214433/https://www.bbc.com/news/education-51880355|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the Welsh government announced that all schools in Wales would be closing by 20 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=All schools in Wales to close by Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318132314/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, the [[First Minister of Scotland]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]] announced that Scottish schools would also be closing from 20 March, and may not reopen before the summer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Schools 'may be shut until summer' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51947670 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140554/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51947670 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later that day, it was announced that schools in Northern Ireland would close to pupils immediately and to staff on 20 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schools in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland to close by the end of the week |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-18/coronavirus-outbreak-wales-school-closing-by-friday-highly-possible-scottish-schools-will-shut/ |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=ITV News |date=18 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318184451/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-18/coronavirus-outbreak-wales-school-closing-by-friday-highly-possible-scottish-schools-will-shut/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, the [[Secretary of State for Education]], [[Gavin Williamson]] announced that schools in England would close from 20 March for an unspecified length of time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Schools in England follow Scotland and Wales in closing |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318174202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] said, however, that schools will still look after the children of [[key workers]], and vulnerable children.<ref name=GuardianSchoolsClosed/> The UK government also announced that [[GCSE]] and [[A Level]] exams were to be cancelled, an unprecedented action in UK educational history, and that grades were to be given out based on predicted grades and teacher assessment.<ref name=GuardianSchoolsClosed>{{cite newspaper |title=UK schools to be closed indefinitely and exams cancelled |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |last1=Adams |first1=Richard |last2=Stewart |first2=Heather |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-be-closed-indefinitely-and-exams-cancelled |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320215503/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/18/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-be-closed-indefinitely-and-exams-cancelled |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Coronavirus: GCSE and A-Level results to be based on teachers predicted grades |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-20/coronavirus-gcse-and-a-level-results-to-be-based-on-teachers-predicted-graces/ |newspaper=[[ITV News]] |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320201045/https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-20/coronavirus-gcse-and-a-level-results-to-be-based-on-teachers-predicted-graces/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Fears that cancelling exams will hit BAME and poor pupils worst |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/19/fears-that-cancelling-exams-will-hit-black-and-poor-pupils-worst |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=21 March 2020 |last1=Weale |first1=Sally |last2=Batty |first2=David |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320132257/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/19/fears-that-cancelling-exams-will-hit-black-and-poor-pupils-worst |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\nWith respect to Christianity, the [[Church of England]], the [[Christian state|state church]], as well as other ecclesiastical provinces of the [[Anglican Communion]] in the British Isles such as the [[Church in Wales]], suspended in-person worship amidst the 2020 coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Church of England suspends public worship over coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-church/church-of-england-suspends-public-worship-over-coronavirus-idUSKBN2142GE |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Church and religious services off across Wales |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-51974782 |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] led a virtual [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] that was broadcast on thirty-nine local BBC stations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Archbishop of Canterbury to lead first virtual Church of England service |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-archbishop-of-canterbury-to-lead-first-virtual-church-of-england-service-11960268 |publisher=[[Sky News]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Catholic Church]], [[Methodist Church in Great Britain]] and the [[Society of Friends]] have also put a temporary moratorium on public worship.<ref name=\"Sherwood2020\">{{cite web |last1=Sherwood |first1=Harriet |title=Church of England suspends all services over coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/17/church-of-england-suspends-services-coronavirus |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Catholic churches preparing to suspend Mass |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51887510 |publisher=BBC |language=English |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Many Christian churches are broadcasting worship services via online livestream, radio and television.<ref name=\"Frost2020\">{{cite web |last1=Frost |first1=Natasha |title=In the face of coronavirus, religions are embracing the power of online community |url=https://qz.com/1815328/religions-are-embracing-live-streaming-and-conference-calls/ |publisher=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe chief rabbi in the United Kingdom advised the suspension of Jewish worship in synagogues and the [[Muslim Council of Britain]] has ordered the closure of mosques in the country.<ref name=\"Sherwood2020\"/>\n\n===Law and order===\nOn 17 March trials lasting longer than three days were postponed until May in England and Wales, while Scottish courts were not starting any new trial indefinitely. In England and Wales those cases already running would continue in the hope of reaching a conclusion.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bowcott |first=Owen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2020/mar/18/longer-criminal-trials-in-england-and-wales-to-be-delayed-due-to-covid-19 |title=Longer criminal trials in England and Wales to be delayed due to Covid-19 |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318222623/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2020/mar/18/longer-criminal-trials-in-england-and-wales-to-be-delayed-due-to-covid-19 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Stubley |first=Peter |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-trials-court-jail-delays-lord-chief-justice-a9407936.html |title=Coronavirus: Criminal trials longer than three days to be put on hold |date=18 March 2020 |work=The Independent |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318152500/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-trials-court-jail-delays-lord-chief-justice-a9407936.html |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> A poll published on 20 March claimed that only 23% of British adults were strictly following the government's coronavirus advice.<ref>{{cite news |title=Only a quarter of UK adults are strictly following government's coronavirus advice, poll finds |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/quarter-uk-adults-strictly-following-governments-coronavirus/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Personal attacks====\n{{Further|List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United Kingdom}}\nThere have been [[List of incidents of xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#United Kingdom|reports of hate incidents]] against Italian and Chinese persons<ref name=\"Guardian Racism\">{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Lucy |title=Chinese in UK report 'shocking' levels of racism after coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/feb/09/chinese-in-uk-report-shocking-levels-of-racism-after-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=9 February 2020}}</ref> and a Singaporean student was assaulted in London in an attack that police linked to coronavirus fears.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-51736755 |title=Coronavirus: Men wanted over racist Oxford Street attack on student |work=BBC News |accessdate=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304122002/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-51736755|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Prisons====\nThe government released specific guidance to prisons in the event of coronavirus symptoms or cases, specifically the rule that \"any prisoner or detainee with a new, continuous cough or a high temperature should be placed in protective isolation for 7 days\".<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: prisons and other prescribed places of detention guidance |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320013825/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance/covid-19-prisons-and-other-prescribed-places-of-detention-guidance |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> There are around 83,000 prisoners in England and Wales.<ref name=Grierson26Mar2020/>\n\nOn 14 March, a prison officer in [[HMP High Down]] in Surrey tested positive for the virus and was sent home to self-isolate. Four officers who had contact with him were placed in isolation as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prison officer tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-51917123 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March, the first coronavirus case was reported within the UK prison population. The prisoner, who had been serving time in [[HMP Manchester]] (commonly referred to as Strangeways), was moved to a hospital. While no other prisoners or staff tested positive for the virus, thirteen prisoners and four members of staff were put into isolation as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bulman |first1=May |title=First UK prisoner infected with coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-cases-prison-uk-hmp-manchester-latest-symptoms-a9409251.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=18 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161647/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/coronavirus-cases-prison-uk-hmp-manchester-latest-symptoms-a9409251.html |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Prison visits remained open, but the situation is being monitored.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slater |first1=Chris |title=Strangeways prisoner tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/strangeways-prisoner-tests-positive-coronavirus-17944421 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318210353/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/strangeways-prisoner-tests-positive-coronavirus-17944421 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 March, it was revealed that around 75 officers at [[HMP Berwyn]] in Wales were off work due to sickness or self-isolation, and 22 prisoners showing symptoms of coronavirus were being isolated by the prison. However, the prison had enough staff members to remain fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rees |first1=Jenny |title=Seventy-five prison officers off sick or isolating |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320154011/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Another prison officer tested positive on 20 March at [[HMP Whitemoor]] near [[March, Cambridgeshire|March]], Cambridgeshire.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elworthy |first1=John |title=Ministry of Justice confirm an officer at top security Whitemoor Prison, March, tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/whitemoor-prison-officer-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-1-6572331 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Cambs Times |date=21 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321195409/https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/whitemoor-prison-officer-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-1-6572331 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the case in HMP Manchester, public services think tank [[Reform (think tank)|Reform]] called for the release of 2,305 \"low-risk\" offenders on short sentences to reduce the risk of coronavirus on the prison population.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cowburn |first1=Ashley |title=Ministers urged to release hundreds of prisoners on short sentences to combat coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-prison-inmates-government-ministers-curfew-a9412661.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=20 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320165607/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-uk-prison-inmates-government-ministers-curfew-a9412661.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Their report argues that prison are \"overcrowded [with] insanitary conditions and poor-quality healthcare\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Reducing the prison population: Extending Home Detention Curfew and scrapping short sentences {{!}} Reform |url=https://reform.uk/research/reducing-prison-population-extending-home-detention-curfew-and-scrapping-short-sentences |website=reform.uk |accessdate=20 March 2020 |date=March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320165609/https://reform.uk/research/reducing-prison-population-extending-home-detention-curfew-and-scrapping-short-sentences |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Similar actions have been taken in Iran and the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=US jails begin releasing prisoners amid pandemic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51947802 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319212202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51947802 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Former justice secretary [[David Gauke]] echoed similar sentiments, citing the \"churn\" of prisoners going in and out of prison as a risk.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Townsend |first1=Mark |last2=Savage |first2=Mark |last3=Doward |first3=Jamie |title=Prisons 'could see 800 deaths' from coronavirus without protective measures |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/21/prisons-could-see-800-deaths-from-coronavirus-without-protective-measures |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Observer |date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321221813/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/mar/21/prisons-could-see-800-deaths-from-coronavirus-without-protective-measures |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, a prisoner tested positive for the virus at [[HMP Birmingham]] and was placed into isolation. The prison was not placed into full lockdown, but made the decision to restrict access.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Carl |title=Prisoner at HMP Birmingham tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/prisoner-hmp-birmingham-tests-positive-17967296 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, a prisoner at [[HMP Oakwood]] near [[Wolverhampton]] tested positive for the virus and was placed into isolation. Visits to the prison were not stopped, but it is believed they were reduced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guttridge |first1=Richard |title=Prisons 'ready to act' but visits allowed as HMP Oakwood coronavirus case confirmed |url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/health/coronavirus-covid19/2020/03/23/prisons-ready-to-act-on-coronavirus-but-visits-still-allowed/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=www.expressandstar.com |date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the Ministry of Justice announced that prison visits would be suspended and that inmates would be confined to their cells.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pegg |first1=David |last2=Allison |first2=Eric |title=Release inmates or face jail pandemic, say prison governors |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/mar/25/release-prisoners-or-face-jail-pandemic-says-chief |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> In order to maintain communication between prisoners and their families, the government promised 900 secure phones to 55 prisons, with calls being monitored and time-limited.<ref>{{cite web |title=Prison visits cancelled |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/prison-visits-cancelled |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=25 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324181945/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/prison-visits-cancelled |archivedate=24 March 2020 |language=en |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> In a committee meeting on the same day, Justice Secretary [[Robert Buckland]] suggested that 50 pregnant inmates might be given early release, and another 9,000 inmates awaiting trial could be transferred to bail hostels.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inmates could be freed to ease virus jail pressures |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52029581 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, it was reported that 84-year-old convicted paedophile Edwin Hillier had died from COVID-19 on 22 March at [[HMP Littlehey]] in Cambridgeshire,<ref>{{cite news |title=School caretaker jailed for child abuse |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-35633835 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=22 February 2016}}</ref> becoming the first inmate in the UK to die from the virus. Another 66-year-old male inmate died from COVID-19 on 26 March at HMP Manchester.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man, 84, is first UK prison coronavirus death |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-52047003 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> As of 1pm the previous day, there were 19 confirmed cases in the prison population across 10 prisons.<ref name=Grierson26Mar2020>{{cite news |last1=Grierson |first1=Jamie |title=Man, 84, becomes first UK prisoner to die with coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/first-prisoner-in-uk-dies-from-coronavirus |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration centres====\nOn 25 March, it was reported that three [[Immigration detention in the United Kingdom|immigration detention centres]] had reported cases of people with coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Titheradge |first=Dr Faye Kirkland and Noel |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52017311 |title=Coronavirus 'symptoms' at three detention centres |date=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Policing====\nOn 26 March, in an attempt to emphasise the importance of following the social distancing instructions given by the government, the police were given powers to impose fines on individuals gathered in groups or who refuse to return home when asked to.<ref name=\"bbc_52101040\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52101040 |title=Coronavirus: Police told to be 'consistent' with lockdown approach |date=31 March 2020 |work=BBC News}}</ref> By 31 March, some police forces, and individual officers, were being criticised as being heavy-handed over the way they were choosing to interpret and apply the new powers.<ref name=\"bbc_52101040\"/>\n\n===Sport===\nOn 5 March, the England\u2013Italy fixtures in the men's and women's' [[Six Nations Championship]] tournaments, set to be played in [[Rome]] on 14 and 15 March, were postponed by tournament organisers after the Italian government introduced restrictions on attendances to sporting events.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254 |title=Coronavirus: England's Six Nations games against Italy postponed |website=BBC Sport |date=5 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306233340/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Scotland's Women's [[Women's Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] home fixture against France on 7 March was also postponed after one Scotland player tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"bbc_women_sixnations\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621 |title=Women's Six Nations: Scotland v France postponed after home player tests positive for coronavirus |website=BBC Sport |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308061514/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Rugby Football Union]] suspended all forms of rugby in England from 17 March to 14 April, which was then extended to the end of the season with the exception of the [[2019\u201320 Premiership Rugby|Premiership]] on 20 March. The [[Welsh Rugby Union]] also suspended all forms of rugby in Wales from 14 to 30 March, which also extended to the end of the season of 20 March.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nTo contain the spread of the virus the [[Premier League]] announced on 6 March an end to pre-match fair play handshakes between players and officials.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51760339 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League & EFL ditch pre-match fair-play handshakes |website=BBC Sport |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307001827/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51760339|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 March, the Premier League match between [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] was postponed in light of confirmation that [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] and [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] owner [[Evangelos Marinakis]] had contracted the virus. Marinakis had met with several Arsenal players when the London side hosted Olympiacos in a [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League knockout phase#Round of 32|Europa League round of 32]] match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51829511 |title=Manchester City v Arsenal postponed over coronavirus fears |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311084144/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51829511|archive-date=11 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 March the four-day [[Cheltenham Festival]] continued as planned with enhanced hygiene measures in place,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/10/cheltenham-festival-key-event-in-racing-calendar-goes-ahead-despite-coronavirus |title=Cheltenham Festival: key race meeting goes ahead despite coronavirus |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Steven |last=Morris |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095618/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/10/cheltenham-festival-key-event-in-racing-calendar-goes-ahead-despite-coronavirus|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as did the [[All England Open Badminton Championships]] in Birmingham the next day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/11/service-as-normal-badminton-birmingham-all-england-championships |title=Service as normal: badminton's finest cock-a-hoop to get back to business |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Sean |last=Ingle |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314212841/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/11/service-as-normal-badminton-birmingham-all-england-championships|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, it was announced that Arsenal manager [[Mikel Arteta]] had tested positive to COVID-19,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51865442 |title=Mikel Arteta: Arsenal manager tests positive for coronavirus |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313005542/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51865442|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the next day [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] midfielder [[Callum Hudson-Odoi]] became the first Premier League player to test positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Chelsea's Callum Hudson-Odoi and Arsenal boss Mikel Arteta test positive |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867854 |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313071303/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867854|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Professional football was later suspended across the United Kingdom on 13 March, with the [[Premier League]], [[English Football League]], [[Women's Super League]], and Welsh and Northern Irish football leagues delaying matches until the beginning of April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended in England \u2013 Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland halt games |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140033/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[Scottish Professional Football League]] suspending matches indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51858736 |title=Coronavirus: Scottish football suspended until further notice |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133750/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51858736|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Professional football in England was later postponed until the end of April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51962751 |title=Coronavirus: English football suspension extended until at least 30&nbsp;April |website=BBC Sport |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319132255/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51962751|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The day also saw the cancellation of the Wales\u2013Scotland Six Nations match scheduled for 14 March<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/13/wales-v-scotland-six-nations-match-called-off-coronavirus-rugby-union |title=Wales v Scotland Six Nations match called off 24 hours before kick-off |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Paul |last=Rees |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134611/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/13/wales-v-scotland-six-nations-match-called-off-coronavirus-rugby-union|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the postponement of the [[London Marathon|London]], [[Greater Manchester Marathon|Manchester]] and [[Brighton Marathon]]s from their April dates until the autumn.<ref name=\"BBC-LM-13Mar2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314143346/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe next five days saw a flurry of further sporting cancellations. Five fixtures set to be played on Saturday 14 March in the [[National League (English football)|National League]] were postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51877974 |title=Coronavirus: Five National League games on Saturday called off following outbreak |website=BBC Sport |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318210942/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51877974|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with all matches across both the National League and the [[Northern Premier League]] suspended two days later and the [[Football Association]] recommending the postponement of grassroots level football \"for the foreseeable future\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/16/national-league-shuts-down-as-fa-puts-all-english-grassroots-football-on-hold |title=National League shuts down as FA puts all English grassroots football on hold |website=The Guardian |agency=PA Media |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317182216/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/16/national-league-shuts-down-as-fa-puts-all-english-grassroots-football-on-hold|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Welsh Rugby Union]] discontinued all rugby matches across Wales from Saturday evening until the end of the month.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51889671 |title=Welsh rugby: WRU announce suspension until end of March |website=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318210942/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51889671|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On Sunday 15 March the [[Netball Superleague]] was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/netball/news/12415/11957895/coronavirus-vitality-netball-superleague-postponed-with-immediate-effect |title=Coronavirus: Vitality Netball Superleague postponed with immediate effect |website=Sky Sports |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318212310/https://www.skysports.com/netball/news/12415/11957895/coronavirus-vitality-netball-superleague-postponed-with-immediate-effect|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Premiership Rugby]] was suspended for five weeks on Monday 16 March, with all rugby activities in England being delayed until 14 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/16/rugby-premiership-suspended-for-five-weeks-over-coronavirus-pandemic |title=Premiership Rugby suspended for five weeks over coronavirus pandemic |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |first=Paul |last=Rees |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318043714/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/16/rugby-premiership-suspended-for-five-weeks-over-coronavirus-pandemic|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Monday additionally saw the cancellation of the [[2020 Grand National|Grand National]],<ref name=\"BBC GN Mar2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/horse-racing/51930209 |title=Coronavirus: Horse racing in Great Britain suspended until end of April |website=BBC Sport |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041609/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/horse-racing/51930209|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> the postponement of the [[Edinburgh Marathon]] from May to September,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/health/edinburgh-marathon-festival-2020-confirmed-date-postponed-race-marathon-route-and-how-enter-2450122 |title=Edinburgh Marathon Festival 2020: confirmed date for postponed race, marathon route and how to enter |website=Edinburgh Evening News |first=Rhona |last=Shennan |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317171121/https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/health/edinburgh-marathon-festival-2020-confirmed-date-postponed-race-marathon-route-and-how-enter-2450122|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the first peacetime cancellation of the [[Boat Race]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rowing/2020/03/16/coronavirus-forces-first-boat-race-cancellation-outside-world/ |title=Coronavirus forces first Boat Race cancellation outside of a world war |newspaper=The Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |first=Rachel |last=Quarrell |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> On Tuesday 17 March all motor racing events sanctioned by the national governing body [[Motorsport UK]] were suspended until May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148702/no-motorsport-uksanctioned-events-until-may |title=No Motorsport UK-sanctioned events until May due to coronavirus |website=Autosport |first=Stephen |last=Lickorish |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318211841/https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148702/no-motorsport-uksanctioned-events-until-may|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> All horse racing events were similarly suspended the following day,<ref name=\"BBC GN Mar2020\"/> as were all boxing tournaments until further notice subject to a [[British Boxing Board of Control]] review in April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11958895/coronavirus-british-boxing-board-of-control-cancels-all-events-due-to-pandemic |title=Coronavirus: British Boxing Board of Control cancels all events due to pandemic |website=Sky Sports |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319022433/https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11958895/coronavirus-british-boxing-board-of-control-cancels-all-events-due-to-pandemic|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Arts and entertainment===\n====Music====\n[[File:Wee Annie, Cleats & Clyde, face mask.jpg|thumb|right|The \"Wee Annie\" statue in [[Gourock]] with a face mask, on 22 March.]]\nOn 13 March, [[BBC Radio 1]] announced that it would cancel its [[BBC Radio 1's Big Weekend|Big Weekend]] music festival, scheduled to take place in [[Dundee]] over the [[Spring Bank Holiday]] weekend at the end of May.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/51672257 |title=Coronavirus: Coachella, Radio 1's Big Weekend, BTS and other music events affected |work=CBBC Newsround |date=13 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301213740/https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/51672257|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other music events to be cancelled included the [[C2C: Country to Country]] festival, the UK's largest country music event,<ref name=MetroGigs/> and the 2020 [[Glastonbury Festival]] which was cancelled on 18 March.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51942898 |title=Glastonbury festival cancelled due to coronavirus |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |last1=Savage |first1=Mark| access-date=18 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318114624/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51942898| archive-date=18 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> Among the artists and bands to postpone or cancel UK gigs or tours were [[Avril Lavigne]] and [[The Who]].<ref name=MetroGigs>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/artists-cancelled-gigs-due-coronavirus-12401000/ |title=Coronavirus: Gigs and events cancelled so far |date=15 March 2020|access-date = 16 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200316162942/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/artists-cancelled-gigs-due-coronavirus-12401000/|archive-date = 16 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/coronavirus-tours-gigs-festivals-cancelled-list-who-bts-billie-eilish-stormzy-a9399646.html |title=Billie Eilish, the Who and BTS among tours and festivals cancelled over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020|access-date = 16 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200317214345/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/coronavirus-tours-gigs-festivals-cancelled-list-who-bts-billie-eilish-stormzy-a9399646.html|archive-date = 17 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> Others, including [[Chris Martin]] of [[Coldplay]], [[Yungblud]], [[Keith Urban]] and [[Christine And The Queens]] responded to the situation by live-streaming gigs through social media.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51924765 |title=Pop stars live-stream concerts to combat isolation |work=BBC News |date=17 March 2020 |last1=Savage |first1=Mark| access-date=18 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318014752/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51924765| archive-date=18 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 March, [[Pride in London]], the UK's largest LGBT [[Pride festival]], scheduled for 27 June, was postponed. It was one of a hundred pride events to be postponed or cancelled in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hunte |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |title=Coronavirus postpones London Pride |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323092251/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 March, the former ''[[Beautiful South]]'' members [[Paul Heaton]] and [[Jacqui Abbott]] announced they would play a free show for NHS staff working on the frontline of the pandemic, giving away 9,000 free tickets for the event in October.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52032618 |title=Paul Heaton and Jacqui Abbott to play free NHS gig |first=Mark |last=Savage |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The [[Isle of Wight Festival|Isle of Wight]] and [[Download Festival|Download]] music festivals, scheduled for June, were cancelled on 26 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/26/download-and-isle-of-wight-festivals-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus |title=Download and Isle of Wight festivals cancelled due to coronavirus |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |date=26 March 2020 |via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> The [[Cambridge Folk Festival]], scheduled to take place over four days from 30 July, was cancelled on 27 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/cambridge-folk-festival-been-cancelled-17997939 |title=Another summer festival has been cancelled this year in Cambridge |first=Alistair |last=Ryder |date=27 March 2020 |website=cambridgenews}}</ref>\n\n====Theatre and cinema====\nOn 15 March, London's [[The Old Vic|Old Vic]] became the first [[West End theatre|West End]] theatre to cancel a performance when it ended its run of [[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Endgame (play)|Endgame]]'' two weeks early.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/old-vic-endgame-coronavirus-daniel-radcliffe-a4387811.html |title=Endgame as Old Vic becomes first London theatre to cancel performances |date=15 March 2020|access-date = 16 March 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154238/https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/old-vic-endgame-coronavirus-daniel-radcliffe-a4387811.html|archive-date = 16 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> On 16 March, other theatres in London, as well as elsewhere around the UK, closed following Boris Johnson's advice that people should avoid such venues.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51906370 |title=West End shuts down after PM's coronavirus advice |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020| access-date=16 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316220403/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51906370| archive-date=16 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 March, cinema chains [[Odeon Cinemas|Odeon]], [[Cineworld]], [[Vue Cinemas|Vue]] and [[Picturehouse Cinemas|Picturehouse]] announced they would be closing all of their UK outlets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51925490 |title=Most UK cinemas shut after virus advice |work=BBC News |date=17 March 2020| access-date=18 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318014723/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51925490| archive-date=18 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Television and radio====\nTelevision programmes to be affected included forthcoming series of ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'' and ''[[Line of Duty]]'', which had their filming schedules delayed.<ref name=soaps/> On 13 March, [[ITV plc|ITV]] announced that the 2020 series finale of ''[[Ant & Dec's Saturday Night Takeaway]]'', scheduled to be broadcast from [[Walt Disney World]] in [[Florida]] would no longer go ahead after the resort announced its intention to close as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/13/ant-decs-saturday-night-takeaway-finale-walt-disney-world-florida-cancelled-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-12396126/ |title=Saturday Night Takeaway Walt Disney World finale in Florida cancelled |newspaper=Metro |publisher= |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314201437/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/13/ant-decs-saturday-night-takeaway-finale-walt-disney-world-florida-cancelled-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-12396126/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March, ITV announced that the filming schedule for its two soaps, ''[[Coronation Street]]'' and ''[[Emmerdale]]'' had not been affected by the pandemic, but said the programmes would \"remind people of important public health issues\" like hand-washing.<ref name=soaps>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51912510 |title=Coronavirus: Coronation Street and Emmerdale 'to remind about hand-washing' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317024423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51912510 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Two days later ITV said that the filming schedule for ''Coronation Street'' would change, and the number of weekly episodes be reduced,<ref name=EastEnders/> This was followed on 22 March by the announcement that filming would completely cease from the following day.<ref name=Lorraine>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-22/coronavirus-coronation-street-emmerdale-suspend-production-coronavirus-fears/ |title=Lorraine and Loose Women to stop live broadcasting as Coronation Street and Emmerdale suspend filming |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 18 March ITV announced the semi-final of the [[The Voice UK (series 9)|ninth series]] of ''[[The Voice UK]]'', scheduled for Saturday 28 March, would be postponed until later in the year.<ref name=Revamp>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51931050 |title=Coronavirus: BBC and ITV revamp broadcast plans amid outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318012425/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51931050 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the [[BBC]] delayed the implementation of its planned changes to [[Television licensing in the United Kingdom|TV licences]] for those aged over 75 from June to August.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316132508/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 25 March the BBC also announced that it would delay its plans to cut 450 news jobs due to the pressure of covering the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52035875 |title=BBC News suspends 450 job cuts to ensure Covid-19 coverage |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the BBC announced major changes to the schedule across the network. While programmes such as ''[[Politics Live]]'', ''[[Victoria Derbyshire (TV programme)|Victoria Derbyshire]]'', ''[[The Andrew Neil Show]]'', ''[[Newswatch (UK TV series)|Newswatch]]'', ''[[The Travel Show]]'' and ''[[HARDtalk]]'' were suspended, others such as ''[[Newsnight]]'' and ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]'' would continue with a smaller number of production staff. ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' would be moved to an earlier timeslot and be broadcast without an audience from a fixed location. Podcast programmes ''Americast'', ''Beyond Today'' and ''The Next Episode'' were also suspended.<ref name=BBC-changes/> On 18 March it was announced that filming on the sets of ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'', ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', ''[[EastEnders]]'', ''[[Holby City]]'', ''[[Pobol y Cwm]]'' and ''[[River City]]'' would be suspended. The broadcaster additionally announced that the number of weekly episodes of ''EastEnders'' would be reduced to ensure that it remained on screen for as long as possible.<ref name=EastEnders>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51943592 |title=Coronavirus: EastEnders, Casualty, Doctors and Holby City suspend filming |date=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318102224/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51943592 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The BBC also said that it would show more educational programmes to cater for children not attending school, and that it was in talks with the [[Department for Education (United Kingdom)|Department for Education]] and schools to support [[GCSE]] and [[A Level]] curriculums with extra programmes on [[BBC Four]] and the [[BBC Red Button]] service.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dave |last=Speck |url=https://www.tes.com/news/coronavirus-bbc-works-schools-offer-tv-lessons |title=Coronavirus: BBC works with schools to offer TV lessons |newspaper=Times Educational Supplement |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192711/https://www.tes.com/news/coronavirus-bbc-works-schools-offer-tv-lessons |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The BBC would also broadcast more programmes focused on health, fitness, education, religion and food recipes, while both the BBC and ITV would produce a weekly prime-time programme giving the public information about the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=Revamp/> On the same day the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020 Eurovision Song Contest]], scheduled to be held in [[Rotterdam]] in May, was also cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51870325 |title=Eurovision Song Contest 2020 cancelled over coronavirus |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140224/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51870325 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 22 March, ITV announced that its daytime programmes ''[[Lorraine (TV series)|Lorraine]]'' and ''[[Loose Women]]'' would cease live broadcasting from the following day.<ref name=Lorraine/>\n\nOn radio the [[BBC World Service]] programmes ''[[The World This Week]]'', ''[[World Update]]'' and ''Weekend'' were all suspended. Radio news summaries on [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]], [[BBC Radio 3|Radio 3]], [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] and [[BBC Radio 5 Live|Radio 5 Live]] were merged into a single output, with [[BBC 6 Music]] using the same script. The [[BBC Asian Network]] and ''[[Newsbeat]]'' worked together to maintain production of stories. ''[[Week in Westminster]]'' which broadcasts on Radio 4 was also suspended.<ref name=BBC-changes>{{Cite press release |title=BBC News sets out plans to keep audiences receiving trusted and accurate information |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/news-coronavirus |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318145141/https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/news-coronavirus |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 March, the BBC announced that its local radio stations in England would broadcast a virtual church service, led initially by the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], but with plans to expand religious services to cover other faiths.<ref name=Revamp/> On the same day [[Radio News Hub]], a radio news bulletin provider based in [[Leeds]] announced that it would produce a daily ten-minute programme giving a round-up of information about the pandemic and that would be made available free of charge to radio stations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2020/03/free-daily-coronavirus-news-round-up-available/ |title=Free daily coronavirus news round-up available |work=Radio Today |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182740/https://radiotoday.co.uk/2020/03/free-daily-coronavirus-news-round-up-available/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 March *28 March, [[BBC Local Radio]] announced that it had teamed up with manufacturers, retailers and the social isolation charity [[WaveLength]] to give away free [[Digital Audio Broadcasting|DAB]] radios to vulnerable people over the age of 70.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2020/03/bbc-to-give-away-dab-radios-for-some-over-70s/ |title=BBC to give away DAB radios to some over 70s |publisher=Radio Today |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Royal family===\nOn 4 March, the 93-year-old Queen [[Elizabeth II]] wore long gloves while awarding honours at a public [[investiture]] ceremony, prompting some to speculate the measure as a precaution against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foster |first1=Max |last2=Wilkinson |first2=David |last3=Guy |first3=Jack |title=Queen Elizabeth wears gloves, sparking coronavirus speculation |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/04/uk/queen-gloves-ceremony-scli-intl-gbr/index.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNN |date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen's long gloves at palace ceremony 'sensible precaution' |url=https://news.sky.com/story/queens-long-gloves-at-palace-ceremony-sensible-precaution-against-coronavirus-11948752 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Sky News |date=4 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March the Queen left London for [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Queen leaves London and moves to Windsor Castle amid outbreak |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/royal-family/queen-coronavirus-royal-family-cancelled-windsor-easter-buckingham-palace-a9406926.html |work=The Independent |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320163644/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/royal-family/queen-coronavirus-royal-family-cancelled-windsor-easter-buckingham-palace-a9406926.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day she issued a message to the nation noting that the country and the world was entering a period of great concern and uncertainty.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=A message from Her Majesty The Queen, 19th&nbsp;March 2020 |date=19 March 2020 |publisher=The Royal Household |url=https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-19th-march-2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319181434/https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-19th-march-2020 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Her grandsons Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|Harry]] both sent messages out via social media.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Heffer |first=Greg |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-prince-william-and-prince-harry-pay-tribute-to-awe-inspiring-public-response-11959943 |title=Coronavirus: Prince William and Prince Harry pay tribute to 'awe-inspiring' public response |date=19 March 2020 |work=Sky News |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319181423/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-prince-william-and-prince-harry-pay-tribute-to-awe-inspiring-public-response-11959943 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Princess Beatrice of York|Princess Beatrice]] cancelled her wedding reception at [[Buckingham Palace]] and took further advice on whether to carry on with a private [[Wedding of Princess Beatrice and Edoardo Mapelli Mozzi|wedding ceremony]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-princess-beatrice-cancels-buckingham-palace-wedding-reception-11959792 |title=Coronavirus: Princess Beatrice cancels Buckingham Palace wedding reception |date=18 March 2020 |work=Sky News |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318202959/https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-princess-beatrice-cancels-buckingham-palace-wedding-reception-11959792 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] greeted people with the [[Namaste]] hand gesture instead of a handshake at the Commonwealth Service at Westminster Abbey to avoid the spread of the virus, and did the same for the Prince's Trust Awards on 11 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince Charles greets investiture recipients with namaste amid coronavirus fears |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-12/prince-charles-meets-recipients-with-namaste-greeting-amid-coronavirus-fears-investiture-ceremony-at-buckingham-palace/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=ITV News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 10 March, Charles met [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco|Prince Albert of Monaco]], who later came down with the infection.<ref name=\"Charles3\">{{cite news |last2=Sykes |first2=Tom |first1=Jamie |last1=Ross |title=Fears for the Queen as Prince Charles Contracts COVID-19 |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/prince-charles-tests-positive-for-coronavirus |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The Daily Beast |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 25 March, it was announced that he had received a positive test result for COVID-19 and was suffering mild symptoms. He self-isolated at [[Birkhall]] on the [[Balmoral Castle]] estate.<ref name=\"Charles1\">{{cite news |title=Prince Charles tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52033845 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Charles2\">{{cite news |last1=Reynolds |first1=Emma |last2=Foster |first2=Max |last3=Wilkinson |first3=David |title=Prince Charles tests positive for novel coronavirus |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/25/europe/prince-charles-coronavirus-gbr-intl/index.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNN |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Concerns were raised for the health of the entire Royal Family, as well as concerns that he may have unwittingly become a [[super-spreader]] of the disease due to the vast number of people he regularly meets. Charles last saw the Queen on 12 March, just one day before the earliest date medical experts believe he would have been contagious.<ref name=\"Charles3\"/> The [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]] tested negative, but self-isolated with him.<ref name=\"Charles1\"/><ref name=\"Charles2\"/> On 30 March [[Clarence House]], the Prince's official residence, confirmed that he had come out of self-isolation after seven days having recovered from the illness.<ref name=\"Charles4\">{{cite news |title=Prince Charles out of virus self-isolation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52088684 |work=BBC News |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Charles5\">{{cite news |title=Prince Charles has recovered from coronavirus |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/royal-family/coronavirus-prince-charles-test-positive-recovered-self-isolation-royal-family-a9434951.html |work=The Independent |date=30 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March the [[William, Duke of Cambridge|Duke]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess of Cambridge]] gave their support to a [[Public Health England]] campaign to protect people's mental health during the outbreak. The campaign encourages people to stay in touch with family and friends via telephone and social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52081021|title=Royals back coronavirus mental health campaign|date=29 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n== Spread to other countries and territories ==\n[[Sophie Gr\u00e9goire Trudeau]], the wife of Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], tested positive for COVID-19 upon her return from [[WE Day]] events in the UK; on 12 March 2020 the Trudeau family entered two weeks of self-isolation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/gr%C3%A9goire-trudeau-self-isolating-1.5495419 |title=Sophie Gr\u00e9goire Trudeau's coronavirus infection comes after attending U.K. event |website=CBC News |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |first=John Paul |last=Tasker |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318154958/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/gr%C3%A9goire-trudeau-self-isolating-1.5495419|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first patient in Mauritius was a 59-year-old man who returned from the [[United Kingdom]] on 7 March 2020. When he arrived in Mauritius, the Mauritian had no symptoms.<ref name=\"Defi\">{{Cite news |url=https://defimedia.info/covid-19-trois-mauriciens-testes-positifs-zot-pe-gayn-tou-tretman-ki-bizin-rassure-le-pm |title=Covid-19 : trois Mauriciens test\u00e9s positifs ; \"zot pe gayn tou tretman ki bizin\", rassure le PM |date=19 March 2020 |work=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]] |first=St\u00e9phanie |last=Mompl\u00e9|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319191648/https://defimedia.info/covid-19-trois-mauriciens-testes-positifs-zot-pe-gayn-tou-tretman-ki-bizin-rassure-le-pm|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other cases of the novel coronavirus resulting from travel to the UK were subsequently reported in [[India]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/city-on-covid-19-map-teen-back-from-uk-tests-positive/articleshow/74682249.cms |title=Kolkata on Covid-19 map, teen back from UK tests positive |website=The Times of India |agency=Television News Network |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=2020-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319045040/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/city-on-covid-19-map-teen-back-from-uk-tests-positive/articleshow/74682249.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/live/2020/mar/19/covid-19-live--i-am-here-to-seek-from-you-your-next-few-weeks-says-pm-in-address-2118519.html |title=COVID-19 LIVE &#124; Telangana confirms 3 new cases, Andhra 1; PM calls for Janta curfew on Mar&nbsp;22 |website=The New Indian Express |publisher=Express Publications |at=08:09am; 10:58am; 04:16pm |date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319160403/https://www.newindianexpress.com/live/2020/mar/19/covid-19-live--i-am-here-to-seek-from-you-your-next-few-weeks-says-pm-in-address-2118519.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-51926323 |title=Coronavirus - Virus: Nigeria don confam new Covid-19 outbreak - See wetin we know so far |website=BBC News |language=Nigerian Pidgin |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe figures in the table below represent laboratory confirmed cases only; however, as indicated by the UK Government's [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Patrick Vallance|Sir Patrick Vallance]], it is likely that other cases in the UK are not reflected in these figures (on 12 March 2020 there were 596 confirmed cases, but the total number of cases was estimated at 5,000\u201310,000).<ref name=BBCNews12March2020>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: People with fever or 'continuous' cough told to self-isolate |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51857856 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News |agency=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313000134/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51857856 |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Death statistics are presented daily, but there may be a delay between death and it entering official statistics so families can be informed first. The delay is usually just a few days, but can be over a week.<ref name=itv-20200330>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-30/what-do-the-statistics-really-tell-us-about-uk-coronavirus-deaths/ |title=What do the statistics really tell us about UK coronavirus deaths? |work=ITV News |date=30 March 2020 |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKnown locations of death are shown in brackets.\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Kingdom medical cases}}\n\n==Graphs==\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=850\n|colors=#F46D43,#A50026,#C4ADA0,#C4ADB0,#C4ADC0\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x= 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1=20,23,35,39,51,87,116,164,209,280,321,384,460,586,798,1140,1391,1543,1950,2626,3269,3983,5018,5683,6650,8077,9529,11658,14543,17089,19522,22141,25150\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|y2=0,0,0,0,0,0,1,2,2,3,5,6,8,10,11,21,35,55,60,103,144,177,233,281,335,422,475,578,759,1019,1228,1408,1789\n|y2Title=Total deaths\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=850\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:1\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar,28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar\n|yAxisTitle=No. of new cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y=5, 3, 12, 4, 12, 36, 29, 48, 45, 69, 43, 61, 78, 136, 202, 342, 251, 152, 407, 676, 643, 714, 1035, 665, 967, 1427, 1452, 2129, 2885, 2546, 2433, 2619