{"title_page": "Tibor Rubin", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= blue buckaroo\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1929|6|18}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2015|12|5|1929|6|18}}\n|birth_place= [[P\u00e1szt\u00f3]], Hungary\n|death_place= [[Garden Grove, California]], U.S.\n|placeofburial= [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]]<br>[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= TiborRubin.jpg\n|medal=cmoh army.jpg\n|medal_size = 50px\n|caption= Tibor Rubin wearing the Medal of Honor he received at the White House.\n|nickname=Ted\n|allegiance= [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1950\u20131953\n|rank= [[Corporal#United States|Corporal]]\n|unit=Company I, [[8th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|8th Cavalry Regiment]], [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|First Cavalry Division]]\n|battles= [[Korean War]]\n|awards= [[Medal of Honor]]<br/>[[Purple Heart]] (2)\n|spouse= {{marriage|Yvonne Meyers|January 27, 1963}}\n|children= 2\n}}\n'''Tibor \"Ted\" Rubin''' (June 18, 1929 \u2013 December 5, 2015) was a Hungarian-born [[United States Army]] soldier. A [[Holocaust]] survivor who emigrated to the [[United States]] in 1948, he fought in the [[Korean War]] and was awarded the [[Medal of Honor]] for his actions during the war, as a combatant and a [[prisoner of war]] (POW).\n\nRubin received the award from President [[George W. Bush]] on September 23, 2005, 55 years after the Korean war.<ref name=GWB>{{cite web\n | date= September 23, 2005 \n | title= President Presents Medal of Honor to Corporal Tibor \"Ted\" Rubin \n | url= https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2005/09/20050923-2.html\n | publisher= Presidential Archive for George W. Bush\n | accessdate= December 5, 2014\n}}</ref> Rubin was repeatedly nominated for various [[military decorations]], but was overlooked because of [[antisemitism]] by a superior.<ref name=army.mil>{{cite web\n | title= An American Hero\n | author= Beth Reece\n | url= http://www.army.mil/medalofhonor/rubin/citation/printable.html\n | publisher= Army.mil\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref> Fellow soldiers who filed affidavits supporting Rubin's nomination for the Medal of Honor said that Rubin's sergeant \"was an anti-Semite who gave Rubin dangerous assignments in hopes of getting him killed\".<ref name=AP>{{cite news\n | date= September 23, 2005\n | author= Erica Werner\n | title= Jewish Vet Gets Medal of Honor 55 Years On\n | publisher= [[Associated Press]]\n | url= http://crownheights.info/general/656/jewish-vet-gets-medal-of-honor-55-years-on/\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref><!--see talk page--> In November, 2016, President Obama signed legislation renaming the Long Beach California VA Medical Center after Rubin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lbpost.com/news/2000010042-house-passes-legislation-that-could-name-long-beach-va-medical-center-after-socal-war-hero?bt_alias=eyJ1c2VySWQiOiAiYzUwMmM5NzctNGJhZi00ZmVhLTkzNDAtM2VkZjUxNjJkOGRiIn0=|title=President Obama Signs Legislation Renaming Long Beach VA Medical Center After SoCal War Hero|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRubin was born on June 18, 1929, in [[P\u00e1szt\u00f3]], a Hungarian town with a [[Jewish]] population of 120 families, one of six children (by three marriages<ref name=Post>{{cite news |title=Tibor \u2018Teddy\u2019 Rubin, who received Medal of Honor for one-man assault in Korea, dies at 86 |author=Adam Bernstein |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=December 8, 2015 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tibor-teddy-rubin-who-received-medal-of-honor-for-one-man-assault-in-korea-dies-at-86/2015/12/08/601402d2-9dc3-11e5-a3c5-c77f2cc5a43c_story.html}}</ref>) of shoemaker Ferenc Rubin.<ref name=JJ>{{cite web\n |date        = May 16, 2002\n |title       = Pentagon Reviews Jewish Veteran Files: Were Tibor Rubin and 137 other soldiers denied the Medal of Honor because of anti-Semitism?\n |author      = Tom Tugend\n |publisher   = [[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|The Jewish Journal]]\n |url         = http://www.jewishjournal.com/home/preview.php?id=8584\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20051027083155/http://www.jewishjournal.com/home/preview.php?id=8584\n |archivedate = October 27, 2005\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen Tibor was 13, Ferenc and Rosa Rubin (stepmother<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tibor-teddy-rubin-who-received-medal-of-honor-for-one-man-assault-in-korea-dies-at-86/2015/12/08/601402d2-9dc3-11e5-a3c5-c77f2cc5a43c_story.html|title = Medal of Honor recipient Tibor Rubin dies at 86|newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]]|date = December 7, 2015}}</ref>) tried to send him to safety in neutral Switzerland, but he was caught and sent to the [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen concentration camp]] in Austria. He was liberated 14 months later by American combat troops. Both of his parents and his two sisters perished in the [[Holocaust]].<ref name=AP/>\n\n==Emigration to the United States==\nRubin entered the United States in 1948, settled in New York and worked first as a shoemaker. He then apprenticed as a butcher at Michael Bela Wilhelm's Hungarian butcher shop on Third Avenue in the [[Yorkville, Manhattan|Yorkville]] neighborhood for about a year.\n\nIn 1949, he tried to enlist in the U.S. Army. He failed the English language test, but tried again in 1950 and passed with some judicious help from two fellow test-takers.<ref name=Prescott1>{{cite news\n | date= April 30, 2008\n | author= Lewis LaMaster\n | title= Tibor Rubin: An Evening of Remembrance\n | publisher= Prescott eNews\n | url= http://www.prescottenews.com/index.php/news/current-news/item/14113-tibor-rubin-an-evening-of-remembrance\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n==Antisemitism in the army==\nBy July 1950, [[Private First Class]] Rubin found himself fighting in South Korea with I Company, [[8th Cavalry Regiment]], [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|First Cavalry Division]].<ref name=AMOHW /> According to lengthy affidavits submitted by nearly a dozen men who served with Rubin in South and North Korea, mostly self-described \"country boys\" from the South and Midwest, an antisemitic sergeant named Arthur Peyton consistently \"volunteered\" Rubin for the most dangerous patrols and missions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Daniel|title=Single Handed: The Inspiring True Story of Tibor \"Teddy\" Rubin \u2013 Holocaust Survivor, Korean War Hero, and Medal of Honor Recipient|publisher=The Berkley Publishing Group|isbn=0425279758}}</ref><ref name=Prescott2>{{cite news\n | date= May 2, 2008\n | author= Lynne LaMaster\n | title= Corporal Tibor Rubin visits the VA Medical Center in Prescott\n | publisher= Prescott eNews\n | url= http://www.prescottenews.com/index.php/feeds/item/14875-corporal-tibor-rubin-visits-the-va-medical-center-in-prescott\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring one mission, according to the testimonies of his comrades, Rubin secured a needed route of retreat for his rifle company by single-handedly defending a hill for 24 hours against waves of North Korean soldiers. For this and other acts of bravery, Rubin was recommended four times for the Medal of Honor by two of his commanding officers. Both officers were killed in action shortly afterwards, but not before ordering Rubin's sergeant to begin the necessary paperwork recommending Rubin for the Medal of Honor. Some of Rubin's comrades were present and witnessed the order being issued, and all are convinced that Peyton deliberately ignored his orders. \"I really believe, in my heart, that [the sergeant] would have jeopardized his own safety rather than assist in any way whatsoever in the awarding of the Medal of Honor to a person of Jewish descent\", wrote Corporal Harold Speakman in a notarized affidavit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/sep/24/nation/na-medal24 |title=Holocaust Survivor Awarded Medal of Honor |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=2005-09-24 |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Chinese POW camp==\nTowards the end of October 1950, massive Chinese troop concentrations had crossed the border into North Korea and were attacking the unprepared American troops now trapped far inside North Korea. Most of Rubin's regiment had been killed or captured. Rubin, severely wounded, was captured and spent the next 30 months in a [[prisoner of war]] camp.\n\nFaced with constant hunger, filth, and disease, most of the GIs simply gave up. \"No one wanted to help anyone. Everybody was for himself\", wrote Leo A. Cormier Jr., a former sergeant and POW. The exception was Rubin. Almost every evening, Rubin would sneak out of the prison camp to steal food from the Chinese and North Korean supply depots, knowing that he would be shot if caught. \"He shared the food evenly among the GIs,\" Cormier wrote. \"He also took care of us, nursed us, carried us to the latrine..., he did many good deeds, which he told us were [[mitzvah]]s in the Jewish tradition... he was a very religious Jew and helping his fellow men was the most important thing to him\". The survivors of the prison war camp credited Rubin with keeping them alive and saving at least 40 American soldiers.<ref name=army.mil />\n\nRubin refused his captors' repeated offers of repatriation to Hungary, by then behind the [[Iron Curtain]].\n\n==Awards and Decorations==\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|[[File:Combat Infantry Badge.svg|200px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Medal_of_Honor_ribbon.svg|width=110}} {{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|other_device=|ribbon=Purple Heart ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|other_device=|ribbon=Prisoner_of_War_Medal_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Army_of_Occupation_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=4|type=service-star|ribbon=Korean_Service_Medal_-_Ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|other_device=|ribbon=United Nations Service Medal Korea ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|other_device=|ribbon=Republic of Korea War Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"12\" align=\"center\" | [[Combat Infantryman Badge]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\"| [[Medal of Honor]]\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\"| [[Purple Heart]]<br>w/ 1 bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Prisoner of War Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Army of Occupation Medal]]<br>w/ 'Japan' clasp \n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[National Defense Service Medal]] \n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Korean Service Medal]]<br>w/ 4 bronze [[campaign star]]s\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[United Nations Korea Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Korean War Service Medal]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Korean_Presidential_Unit_Citation.png|width=110}}\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"12\" align=\"center\" | [[Republic of Korea Presidential Unit Citation]]<br>(Army Version)\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Medal of Honor===\nIn 1993, a study was commissioned by the United States Army to investigate racial discrimination in the awarding of medals. In 2001, after considering the case of [[Leonard M. Kravitz]], Congress directed the military to further review certain cases. The ensuing investigation showed that Rubin had been the subject of discrimination due to his religion and should have received the Medal of Honor.<ref name=JJ /><ref name=\"JewishLib\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/tibor_rubin.html|title=Tibor Rubin|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=July 21, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, President George W. Bush presented the Medal of Honor to Rubin in a ceremony at the [[White House]], for his actions in 1950 during the Korean War.<ref name=\"GWB\"/>\n\n===Citation===\n{{quotation|[[File:Medal of Honor flag.png|150px|right|alt=Medal of Honor flag]] For conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty: Corporal Tibor Rubin distinguished himself by extraordinary heroism during the period from July 23, 1950, to April 20, 1953, while serving as a rifleman with Company I, [[8th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|8th Cavalry Regiment]], [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] in the Republic of Korea.  While his unit was retreating to the Pusan Perimeter, Corporal Rubin was assigned to stay behind to keep open the vital Taegu-Pusan Road link used by his withdrawing unit. During the ensuing battle, overwhelming numbers of North Korean troops assaulted a hill defended solely by Corporal Rubin.  He inflicted a staggering number of casualties on the attacking force during his personal 24-hour battle, single-handedly slowing the enemy advance and allowing the 8th Cavalry Regiment to complete its withdrawal successfully. Following the breakout from the Pusan Perimeter, the 8th Cavalry Regiment proceeded northward and advanced into North Korea. During the advance, he helped capture several hundred North Korean soldiers. On October 30, 1950, Chinese forces attacked his unit at [[Unsan]], North Korea, during a massive nighttime assault. That night and throughout the next day, he manned a .30 caliber machine gun at the south end of the unit's line after three previous gunners became casualties. He continued to man his machine gun until his ammunition was exhausted. His determined stand slowed the pace of the enemy advance in his sector, permitting the remnants of his unit to retreat southward. As the battle raged, Corporal Rubin was severely wounded and captured by the Chinese. Choosing to remain in the prison camp despite offers from the Chinese to return him to his native Hungary, Corporal Rubin disregarded his own personal safety and immediately began sneaking out of the camp at night in search of food for his comrades. Breaking into enemy food storehouses and gardens, he risked certain torture or death if caught. Corporal Rubin provided not only food to the starving Soldiers, but also desperately needed medical care and moral support for the sick and wounded of the POW camp. His brave, selfless efforts were directly attributed to saving the lives of as many as forty of his fellow prisoners. Corporal Rubin's gallant actions in close contact with the enemy and unyielding courage and bravery while a prisoner of war are in the highest traditions of military service and reflect great credit upon himself and the United States Army.<ref name=AMOHW>{{cite web\n|accessdate=2014-12-05\n|url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/koreanwar.html#RUBIN\n|title = Medal of Honor Recipients \u2013 Korean War: Tibor Rubin\n|publisher= [[United States Army Center of Military History]]}}</ref>}}\n\n==Later life and death==\nAfter his military service, he worked in his brother's Long Beach liquor store.<ref name=LATimes/> Rubin was a resident of [[Garden Grove, California]].<ref name=OCR>{{cite news\n | date= October 18, 2005\n | title= Medal of Honor recipient just did duty\n | author= Nguyen Huy Vu\n | url= http://www.ocregister.com/news/medal-207819-honor-rubin.html\n | publisher= [[Orange County Register]]\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n | quote= Mr. Rubin recommends not harboring hatred even with all his suffering and loss: \"If you feel hate for your fellow man ... you'll only hurt yourself...\"\n}}</ref>\n\nHe regularly volunteered at the Long Beach Veterans Hospital; having earned an award for more than 20,000 hours of volunteer work. On May 10, 2017, the Medical Center was renamed in his honor as the \"Tibor Rubin VA Medical Center\".<ref name=VALBC>{{cite news\n | date= May 10, 2017\n | title= Medical Center in Long Beach Named for Corporal Tibor Rubin\n | author= Michelle Spivak\n | url= https://www.longbeach.va.gov/about/tibor_rubin.asp\n | publisher= [[U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs]]\n | accessdate= June 21, 2018\n | quote=\n}}</ref>\n\nRubin died December 5, 2015, at his home in Garden Grove.<ref name=\"LATimes\" /> He was survived by his wife Yvonne and their two children, Frank and Rosie.<ref name=\"LATimes\" />\n\n==''Finnigan's War''==\nTibor Rubin is one of the Korean War heroes honored in the 2013 documentary ''Finnigan's War'', directed by Conor Timmis.  Rubin recalls his Holocaust experience and Korean War POW experience.  Rubin's interview is intercut with footage of President George W. Bush telling Rubin's life story during his 2005 Medal of Honor ceremony.  Actor Mark Hamill narrates Rubin's Medal of Honor citation in the film.  Filmmaker Conor Timmis was greatly impressed by Rubin's positive attitude and sense of humor despite all the suffering he endured during his life.<ref>{{cite web\n|last= Timmis |first=Conor\n|url=  https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1854531/\n|title= Finnigan's War}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[List of Korean War Medal of Honor recipients]]\n* [[List of Jewish Medal of Honor recipients]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Cohen, Daniel M. (2015). ''Single Handed: The Inspiring True Story of Tibor \"Teddy\" Rubin, Holocaust Survivor, Korean War Hero, and Medal of Honor Recipient''. New York: Berkley Caliber, {{ISBN|978-0425279755}} {{OCLC|900559301}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/23/AR2005092301699.html Jewish Vet Gets Medal of Honor 55 Years On] Josh White, ''[[The Washington Post]]'', September 24, 2005\n* [http://www.fau.edu/library/br129.htm Tibor Rubin: An Unusual Hero of The Korean War]\n\n=== Videos ===\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?189010-1/medal-honor-presentation Video of Medal of Honor Presentation] by George W. Bush, September 23, 2005, from [[CSPAN]]\n* [http://www.army.mil/medalofhonor/rubin/video/index.html List of Videos for Medal of Honor Recipient Corporal Tibor Rubin], U.S. Army website\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gTnmDQVMank Tibor Rubin \u2013 Medal of Honor, Korean War], [[Artisan Books]] and the Congressional Medal of Honor Foundation\n\n{{ACMH}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rubin, Tibor}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from P\u00e1szt\u00f3]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American prisoners of war in the Korean War]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Foreign-born Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Korean War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Hungarian-born Medal of Honor recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Tibor Rubin\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1929|6|18}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2015|12|5|1929|6|18}}\n|birth_place= [[P\u00e1szt\u00f3]], Hungary\n|death_place= [[Garden Grove, California]], U.S.\n|placeofburial= [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]]<br>[[Los Angeles, California]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= TiborRubin.jpg\n|medal=cmoh army.jpg\n|medal_size = 50px\n|caption= Tibor Rubin wearing the Medal of Honor he received at the White House.\n|nickname=Ted\n|allegiance= [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1950\u20131953\n|rank= [[Corporal#United States|Corporal]]\n|unit=Company I, [[8th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|8th Cavalry Regiment]], [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|First Cavalry Division]]\n|battles= [[Korean War]]\n|awards= [[Medal of Honor]]<br/>[[Purple Heart]] (2)\n|spouse= {{marriage|Yvonne Meyers|January 27, 1963}}\n|children= 2\n}}\n'''Tibor \"Ted\" Rubin''' (June 18, 1929 \u2013 December 5, 2015) was a Hungarian-born [[United States Army]] soldier. A [[Holocaust]] survivor who emigrated to the [[United States]] in 1948, he fought in the [[Korean War]] and was awarded the [[Medal of Honor]] for his actions during the war, as a combatant and a [[prisoner of war]] (POW).\n\nRubin received the award from President [[George W. Bush]] on September 23, 2005, 55 years after the Korean war.<ref name=GWB>{{cite web\n | date= September 23, 2005 \n | title= President Presents Medal of Honor to Corporal Tibor \"Ted\" Rubin \n | url= https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2005/09/20050923-2.html\n | publisher= Presidential Archive for George W. Bush\n | accessdate= December 5, 2014\n}}</ref> Rubin was repeatedly nominated for various [[military decorations]], but was overlooked because of [[antisemitism]] by a superior.<ref name=army.mil>{{cite web\n | title= An American Hero\n | author= Beth Reece\n | url= http://www.army.mil/medalofhonor/rubin/citation/printable.html\n | publisher= Army.mil\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref> Fellow soldiers who filed affidavits supporting Rubin's nomination for the Medal of Honor said that Rubin's sergeant \"was an anti-Semite who gave Rubin dangerous assignments in hopes of getting him killed\".<ref name=AP>{{cite news\n | date= September 23, 2005\n | author= Erica Werner\n | title= Jewish Vet Gets Medal of Honor 55 Years On\n | publisher= [[Associated Press]]\n | url= http://crownheights.info/general/656/jewish-vet-gets-medal-of-honor-55-years-on/\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref><!--see talk page--> In November, 2016, President Obama signed legislation renaming the Long Beach California VA Medical Center after Rubin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lbpost.com/news/2000010042-house-passes-legislation-that-could-name-long-beach-va-medical-center-after-socal-war-hero?bt_alias=eyJ1c2VySWQiOiAiYzUwMmM5NzctNGJhZi00ZmVhLTkzNDAtM2VkZjUxNjJkOGRiIn0=|title=President Obama Signs Legislation Renaming Long Beach VA Medical Center After SoCal War Hero|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRubin was born on June 18, 1929, in [[P\u00e1szt\u00f3]], a Hungarian town with a [[Jewish]] population of 120 families, one of six children (by three marriages<ref name=Post>{{cite news |title=Tibor \u2018Teddy\u2019 Rubin, who received Medal of Honor for one-man assault in Korea, dies at 86 |author=Adam Bernstein |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=December 8, 2015 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tibor-teddy-rubin-who-received-medal-of-honor-for-one-man-assault-in-korea-dies-at-86/2015/12/08/601402d2-9dc3-11e5-a3c5-c77f2cc5a43c_story.html}}</ref>) of shoemaker Ferenc Rubin.<ref name=JJ>{{cite web\n |date        = May 16, 2002\n |title       = Pentagon Reviews Jewish Veteran Files: Were Tibor Rubin and 137 other soldiers denied the Medal of Honor because of anti-Semitism?\n |author      = Tom Tugend\n |publisher   = [[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|The Jewish Journal]]\n |url         = http://www.jewishjournal.com/home/preview.php?id=8584\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20051027083155/http://www.jewishjournal.com/home/preview.php?id=8584\n |archivedate = October 27, 2005\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen Tibor was 13, Ferenc and Rosa Rubin (stepmother<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tibor-teddy-rubin-who-received-medal-of-honor-for-one-man-assault-in-korea-dies-at-86/2015/12/08/601402d2-9dc3-11e5-a3c5-c77f2cc5a43c_story.html|title = Medal of Honor recipient Tibor Rubin dies at 86|newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]]|date = December 7, 2015}}</ref>) tried to send him to safety in neutral Switzerland, but he was caught and sent to the [[Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp|Mauthausen concentration camp]] in Austria. He was liberated 14 months later by American combat troops. Both of his parents and his two sisters perished in the [[Holocaust]].<ref name=AP/>\n\n==Emigration to the United States==\nRubin entered the United States in 1948, settled in New York and worked first as a shoemaker. He then apprenticed as a butcher at Michael Bela Wilhelm's Hungarian butcher shop on Third Avenue in the [[Yorkville, Manhattan|Yorkville]] neighborhood for about a year.\n\nIn 1949, he tried to enlist in the U.S. Army. He failed the English language test, but tried again in 1950 and passed with some judicious help from two fellow test-takers.<ref name=Prescott1>{{cite news\n | date= April 30, 2008\n | author= Lewis LaMaster\n | title= Tibor Rubin: An Evening of Remembrance\n | publisher= Prescott eNews\n | url= http://www.prescottenews.com/index.php/news/current-news/item/14113-tibor-rubin-an-evening-of-remembrance\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n==Antisemitism in the army==\nBy July 1950, [[Private First Class]] Rubin found himself fighting in South Korea with I Company, [[8th Cavalry Regiment]], [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|First Cavalry Division]].<ref name=AMOHW /> According to lengthy affidavits submitted by nearly a dozen men who served with Rubin in South and North Korea, mostly self-described \"country boys\" from the South and Midwest, an antisemitic sergeant named Arthur Peyton consistently \"volunteered\" Rubin for the most dangerous patrols and missions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Daniel|title=Single Handed: The Inspiring True Story of Tibor \"Teddy\" Rubin \u2013 Holocaust Survivor, Korean War Hero, and Medal of Honor Recipient|publisher=The Berkley Publishing Group|isbn=0425279758}}</ref><ref name=Prescott2>{{cite news\n | date= May 2, 2008\n | author= Lynne LaMaster\n | title= Corporal Tibor Rubin visits the VA Medical Center in Prescott\n | publisher= Prescott eNews\n | url= http://www.prescottenews.com/index.php/feeds/item/14875-corporal-tibor-rubin-visits-the-va-medical-center-in-prescott\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring one mission, according to the testimonies of his comrades, Rubin secured a needed route of retreat for his rifle company by single-handedly defending a hill for 24 hours against waves of North Korean soldiers. For this and other acts of bravery, Rubin was recommended four times for the Medal of Honor by two of his commanding officers. Both officers were killed in action shortly afterwards, but not before ordering Rubin's sergeant to begin the necessary paperwork recommending Rubin for the Medal of Honor. Some of Rubin's comrades were present and witnessed the order being issued, and all are convinced that Peyton deliberately ignored his orders. \"I really believe, in my heart, that [the sergeant] would have jeopardized his own safety rather than assist in any way whatsoever in the awarding of the Medal of Honor to a person of Jewish descent\", wrote Corporal Harold Speakman in a notarized affidavit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/sep/24/nation/na-medal24 |title=Holocaust Survivor Awarded Medal of Honor |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=2005-09-24 |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Chinese POW camp==\nTowards the end of October 1950, massive Chinese troop concentrations had crossed the border into North Korea and were attacking the unprepared American troops now trapped far inside North Korea. Most of Rubin's regiment had been killed or captured. Rubin, severely wounded, was captured and spent the next 30 months in a [[prisoner of war]] camp.\n\nFaced with constant hunger, filth, and disease, most of the GIs simply gave up. \"No one wanted to help anyone. Everybody was for himself\", wrote Leo A. Cormier Jr., a former sergeant and POW. The exception was Rubin. Almost every evening, Rubin would sneak out of the prison camp to steal food from the Chinese and North Korean supply depots, knowing that he would be shot if caught. \"He shared the food evenly among the GIs,\" Cormier wrote. \"He also took care of us, nursed us, carried us to the latrine..., he did many good deeds, which he told us were [[mitzvah]]s in the Jewish tradition... he was a very religious Jew and helping his fellow men was the most important thing to him\". The survivors of the prison war camp credited Rubin with keeping them alive and saving at least 40 American soldiers.<ref name=army.mil />\n\nRubin refused his captors' repeated offers of repatriation to Hungary, by then behind the [[Iron Curtain]].\n\n==Awards and Decorations==\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|[[File:Combat Infantry Badge.svg|200px]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Medal_of_Honor_ribbon.svg|width=110}} {{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|other_device=|ribbon=Purple Heart ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|other_device=|ribbon=Prisoner_of_War_Medal_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Army_of_Occupation_ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=4|type=service-star|ribbon=Korean_Service_Medal_-_Ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|other_device=|ribbon=United Nations Service Medal Korea ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=award-star|other_device=|ribbon=Republic of Korea War Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=110}}\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"12\" align=\"center\" | [[Combat Infantryman Badge]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\"| [[Medal of Honor]]\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\"| [[Purple Heart]]<br>w/ 1 bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Prisoner of War Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Army of Occupation Medal]]<br>w/ 'Japan' clasp \n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[National Defense Service Medal]] \n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Korean Service Medal]]<br>w/ 4 bronze [[campaign star]]s\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[United Nations Korea Medal]]\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"| [[Korean War Service Medal]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |{{Ribbon devices|number=|type=oak|ribbon=Korean_Presidential_Unit_Citation.png|width=110}}\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"12\" align=\"center\" | [[Republic of Korea Presidential Unit Citation]]<br>(Army Version)\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Medal of Honor===\nIn 1993, a study was commissioned by the United States Army to investigate racial discrimination in the awarding of medals. In 2001, after considering the case of [[Leonard M. Kravitz]], Congress directed the military to further review certain cases. The ensuing investigation showed that Rubin had been the subject of discrimination due to his religion and should have received the Medal of Honor.<ref name=JJ /><ref name=\"JewishLib\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/tibor_rubin.html|title=Tibor Rubin|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=July 21, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, President George W. Bush presented the Medal of Honor to Rubin in a ceremony at the [[White House]], for his actions in 1950 during the Korean War.<ref name=\"GWB\"/>\n\n===Citation===\n{{quotation|[[File:Medal of Honor flag.png|150px|right|alt=Medal of Honor flag]] For conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty: Corporal Tibor Rubin distinguished himself by extraordinary heroism during the period from July 23, 1950, to April 20, 1953, while serving as a rifleman with Company I, [[8th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|8th Cavalry Regiment]], [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] in the Republic of Korea.  While his unit was retreating to the Pusan Perimeter, Corporal Rubin was assigned to stay behind to keep open the vital Taegu-Pusan Road link used by his withdrawing unit. During the ensuing battle, overwhelming numbers of North Korean troops assaulted a hill defended solely by Corporal Rubin.  He inflicted a staggering number of casualties on the attacking force during his personal 24-hour battle, single-handedly slowing the enemy advance and allowing the 8th Cavalry Regiment to complete its withdrawal successfully. Following the breakout from the Pusan Perimeter, the 8th Cavalry Regiment proceeded northward and advanced into North Korea. During the advance, he helped capture several hundred North Korean soldiers. On October 30, 1950, Chinese forces attacked his unit at [[Unsan]], North Korea, during a massive nighttime assault. That night and throughout the next day, he manned a .30 caliber machine gun at the south end of the unit's line after three previous gunners became casualties. He continued to man his machine gun until his ammunition was exhausted. His determined stand slowed the pace of the enemy advance in his sector, permitting the remnants of his unit to retreat southward. As the battle raged, Corporal Rubin was severely wounded and captured by the Chinese. Choosing to remain in the prison camp despite offers from the Chinese to return him to his native Hungary, Corporal Rubin disregarded his own personal safety and immediately began sneaking out of the camp at night in search of food for his comrades. Breaking into enemy food storehouses and gardens, he risked certain torture or death if caught. Corporal Rubin provided not only food to the starving Soldiers, but also desperately needed medical care and moral support for the sick and wounded of the POW camp. His brave, selfless efforts were directly attributed to saving the lives of as many as forty of his fellow prisoners. Corporal Rubin's gallant actions in close contact with the enemy and unyielding courage and bravery while a prisoner of war are in the highest traditions of military service and reflect great credit upon himself and the United States Army.<ref name=AMOHW>{{cite web\n|accessdate=2014-12-05\n|url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/koreanwar.html#RUBIN\n|title = Medal of Honor Recipients \u2013 Korean War: Tibor Rubin\n|publisher= [[United States Army Center of Military History]]}}</ref>}}\n\n==Later life and death==\nAfter his military service, he worked in his brother's Long Beach liquor store.<ref name=LATimes/> Rubin was a resident of [[Garden Grove, California]].<ref name=OCR>{{cite news\n | date= October 18, 2005\n | title= Medal of Honor recipient just did duty\n | author= Nguyen Huy Vu\n | url= http://www.ocregister.com/news/medal-207819-honor-rubin.html\n | publisher= [[Orange County Register]]\n | accessdate= December 12, 2014\n | quote= Mr. Rubin recommends not harboring hatred even with all his suffering and loss: \"If you feel hate for your fellow man ... you'll only hurt yourself...\"\n}}</ref>\n\nHe regularly volunteered at the Long Beach Veterans Hospital; having earned an award for more than 20,000 hours of volunteer work. On May 10, 2017, the Medical Center was renamed in his honor as the \"Tibor Rubin VA Medical Center\".<ref name=VALBC>{{cite news\n | date= May 10, 2017\n | title= Medical Center in Long Beach Named for Corporal Tibor Rubin\n | author= Michelle Spivak\n | url= https://www.longbeach.va.gov/about/tibor_rubin.asp\n | publisher= [[U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs]]\n | accessdate= June 21, 2018\n | quote=\n}}</ref>\n\nRubin died December 5, 2015, at his home in Garden Grove.<ref name=\"LATimes\" /> He was survived by his wife Yvonne and their two children, Frank and Rosie.<ref name=\"LATimes\" />\n\n==''Finnigan's War''==\nTibor Rubin is one of the Korean War heroes honored in the 2013 documentary ''Finnigan's War'', directed by Conor Timmis.  Rubin recalls his Holocaust experience and Korean War POW experience.  Rubin's interview is intercut with footage of President George W. Bush telling Rubin's life story during his 2005 Medal of Honor ceremony.  Actor Mark Hamill narrates Rubin's Medal of Honor citation in the film.  Filmmaker Conor Timmis was greatly impressed by Rubin's positive attitude and sense of humor despite all the suffering he endured during his life.<ref>{{cite web\n|last= Timmis |first=Conor\n|url=  https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1854531/\n|title= Finnigan's War}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[List of Korean War Medal of Honor recipients]]\n* [[List of Jewish Medal of Honor recipients]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Cohen, Daniel M. (2015). ''Single Handed: The Inspiring True Story of Tibor \"Teddy\" Rubin, Holocaust Survivor, Korean War Hero, and Medal of Honor Recipient''. New York: Berkley Caliber, {{ISBN|978-0425279755}} {{OCLC|900559301}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/23/AR2005092301699.html Jewish Vet Gets Medal of Honor 55 Years On] Josh White, ''[[The Washington Post]]'', September 24, 2005\n* [http://www.fau.edu/library/br129.htm Tibor Rubin: An Unusual Hero of The Korean War]\n\n=== Videos ===\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?189010-1/medal-honor-presentation Video of Medal of Honor Presentation] by George W. Bush, September 23, 2005, from [[CSPAN]]\n* [http://www.army.mil/medalofhonor/rubin/video/index.html List of Videos for Medal of Honor Recipient Corporal Tibor Rubin], U.S. Army website\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gTnmDQVMank Tibor Rubin \u2013 Medal of Honor, Korean War], [[Artisan Books]] and the Congressional Medal of Honor Foundation\n\n{{ACMH}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rubin, Tibor}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from P\u00e1szt\u00f3]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American prisoners of war in the Korean War]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Foreign-born Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Korean War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Hungarian-born Medal of Honor recipients]]\n", "name_user": "2601:206:8201:2f0:a17f:ecb1:ebe3:3a69", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(changed name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tibor_Rubin"}
{"title_page": "Joseph Dervaes", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Joseph Dervaes\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Joseph Dervaes\n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1906|10|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Wetteren]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1986|4|12|1906|10|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Ghent]], Belgium\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n| updated        = \n}}\n'''Joseph Dervaes''' (27 October 1906&nbsp;\u2013 12 April 1986) was a Belgian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"procyclingstats\">{{cite web |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=183296 |title=Joseph Dervaes |accessdate=29 April 2014 |work=Pro Cycling Stats}}</ref> He won the [[Belgian National Road Race Championships|Belgian national road race title]] in 1928 and the [[Tour of Flanders]] in 1929.<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8907 |title=Joseph Dervaes |accessdate=29 April 2014 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|8907}}\n\n{{Tour of Flanders winners}}\n{{Belgian National Road Race Championships (men)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dervaes, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Wetteren]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from East Flanders]]\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1900s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Joseph Dervaes\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Joseph Dervaes\n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1906|10|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Wetteren]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1986|4|12|1906|10|27|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Ghent]], Belgium\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n| updated        = \n}}\n'''Joseph Dervaes''' (27 October 1906&nbsp;\u2013 12 April 1986) was a Belgian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"procyclingstats\">{{cite web |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=183296 |title=Joseph Dervaes |accessdate=29 April 2014 |work=Pro Cycling Stats}}</ref> He won the [[Belgian National Road Race Championships|Belgian national road race title]] in 1928 and the [[Tour of Flanders]] in 1929.<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=8907 |title=Joseph Dervaes |accessdate=29 April 2014 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|8907}}\n\n{{Tour of Flanders winners}}\n{{Belgian National Road Race Championships (men)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dervaes, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Wetteren]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from East Flanders]]\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1900s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Dervaes"}
{"title_page": "WP Suspension", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = WP Suspension GmbH\n| logo = WP Suspension logo.svg\n| logo_alt = Logo of the company WP Suspension\n| former_name = White Power Suspension\n| type = [[Companies with limited liability in German speaking countries|GmbH]]\n| industry = [[Motorcycle]]\n| founded = 1977\n| founder = Wim Peters\n| hq_location_city = [[Mattighofen]]\n| hq_location_country = Austria\n| products = Motorcycle suspension components\n| parent = [[KTM|KTM AG]]\n| website = {{URL|www.wp-suspension.com}}\n}}[[File:White power suspension.jpg|alt=WP rear shock unit|thumb|WP rear shock unit on a [[KTM 950 Adventure]]]]'''WP Suspension GmbH''' is a manufacturer of components for [[motorcycle suspension]] systems based in Austrian. The company was founded in 1977 as ''White Power Suspension [[Besloten vennootschap|B.V.]]'' in [[Malden, Netherlands|Malden]], Netherlands, by Wim Peters,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cycleworld.com/2015/04/22/wp-factory-dutch-suspension-manufacturer-tour/|title=WP Factory Tour|last=Catterson|first=Brian|date=2015-04-22|website=Cycle World|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> and is amongst the largest manufacturers of suspension components for [[Motorcycle|motorcycles]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorradonline.de/zubehoer/portraet-wp-suspension-wp-suspension/|title=Portr\u00e4t: WP Suspension|last=Herder|first=Klaus|date=2010-08-19|website=Motorrad Online|publisher=Motorrad Magazine|language=DE|trans-title=Portrait: WP Suspension|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> It is today a [[Wholly Owned Subsidiary|wholly owned subsidiary]] of [[KTM|KTM AG]].\n\n== Company History ==\nDutch motocross rider Wim Peters had a serious crash in a race in 1975, needing over a year for recovery from injuries. The trained mechanical engineer used this downtime to improve the suspension elements of his motocross machine. Though the parts were originally intended only for his own use, Peters' success with his components was noticed by other racers, and he founded the company in 1977 to deal with demand.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA visual characteristic of the brand are the white coil springs on the [[Coilover|coilover suspension struts]], which also led to the original brand name, ''White Power''. The white [[Powder coating|coating]] of the springs was originally due to the chosen supplier being a [[hospital bed]] manufacturer, and white was the only colour they had available.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Racing success at the end of the 1970s and into the 1980s established the brand's reputation.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://tractivesuspension.com/history/|title=History|last=|first=|date=|website=Tractivesuspension.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322130425/https://tractivesuspension.com/history/|archive-date=2020-03-22|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, the company developed from an [[Automotive aftermarket|aftermarket]] producer to an [[original equipment manufacturer]] for [[KTM]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Griewe|first=Ron|date=January 1985|title=Dissecting the White Power Fork|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=KEtpOie7PjkC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=white%20power&f=false|journal=Cycle World|volume=24|issue=1|pages=54-55|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Griewe|first=Ron|date=August 1985|title=KTM 350MXC|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=KEtpOie7PjkC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=white%20power&f=false|journal=Cycle World|volume=24|issue=8|pages=40|via=Google Books}}</ref> in 1983, and later for [[Husaberg]] and [[BMW Motorrad]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1983, WP was the first manufacturer to introduce an [[upside-down fork]] (USD) into mass production.<!-- [[BSA Bantam]] had USD-appearance forks in 1950s --><ref name=\":1\" /> The USD fork has since become the standard equipment in on-road and off-road performance motorcycles.\n\nIn 1984, WP supplied suspension components to KTM's first [[Motocross World Championship]] victory in the 250cc class with [[Heinz Kinigadner]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wp-group.com/media/1480/firmenpraesentation_29032017.pdf|title=WP GROUP - COMPANY PRESENTATION|last=|first=|date=2017|website=WP-Group.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322120519/https://www.wp-group.com/media/1480/firmenpraesentation_29032017.pdf|archive-date=2020-03-22|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter bankruptcy in 1991 and the subsequent refounding, the brand name ''WP Suspension'' replaced the name ''White Power''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1994, WP supplied suspension components to the [[Benetton B194|B194]] car by [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] which propelled [[Michael Schumacher]] to his first [[Formula One|Formula 1]] world championship title.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== KTM subsidiary ===\nFrom 1997, [[KTM|KTM Power Sports]] gradually took over the company. Wim Peters remained connected with WP, initially as managing director and later as consultant until his departure in 2004. Beginning in 2009, production was moved to [[Munderfing]], Austria, and suspension components are no longer produced in the former main factory in Malden, Netherlands.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 2010s, WP expanded their manufacturing portfolio to include frames, exhaust systems, and oil and water coolers for motorcycles and was briefly renamed ''WP Performance Systems GmbH''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> As of 2020, the non-suspension activities have been sold off or transferred to other divisions within the parent company, with WP again concentrating solely on the development and manufacture of motorcycle suspension systems.\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Shock absorber]]\n*[[Motorcycle suspension]]\n*[[Motorcycle fork]]\n*[[List of motorcycle suspension manufacturers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:Companies of Austria]]\n[[Category:Motorcycle parts manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Shock absorber manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies of Austria]]\n[[Category:Automotive motorsports and performance companies]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://i.imgur.com/2voW7Pv.jpg Image of WP coilovers in the B194 front suspension]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20200322143625/https://media.gettyimages.com/photos/benettonford-b194-grand-prix-of-monaco-circuit-de-monaco-15-may-1994-picture-id951894338?s=2048x2048 Image of WP coilovers in the B194 rear suspension]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = WP Suspension GmbH\n| logo = WP Suspension logo.svg\n| logo_alt = Logo of the company WP Suspension\n| former_name = White Power Suspension\n| type = [[Companies with limited liability in German speaking countries|GmbH]]\n| industry = [[Motorcycle]]\n| founded = 1977\n| founder = Wim Peters\n| hq_location_city = [[Mattighofen]]\n| hq_location_country = Austria\n| products = Motorcycle suspension components\n| parent = [[KTM|KTM AG]]\n| website = {{URL|www.wp-suspension.com}}\n}}[[File:White power suspension.jpg|alt=WP rear shock unit|thumb|WP rear shock unit on a [[KTM 950 Adventure]]]]'''WP Suspension GmbH''' is a manufacturer of components for [[motorcycle suspension]] systems based in Austrian. The company was founded in 1977 as ''White Power Suspension [[Besloten vennootschap|B.V.]]'' in [[Malden, Netherlands|Malden]], Netherlands, by Wim Peters,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cycleworld.com/2015/04/22/wp-factory-dutch-suspension-manufacturer-tour/|title=WP Factory Tour|last=Catterson|first=Brian|date=2015-04-22|website=Cycle World|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> and is amongst the largest manufacturers of suspension components for [[Motorcycle|motorcycles]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|ur