page&q=white%20power&f=false|journal=Cycle World|volume=24|issue=1|pages=54-55|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Griewe|first=Ron|date=August 1985|title=KTM 350MXC|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=KEtpOie7PjkC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=white%20power&f=false|journal=Cycle World|volume=24|issue=8|pages=40|via=Google Books}}</ref> in 1983, and later for [[Husaberg]] and [[BMW Motorrad]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1983, WP was the first manufacturer to introduce an [[upside-down fork]] (USD) into mass production.<!-- [[BSA Bantam]] had USD-appearance forks in 1950s --><ref name=\":1\" /> The USD fork has since become the standard equipment in on-road and off-road performance motorcycles.\n\nIn 1984, WP supplied suspension components to KTM's first [[Motocross World Championship]] victory in the 250cc class with [[Heinz Kinigadner]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wp-group.com/media/1480/firmenpraesentation_29032017.pdf|title=WP GROUP - COMPANY PRESENATION|last=|first=|date=2017|website=WP-Group.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322120519/https://www.wp-group.com/media/1480/firmenpraesentation_29032017.pdf|archive-date=2020-03-22|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter bankruptcy in 1991 and the subsequent refounding, the brand name ''WP Suspension'' replaced the name ''White Power''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1994, WP supplied suspension components to the [[Benetton B194|B194]] car by [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] which propelled [[Michael Schumacher]] to his first [[Formula One|Formula 1]] world championship title.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== KTM subsidiary ===\nFrom 1997, [[KTM|KTM Power Sports]] gradually took over the company. Wim Peters remained connected with WP, initially as managing director and later as consultant until his departure in 2004. Beginning in 2009, production was moved to [[Munderfing]], Austria, and suspension components are no longer produced in the former main factory in Malden, Netherlands.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the 2010s, WP expanded their manufacturing portfolio to include frames, exhaust systems, and oil and water coolers for motorcycles and was briefly renamed ''WP Performance Systems GmbH''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> As of 2020, the non-suspension activities have been sold off or transferred to other divisions within the parent company, with WP again concentrating solely on the development and manufacture of motorcycle suspension systems.\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Shock absorber]]\n*[[Motorcycle suspension]]\n*[[Motorcycle fork]]\n*[[List of motorcycle suspension manufacturers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:Companies of Austria]]\n[[Category:Motorcycle parts manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Shock absorber manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies of Austria]]\n[[Category:Automotive motorsports and performance companies]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://i.imgur.com/2voW7Pv.jpg Image of WP coilovers in the B194 front suspension]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20200322143625/https://media.gettyimages.com/photos/benettonford-b194-grand-prix-of-monaco-circuit-de-monaco-15-may-1994-picture-id951894338?s=2048x2048 Image of WP coilovers in the B194 rear suspension]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP_Suspension"}
{"title_page": "Nursery Cryme", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Nursery Cryme\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]\n| cover        = NurseryCryme71.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 12 november 1971\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = [[Trident Studios]]<br><small>(London, England)</small>\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Progressive rock]]\n}}\n| length       = 39:26\n| label        = [[Charisma Records|Charisma]]\n| producer     = [[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]]\n| prev_title   = [[Trespass (album)|Trespass]]\n| prev_year    = 1970\n| next_title   = [[Foxtrot (album)|Foxtrot]]\n| next_year    = 1972\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Nursery Cryme\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Happy the Man\"/\"Seven Stones\n | single1date = 12 May 1972\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Nursery Cryme''''' is the third [[studio album]] by the English rock band [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], released in November 1971 on [[Charisma Records]]. It was their first to feature drummer/vocalist [[Phil Collins]] and guitarist [[Steve Hackett]]. The album received a mixed response from critics and was not initially a commercial success; it did not enter the UK chart until 1974, when it reached its peak at No. 39. However, the album was successful in Continental Europe, particularly Italy. At approximately 39 minutes long, it is the shortest studio album by the band to date.\n\nFollowing extensive touring in support of their previous album ''[[Trespass (album)|Trespass]]'' (1970), which included the recruitment of Collins and Hackett, the band began writing and rehearsing for a follow-up in [[Luxford House]], [[East Sussex]], with recording following at [[Trident Studios]]. ''Nursery Cryme'' saw the band take a more aggressive direction of some songs, with substantially improved drumming. The opening piece, \"[[The Musical Box (Genesis song)|The Musical Box]]\" combined the band's trademark mix of [[twelve-string guitar]]s with harsh electric guitars and keyboards. The song, a macabre [[fairy story]] set in Victorian Britain, became the inspiration for the album cover, and went on to be a live favourite. Collins brought a new dimension to the group, covering the majority of the backing vocals (including his first lead vocal with Genesis on \"For Absent Friends\") and bringing in a sense of humour on tracks like \"Harold The Barrel\". Banks made more prominent use of the [[Mellotron]] at Hackett's suggestion and used it prominently on several tracks.\n\nThe band toured the UK and Europe for one year to promote the album, which raised their profile in both territories. The tour included a successful Italian leg in April 1972, where the group played to enthusiastic crowds. ''Nursery Cryme'' was certified Silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] in 2013.\n\n==Background==\nGenesis recorded their first album as a professional outfit, ''[[Trespass (album)|Trespass]]'' in June 1970, but immediately afterwards, founding member and guitarist [[Anthony Phillips]] quit owing to increased stress and unhappiness in touring.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=34\u201335}} The other founders, singer [[Peter Gabriel]], keyboardist [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]] and bassist/guitarist [[Mike Rutherford]] almost split the group up, but decided to carry on and replace drummer [[John Mayhew (musician)|John Mayhew]] with someone who was an equal stature to the others, and who could write.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=35}}\n\n[[Phil Collins]] joined as the new drummer in August, also becoming an important backing vocalist, but they were unable to find a suitable replacement for Phillips. This led to the group completing the first half of their 1970\u20131971 tour as a four-piece with Rutherford playing rhythm guitar and [[bass pedal]]s and Banks playing lead guitar lines on a [[Pianet]] through a distorted [[Distortion (music)|fuzz box]] amplifier in addition to his own keyboard parts. Banks credited this to improving his technique as it required him to play two keyboards simultaneously.{{sfn|Genesis|2007|p=96}}{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=41}} The group felt that Collins was the best drummer they had worked with at that point, and his playing style and musical tastes gave a new dimension to their sound.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=46}} Some songs were not practical to play live as a four-piece, so they decided to look again for a lead guitarist. In November 1970, [[Mick Barnard]] joined the group on recommendation from [[Friars Aylesbury]]'s David Stopps, and \"The Musical Box\" was added to the live set.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=41}} However, the rest of the group quickly realised that Barnard was not up to the same standard as the others, and they kept a look out for a better player.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=42}}\n\n[[File:Luxford House.jpg|thumb|260px|right|Rehearsals took place at [[Luxford House]]]]\nGenesis recruited [[Steve Hackett]] after Gabriel spotted an advert he placed in ''[[Melody Maker]]'' in December 1970, which read \"Imaginative guitarist/writer seeks involvement with receptive musicians, determined to drive beyond existing stagnant music forms\". He saw Genesis play a concert at the [[Lyceum Theatre, London]] on 28 December, and was told by Gabriel that Barnard would have to be replaced.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=43}} Hackett quickly developed a rapport with Rutherford, sharing their love of [[twelve-string guitar]]s and new musical ideas, and joined the band in early 1971.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=44}}\n\nWith the addition of Hackett, Genesis continued touring which included the \"Six Bob Tour\" with their [[Charisma Records]] labelmates [[Lindisfarne]] and [[Van der Graaf Generator]],{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=44}} their first overseas shows which occurred in [[Belgium]]{{sfn|Hewitt|2001|p=32}} and the first of three appearances at the annual [[Reading Festival]].{{sfn|Platts|2001|p=42}} Early attempts to work on material for their next studio album in what Hackett described as \"the odd day in a windy church hall\" while on tour were unproductive, causing the group to dedicate time. In July, they began a three-month break from touring to write and record which was Hackett's first experience of rehearsing with a group to a professional standard.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=14:34\u201315:16}}\n\nAt the suggestion of Charisma's owner [[Tony Stratton-Smith]], the five retreated to [[Luxford House]], a 16th-century [[Grade II listed building]] that Stratton-Smith owned in [[Crowborough]], [[East Sussex]].{{sfn|Genesis|2007|pages=105\u2013106}} The group nicknamed the house \"Toad Hall\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=29:42\u201330:25}} The group was apprehensive about writing without Phillips, and both Collins and Hackett were unsure of what level of musical contributions they would be able to make.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=51}} Hackett was keen to explore new sounds and musical ideas, and suggested the group buy a [[Mellotron]], which Banks used as his main instrument, along with the [[Hammond organ]], instead of the piano. Some material had been written when Phillips and Mayhew were still in the band, and were reworked by the new members. Collins was a particular workaholic and was happy to jam with anyone at any time.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=53}}\n\n==Recording==\nWith the new material worked out, Genesis recorded ''Nursery Cryme'' at [[Trident Studios]] in London in August 1971 with [[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]] as their producer and [[David Hentschel]] their assistant engineer who, like Anthony, had worked the same role on ''Trespass''.<ref name=cas1052>{{cite AV media notes|title=Nursery Cryme|publisher=Charisma Records|id=CAS 1052|year=1971}}</ref> The album features Hackett playing a [[Les Paul]] guitar which the band had bought him along with a Hiwatt stack amplifier. He recalled some difficulty in understanding what Banks and Rutherford were talking about as the two had devised their own sayings, for instance a passage that they had played was referred to as a \"nice guy\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=15:00\u201316:18}}\n\n===Songs===\n\n====\"The Musical Box\"====\n\"[[The Musical Box (Genesis song)|The Musical Box]]\" was a lengthy piece that described a macabre story placed in Victorian Britain. A young boy, Henry, is accidentally decapitated by his friend Cynthia while playing croquet. Returning to the house, Cynthia plays Henry's old musical box, which unleashes the spirit of Henry as an old man. Henry has become sexually frustrated and attempts to seduce Cynthia. The nurse enters the room, hurls the musical box at the wall, destroying both it and Henry.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=54}}<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Nursery Cryme|publisher=[[Charisma Records]]|id=CAS 1052|year=1971}}</ref>\n\nThe song originated when Phillips was in the group who would often write with Rutherford on [[twelve-string guitar|12-string acoustic guitars]]. The latter had begun to experiment with unorthodox guitar tunings and had the top three strings tuned into F sharp which provided the jangly sound heard in the opening and the chord that signalled the start of the electric guitar solo.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=17:14\u201317:44}} The tuning influenced the title of an acoustic piece, \"F#\" (pronounced \"F sharp\") that became the basis of \"The Musical Box\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anthonyphillips.co.uk/discography/arccol.htm|title=Archive Collection|website=Anthonyphillips.co.uk|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> which was developed further after Phillips's departure. The opening section of the song features both Rutherford and Banks on twelve-string.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.guitarplayer.com/technique/decoding-the-12-string-tapestry-of-early-genesis|title=Decoding the 12-string Tapestry of Early Genesis|date=21 July 2015|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe guitar solos originated from Barnard's brief tenure in Genesis.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=41}} Hackett modified sections that Phillips and Barnard had written while adding his own arrangements to the song.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=53}} He realised that neither member had made a sound that resembled an actual musical box, so he took the opportunity to record a guitar lick that is heard before the lyric \"Here it comes again\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=18:23\u201318:43}} Gabriel, a big fan of [[The Who]] at the time, pushed for Rutherford to come up with a \"ballsy, attacking\" section in a similar style to their guitarist [[Pete Townshend]]. Gabriel incorporated themes of violence and sex into the lyrics.<ref name=gabdvd>[[#NurseryCrymeDVD|Gabriel, Peter. ''Reissues Interview 2007'' at 18:43\u201320:11]]</ref> Collins was inspired to play a rolling drum part during the middle section from hearing \"[[The Weaver's Answer]]\" by [[Family (band)|Family]], and put it to the rhythm. \"All of a sudden\", speaking about \"The Musical Box\" at this point, \"It's 'wahey we're off!'\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=21:30\u201321:50}}\n\nThe song became a live favourite during Gabriel's tenure with the band. He first decided on the idea of wearing costumes at a gig in the National Stadium, Dublin in September 1972, leaving during the instrumental break and re-appearing at the conclusion wearing his wife's red dress and a fox's head.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=69\u201370}} Later, he would wear an \"old man\" mask for the song's ending, acting out the part of the aged Henry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/sep/03/genesis-10-of-the-best|title=Genesis: 20 of the best|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 September 2014|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Other songs====\n[[File:Rbk dolde.jpg|thumb|left|\"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" described an outbreak of ''[[Heracleum mantegazzianum]]'' attacking the human race.]]\n\"For Absent Friends\" is an acoustic song that marked Hackett's first significant writing contribution for the group, and the first Genesis song with Collins on lead vocals.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=55}} After coming up with the music himself and the lyrics with Collins, Hackett recalled being shy when he presented it to Gabriel as they were the new members of the group.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=24:41\u201325:40}}\n\n\"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" warns of the spread of the toxic plant ''[[Heracleum mantegazzianum]]'' after it was \"captured\" in Russia and brought to England by a Victorian explorer. Though the real plant is extremely toxic and dangerous, the song's lyrics are a humorous exaggeration, suggesting the plant is attempting to take over the human race.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=55}} Both \"The Musical Box\" and \"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" feature Hackett's first use of [[Tapping|guitar tapping]], a technique whereby the index finger of the plucking hand is applied directly to the guitar [[fret board]]. The opening to the latter features Hackett and Banks playing triplets in harmony.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=31:02\u201331:49}}{{efn|\"Tapping\" did not attract mainstream attention until [[Eddie Van Halen]] demonstrated it in his instrumental \"[[Eruption (instrumental)|Eruption]]\", seven years after ''Nursery Cryme''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/steve-hackett-how-i-invented-finger-tapping-542029|title=Steve Hackett: how I invented finger tapping|website=Musicradar.com|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n\"Seven Stones\" was conceived by Banks who used what Rutherford described as \"his big, schmaltzy, music hall chords [that] he loved.\"{{sfn|Rutherford|2014|p=76}} ''[[Melody Maker]]'' reporter [[Chris Welch]] described the song as \"strangely mournful and inconclusive.\" He theorised that the old man addressed in the lyric is expressing his \"profound belief that the secret of success and good fortune is based purely on random events and chance.\"{{sfn|Welch|2011|p=34}}\n\n\"Harold the Barrel\" showed a humorous side to Genesis, which was encouraged by Collins. The lyrics show [[black humour]] of a man contemplating suicide by jumping off a building, with wordplay influenced by [[John Lennon]]'s ''[[In His Own Write]]''.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=46,55}} The track was recorded with Gabriel and Collins singing the song as a duet. Their vocals were mixed onto the same audio track so they cannot be separated.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=26:31\u201326:50}}{{efn|Gabriel and Collins would continue to sing together on several Genesis songs during their shared time in the band, performing a \"composite voice\" according to Hackett. Collins successfully replaced Gabriel as lead singer in 1975 because his voice was already familiar to listeners.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=119}}}}\n\n\"Harlequin\" was written by Rutherford. He played two separate guitar parts on a single 12-string which he thought produced \"pretty dodgy\" results, and was also critical of his lyrics.{{sfn|Rutherford|2014|p=76}}\n\n\"The Fountain of Salmacis\" tells the story of [[Salmacis]], the Greek mythological [[Naiad]] who became the first [[hermaphrodite]]. It originated from a short rundown passage that Banks had come up with while at university. The track makes use of the Mellotron, with an influence from [[King Crimson]]'s ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]''. Banks thought the instrument greatly complemented his piece when combined with the organ. It became the basis for \"The Fountain of Salmacis\" which was taken further to a complete song as the result of group jams.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=28:26\u201329:24}} Hackett particularly enjoyed the time he came up with his ending guitar solo, which occurred around midnight at Luxford House during a rare moment when the group were up for recording.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=29:42\u201330:25}}{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=55}}\n\n==Cover==\nThe album's sleeve was designed and illustrated by [[Paul Whitehead]] who had also designed the cover for ''Trespass'' and the band's next album, ''[[Foxtrot (album)|Foxtrot]]''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CpfMOEIZag4C&pg=PA15|page=15|title=Genesis and The Lamb Lies Down on Broadway|author=Kevin Holm-Hudson|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|date= 2008|isbn=9780754661474}}</ref> The cover depicts characters and scenes based on \"The Musical Box\" and Coxhill, the manor house with a croquet lawn, itself based on the Victorian home Gabriel grew up in.{{sfn|Macan|1997|pp=60\u201361}} When the group originally saw Whitehead's painting, they said it didn't look old enough, so he varnished it with honey which made it look like it was an antique from the 19th century. When originally released, the cover shocked some people, because of the severed heads pictured on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/cover-story-genesis-nursery-cryme|title=Out Of The Box: The Story Behind The Cover Of Genesis' \"Nursery Cryme\"|work=Louder Sound|first=Malcolm|last=Dome|date=12 November 2016|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe inner sleeve resembled an old photo album, with a panel for each song along with an illustrated picture.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=56}} Whitehead later picked his design for ''Nursery Cryme'' as his favourite of the three done for Genesis, noting: \"It just works very well with the music. It fits perfect. It's the right colour, the right vibe\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofgenesis.com/PaulWhitehead-interview.htm|title=Interviews \u2013 Paul Whitehead|publisher=World of Genesis|date=25 July 2001|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Nursery Cryme'' was released in November 1971.{{sfn|Welch|2011|p=31}} Charisma promoted the album less than ''Trespass'' since the company was busy with Lindisfarne's ''[[Fog on the Tyne]]''. The group felt discouraged by the general indifference from the record company, and believed songs like \"The Musical Box\" could have been as popular as \"[[Stairway to Heaven]]\", released at the same time.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=57}}\n\nThe album did not chart in the UK until May 1974, when it peaked at {{thinspace|No.| 39}},{{sfn|Genesis|2007|p=349}} and charted there again when reissued in 1984, reaching {{thinspace|No.| 68}}. Though the group still had a minor cult following at home, they started to achieve commercial and critical success in mainland Europe, with the album reaching No. 4 on the Italian charts.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=59}} The album continued to sell, and reached Silver certification by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] on 22 July 2013 for sales in excess of 60,000 copies.<ref name=bpi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx|title=Certified Awards: Enter \"Nursery Cryme\" in the search field and select \"Title\" and \"Exact Match\".|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom November 1971 to August 1972, Genesis toured to support the album which included further visits to Belgium, and Italy for the first time where they played to enthusiastic crowds.{{sfn|Genesis|2007|p=349}} During the tour Genesis recorded \"Happy the Man\", a non-album single, with \"Seven Stones\" from ''Nursery Cryme'' on its B-side.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=61,249}} The group played a thirty-minute set on Belgian television to promote the album, which is the earliest surviving full broadcast of the group and has been repeated numerous times. Gabriel had yet to develop his on-stage costume attire and performed the show in a more straightforward frontman role.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=59}} It has been one of Genesis' most popular [[bootleg recording|bootlegs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/genesis-dvd-bootleg-mw0001344494|title=Genesis [DVD/Bootleg]|first=Bruce|last=Eder|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Album ratings\n| title = Retrospective professional reviews\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=nursery-cryme-r8165|pure_url=yes}} |title=Nursery Cryme \u2013 Genesis &#124; AllMusic |first=Stephen Thomas |last=Erlewine |website=AllMusic |year=2011 <!-- latest update --> |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev2Score = C\u2013<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: G|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=G&bk=70|accessdate=February 24, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Great Rock Discography]]''\n| rev4Score = 8/10<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev5 = [[Music Story]]\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev6 = ''[[MusicHound|MusicHound Rock]]''\n| rev6Score = 3/5<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A4517.htm|title=Genesis|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7      = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite book | author1= Nathan Brackett | author2= Christian David Hoard| title = The new Rolling Stone album guide | publisher = Simon & Schuster | page = 327 | location = New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-7432-0169-8 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&pg=PA327 }}</ref>\n}}\nCritical response to the album was mixed. Richard Cromelin of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' summarised that its \"main problem lies not in Genesis' concepts, which are, if nothing else, outrageously imaginative and lovably eccentric, nor with their musical structures\u2014long, involved, multi-movemented frameworks on which they hang their narratives\u2014nor even with their playing, which does get pretty lethargic at points. It's the godawful production, a murky, distant stew that at best bubbles quietly when what is desperately needed are the explosions of drums and guitars, the screaming of the organ, the abrasive rasp of vocal cords.\" He nonetheless remarked positively on some of the songs, and noted that he saw promise in the band.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/genesis/albums/album/304752/review/5940391/nursery_cryme |title=Genesis: Nursery Cryme : Music Reviews : Rolling Stone |first=Richard |last=Cromelin |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=26 October 1972 |accessdate=7 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430233653/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/genesis/albums/album/304752/review/5940391/nursery_cryme |archivedate=30 April 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In a full page advert published in ''Melody Maker'', keyboardist [[Keith Emerson]] wrote a positive summary: \"This is not the start for Genesis neither is it the end. No bullshit: Their new album really is incredible\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://thegenesisarchive.co.uk/melody-maker-keith-emerson-talks-about-nursery-cryme-20th-november/|title=Genesis \u2013 Nursery Cryme \u2013 Keith Emerson says...|magazine=Melody Maker|date=20 November 1971|via=The Genesis Archive|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref> ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic in a review compiled for ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981). Writing in sarcastic exclamations, he said of the record: \"[[minced oath|God's wounds]]! It's a 'rock' version of the myth of [[Hermaphroditus]]! In quotes cos the organist and the (mime-influenced) vocalist have the drummer a little confused! Or maybe it's just the invocation to [[Old King Cole]]!\"<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n\nRetrospective appraisals have been mildly positive. [[BBC Music]] praised the two new members of the band as fundamental to Genesis's artistic success, remarking \"Collins' snappy drums were augmented by his uncanny ability to sound not unlike Gabriel&nbsp;... Hackett's armoury of tapping and swell techniques really broadened the palette of the band, giving Tony Banks more room for his Delius-lite organ filigrees, not to mention their newly purchased Mellotron\", and gushed that \"Genesis had virtually invented their own genre, Edwardian rock\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/p4xm |title=BBC \u2013 Music \u2013 Review of Genesis \u2013 Nursery Cryme |first=Chris |last=Jones |publisher=BBC  |date=18 April 2007 |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref> Although [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] deemed the album highly uneven, he considered \"The Musical Box\" and \"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" to be \"genuine masterpieces\", and concluded that even if the rest of the album \"isn't quite as compelling or quite as structured, it doesn't quite matter because these are the songs that showed what Genesis could do, and they still stand as pinnacles of what the band could achieve\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> [[Geddy Lee]] of [[Rush (band)|Rush]] included this album among his favourites in a list from an interview with ''[[The Quietus]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thequietus.com/articles/09210-rush-geddy-lee-interview-favourite-albums?page=5 |title= In The Mood: The Favourite Albums Of Rush's Geddy Lee |date= 29 June 2012<!-- 08:44-->}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs composed and arranged by [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]], [[Phil Collins]], [[Peter Gabriel]], [[Steve Hackett]], and [[Mike Rutherford]].<ref name=cas1052/>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Side one\n| title1          = [[The Musical Box (Genesis song)|The Musical Box]]\n| length1         = 10:25\n| title2          = For Absent Friends\n| length2         = 1:48\n| title3          = The Return of the Giant Hogweed\n| length3         = 8:09\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Side two\n| title1          = Seven Stones\n| length1         = 5:08\n| title2          = Harold the Barrel\n| length2         = 3:01\n| title3          = Harlequin\n| length3         = 2:56\n| title4          = The Fountain of Salmacis\n| length4         = 8:02\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's 1971 and 2007 liner notes.<ref name=cas1052/>\n\n'''Genesis'''\n*[[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]] \u2013 [[Hammond organ|organ]],  [[Mellotron]], [[piano]], [[electric piano]], [[Twelve-string guitar|12-string guitar]], [[backing vocals]]\n*[[Mike Rutherford]] \u2013 bass, [[bass pedal]]s, 12-string guitar, backing vocals\n*[[Peter Gabriel]] \u2013 lead voice, flute, oboe, bass drum, tambourine\n*[[Steve Hackett]] \u2013 electric guitar, 12-string guitar\n*[[Phil Collins]] \u2013 drums, voices, percussion, lead vocals on \"For Absent Friends\" <small>(uncredited)</small>\n\n'''Production'''\n*[[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]] \u2013 production\n*[[David Hentschel]] \u2013 assistant engineer\n*[[Mike Stone (record producer)|Mike Stone]] \u2013 [[tape op|tape jockey]]\n*[[Paul Whitehead]] \u2013 sleeve design\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n|{{Album chart|UK|39|artist=Genesis}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry |region=United Kingdom |artist=Genesis |title=Nursery Cryme |award=Silver |type=album |relyear=2009}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom |nosales=yes }}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Books===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=Genesis \u2013 A Biography|first=Dave|last=Bowler|first2=Bryan|last2=Dray|publisher=Sidgwick & Jackson|year=1992|isbn=978-0-283-06132-5|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/genesisbiography0000bowl_h5d4}}\n* {{cite book|title=Genesis: Chapter and Verse|first=Tony|last=Banks|first2=Phil|last2=Collins|first3=Peter|last3=Gabriel|first4=Steve|last4=Hackett|first5=Mike|last5=Rutherford|editor1-first=Philipp|editor1-last=Dodd|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|year=2007|isbn=978-0-297-84434-1|ref={{harvid|Genesis|2007}}}}\n* {{cite book|title=Opening the Musical Box \u2013 A Genesis Chronicle|first=Alan|last=Hewitt|publisher=Firefly Publishing|year=2001|isbn=978-0-946-71930-3|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/openingmusicalbo00hewi}}\n* {{cite book|last=Macan|first=Edward|title=Rocking the Classics: English Progressive Rock and the Counterculture|url=https://archive.org/details/rockingclassicse0000maca|url-access=registration|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=1997|isbn=978-0-195-09887-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Platts|first=Robin|title=Genesis: Inside & Out (1967\u20132000)|publisher=Collector's Guide Publishing|year=2001|isbn=978-1-896-52271-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rutherford|first=Mike|title=The Living Years|publisher=Hachette UK|year=2014|isbn=978-1-472-11035-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Welch|first=Chris|title=Genesis: The Complete Guide to Their Music|publisher=Omnibus Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0-857-12739-6|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===DVD media===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite video|people=Banks, Tony; Collins, Phil; Gabriel, Peter; Hackett, Steve; Rutherford, Mike|title=Genesis 1970\u20131975: Nursery Cryme|medium=DVD|date=10 November 2008|publisher=Virgin Records|id={{UPC|5099951968328}}|ref={{harvid|Nursery Cryme|2007}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.genesis-music.com/}}\n* {{Curlie|Arts/Music/Styles/R/Rock/Progressive/Bands_and_Artists/G/Genesis/}}\n\n{{Genesis|}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2014}}\n\n[[Category:1971 albums]]\n[[Category:Genesis (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Charisma Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Anthony (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Trident Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Nursery Cryme\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]\n| cover        = NurseryCryme71.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|df=yes|1971|11}}\n| recorded     = 12 november 1971\n| venue        = \n| studio       = [[Trident Studios]]<br><small>(London, England)</small>\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Progressive rock]]\n}}\n| length       = 39:26\n| label        = [[Charisma Records|Charisma]]\n| producer     = [[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]]\n| prev_title   = [[Trespass (album)|Trespass]]\n| prev_year    = 1970\n| next_title   = [[Foxtrot (album)|Foxtrot]]\n| next_year    = 1972\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Nursery Cryme\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Happy the Man\"/\"Seven Stones\n | single1date = 12 May 1972\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Nursery Cryme''''' is the third [[studio album]] by the English rock band [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], released in November 1971 on [[Charisma Records]]. It was their first to feature drummer/vocalist [[Phil Collins]] and guitarist [[Steve Hackett]]. The album received a mixed response from critics and was not initially a commercial success; it did not enter the UK chart until 1974, when it reached its peak at No. 39. However, the album was successful in Continental Europe, particularly Italy. At approximately 39 minutes long, it is the shortest studio album by the band to date.\n\nFollowing extensive touring in support of their previous album ''[[Trespass (album)|Trespass]]'' (1970), which included the recruitment of Collins and Hackett, the band began writing and rehearsing for a follow-up in [[Luxford House]], [[East Sussex]], with recording following at [[Trident Studios]]. ''Nursery Cryme'' saw the band take a more aggressive direction of some songs, with substantially improved drumming. The opening piece, \"[[The Musical Box (Genesis song)|The Musical Box]]\" combined the band's trademark mix of [[twelve-string guitar]]s with harsh electric guitars and keyboards. The song, a macabre [[fairy story]] set in Victorian Britain, became the inspiration for the album cover, and went on to be a live favourite. Collins brought a new dimension to the group, covering the majority of the backing vocals (including his first lead vocal with Genesis on \"For Absent Friends\") and bringing in a sense of humour on tracks like \"Harold The Barrel\". Banks made more prominent use of the [[Mellotron]] at Hackett's suggestion and used it prominently on several tracks.\n\nThe band toured the UK and Europe for one year to promote the album, which raised their profile in both territories. The tour included a successful Italian leg in April 1972, where the group played to enthusiastic crowds. ''Nursery Cryme'' was certified Silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] in 2013.\n\n==Background==\nGenesis recorded their first album as a professional outfit, ''[[Trespass (album)|Trespass]]'' in June 1970, but immediately afterwards, founding member and guitarist [[Anthony Phillips]] quit owing to increased stress and unhappiness in touring.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=34\u201335}} The other founders, singer [[Peter Gabriel]], keyboardist [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]] and bassist/guitarist [[Mike Rutherford]] almost split the group up, but decided to carry on and replace drummer [[John Mayhew (musician)|John Mayhew]] with someone who was an equal stature to the others, and who could write.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=35}}\n\n[[Phil Collins]] joined as the new drummer in August, also becoming an important backing vocalist, but they were unable to find a suitable replacement for Phillips. This led to the group completing the first half of their 1970\u20131971 tour as a four-piece with Rutherford playing rhythm guitar and [[bass pedal]]s and Banks playing lead guitar lines on a [[Pianet]] through a distorted [[Distortion (music)|fuzz box]] amplifier in addition to his own keyboard parts. Banks credited this to improving his technique as it required him to play two keyboards simultaneously.{{sfn|Genesis|2007|p=96}}{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=41}} The group felt that Collins was the best drummer they had worked with at that point, and his playing style and musical tastes gave a new dimension to their sound.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=46}} Some songs were not practical to play live as a four-piece, so they decided to look again for a lead guitarist. In November 1970, [[Mick Barnard]] joined the group on recommendation from [[Friars Aylesbury]]'s David Stopps, and \"The Musical Box\" was added to the live set.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=41}} However, the rest of the group quickly realised that Barnard was not up to the same standard as the others, and they kept a look out for a better player.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=42}}\n\n[[File:Luxford House.jpg|thumb|260px|right|Rehearsals took place at [[Luxford House]]]]\nGenesis recruited [[Steve Hackett]] after Gabriel spotted an advert he placed in ''[[Melody Maker]]'' in December 1970, which read \"Imaginative guitarist/writer seeks involvement with receptive musicians, determined to drive beyond existing stagnant music forms\". He saw Genesis play a concert at the [[Lyceum Theatre, London]] on 28 December, and was told by Gabriel that Barnard would have to be replaced.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=43}} Hackett quickly developed a rapport with Rutherford, sharing their love of [[twelve-string guitar]]s and new musical ideas, and joined the band in early 1971.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=44}}\n\nWith the addition of Hackett, Genesis continued touring which included the \"Six Bob Tour\" with their [[Charisma Records]] labelmates [[Lindisfarne]] and [[Van der Graaf Generator]],{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=44}} their first overseas shows which occurred in [[Belgium]]{{sfn|Hewitt|2001|p=32}} and the first of three appearances at the annual [[Reading Festival]].{{sfn|Platts|2001|p=42}} Early attempts to work on material for their next studio album in what Hackett described as \"the odd day in a windy church hall\" while on tour were unproductive, causing the group to dedicate time. In July, they began a three-month break from touring to write and record which was Hackett's first experience of rehearsing with a group to a professional standard.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=14:34\u201315:16}}\n\nAt the suggestion of Charisma's owner [[Tony Stratton-Smith]], the five retreated to [[Luxford House]], a 16th-century [[Grade II listed building]] that Stratton-Smith owned in [[Crowborough]], [[East Sussex]].{{sfn|Genesis|2007|pages=105\u2013106}} The group nicknamed the house \"Toad Hall\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=29:42\u201330:25}} The group was apprehensive about writing without Phillips, and both Collins and Hackett were unsure of what level of musical contributions they would be able to make.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=51}} Hackett was keen to explore new sounds and musical ideas, and suggested the group buy a [[Mellotron]], which Banks used as his main instrument, along with the [[Hammond organ]], instead of the piano. Some material had been written when Phillips and Mayhew were still in the band, and were reworked by the new members. Collins was a particular workaholic and was happy to jam with anyone at any time.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=53}}\n\n==Recording==\nWith the new material worked out, Genesis recorded ''Nursery Cryme'' at [[Trident Studios]] in London in August 1971 with [[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]] as their producer and [[David Hentschel]] their assistant engineer who, like Anthony, had worked the same role on ''Trespass''.<ref name=cas1052>{{cite AV media notes|title=Nursery Cryme|publisher=Charisma Records|id=CAS 1052|year=1971}}</ref> The album features Hackett playing a [[Les Paul]] guitar which the band had bought him along with a Hiwatt stack amplifier. He recalled some difficulty in understanding what Banks and Rutherford were talking about as the two had devised their own sayings, for instance a passage that they had played was referred to as a \"nice guy\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=15:00\u201316:18}}\n\n===Songs===\n\n====\"The Musical Box\"====\n\"[[The Musical Box (Genesis song)|The Musical Box]]\" was a lengthy piece that described a macabre story placed in Victorian Britain. A young boy, Henry, is accidentally decapitated by his friend Cynthia while playing croquet. Returning to the house, Cynthia plays Henry's old musical box, which unleashes the spirit of Henry as an old man. Henry has become sexually frustrated and attempts to seduce Cynthia. The nurse enters the room, hurls the musical box at the wall, destroying both it and Henry.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=54}}<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Nursery Cryme|publisher=[[Charisma Records]]|id=CAS 1052|year=1971}}</ref>\n\nThe song originated when Phillips was in the group who would often write with Rutherford on [[twelve-string guitar|12-string acoustic guitars]]. The latter had begun to experiment with unorthodox guitar tunings and had the top three strings tuned into F sharp which provided the jangly sound heard in the opening and the chord that signalled the start of the electric guitar solo.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=17:14\u201317:44}} The tuning influenced the title of an acoustic piece, \"F#\" (pronounced \"F sharp\") that became the basis of \"The Musical Box\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anthonyphillips.co.uk/discography/arccol.htm|title=Archive Collection|website=Anthonyphillips.co.uk|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> which was developed further after Phillips's departure. The opening section of the song features both Rutherford and Banks on twelve-string.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.guitarplayer.com/technique/decoding-the-12-string-tapestry-of-early-genesis|title=Decoding the 12-string Tapestry of Early Genesis|date=21 July 2015|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe guitar solos originated from Barnard's brief tenure in Genesis.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=41}} Hackett modified sections that Phillips and Barnard had written while adding his own arrangements to the song.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=53}} He realised that neither member had made a sound that resembled an actual musical box, so he took the opportunity to record a guitar lick that is heard before the lyric \"Here it comes again\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=18:23\u201318:43}} Gabriel, a big fan of [[The Who]] at the time, pushed for Rutherford to come up with a \"ballsy, attacking\" section in a similar style to their guitarist [[Pete Townshend]]. Gabriel incorporated themes of violence and sex into the lyrics.<ref name=gabdvd>[[#NurseryCrymeDVD|Gabriel, Peter. ''Reissues Interview 2007'' at 18:43\u201320:11]]</ref> Collins was inspired to play a rolling drum part during the middle section from hearing \"[[The Weaver's Answer]]\" by [[Family (band)|Family]], and put it to the rhythm. \"All of a sudden\", speaking about \"The Musical Box\" at this point, \"It's 'wahey we're off!'\".{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=21:30\u201321:50}}\n\nThe song became a live favourite during Gabriel's tenure with the band. He first decided on the idea of wearing costumes at a gig in the National Stadium, Dublin in September 1972, leaving during the instrumental break and re-appearing at the conclusion wearing his wife's red dress and a fox's head.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=69\u201370}} Later, he would wear an \"old man\" mask for the song's ending, acting out the part of the aged Henry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/sep/03/genesis-10-of-the-best|title=Genesis: 20 of the best|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 September 2014|accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Other songs====\n[[File:Rbk dolde.jpg|thumb|left|\"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" described an outbreak of ''[[Heracleum mantegazzianum]]'' attacking the human race.]]\n\"For Absent Friends\" is an acoustic song that marked Hackett's first significant writing contribution for the group, and the first Genesis song with Collins on lead vocals.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=55}} After coming up with the music himself and the lyrics with Collins, Hackett recalled being shy when he presented it to Gabriel as they were the new members of the group.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=24:41\u201325:40}}\n\n\"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" warns of the spread of the toxic plant ''[[Heracleum mantegazzianum]]'' after it was \"captured\" in Russia and brought to England by a Victorian explorer. Though the real plant is extremely toxic and dangerous, the song's lyrics are a humorous exaggeration, suggesting the plant is attempting to take over the human race.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=55}} Both \"The Musical Box\" and \"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" feature Hackett's first use of [[Tapping|guitar tapping]], a technique whereby the index finger of the plucking hand is applied directly to the guitar [[fret board]]. The opening to the latter features Hackett and Banks playing triplets in harmony.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=31:02\u201331:49}}{{efn|\"Tapping\" did not attract mainstream attention until [[Eddie Van Halen]] demonstrated it in his instrumental \"[[Eruption (instrumental)|Eruption]]\", seven years after ''Nursery Cryme''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/steve-hackett-how-i-invented-finger-tapping-542029|title=Steve Hackett: how I invented finger tapping|website=Musicradar.com|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n\"Seven Stones\" was conceived by Banks who used what Rutherford described as \"his big, schmaltzy, music hall chords [that] he loved.\"{{sfn|Rutherford|2014|p=76}} ''[[Melody Maker]]'' reporter [[Chris Welch]] described the song as \"strangely mournful and inconclusive.\" He theorised that the old man addressed in the lyric is expressing his \"profound belief that the secret of success and good fortune is based purely on random events and chance.\"{{sfn|Welch|2011|p=34}}\n\n\"Harold the Barrel\" showed a humorous side to Genesis, which was encouraged by Collins. The lyrics show [[black humour]] of a man contemplating suicide by jumping off a building, with wordplay influenced by [[John Lennon]]'s ''[[In His Own Write]]''.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=46,55}} The track was recorded with Gabriel and Collins singing the song as a duet. Their vocals were mixed onto the same audio track so they cannot be separated.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=26:31\u201326:50}}{{efn|Gabriel and Collins would continue to sing together on several Genesis songs during their shared time in the band, performing a \"composite voice\" according to Hackett. Collins successfully replaced Gabriel as lead singer in 1975 because his voice was already familiar to listeners.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=119}}}}\n\n\"Harlequin\" was written by Rutherford. He played two separate guitar parts on a single 12-string which he thought produced \"pretty dodgy\" results, and was also critical of his lyrics.{{sfn|Rutherford|2014|p=76}}\n\n\"The Fountain of Salmacis\" tells the story of [[Salmacis]], the Greek mythological [[Naiad]] who became the first [[hermaphrodite]]. It originated from a short rundown passage that Banks had come up with while at university. The track makes use of the Mellotron, with an influence from [[King Crimson]]'s ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]''. Banks thought the instrument greatly complemented his piece when combined with the organ. It became the basis for \"The Fountain of Salmacis\" which was taken further to a complete song as the result of group jams.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=28:26\u201329:24}} Hackett particularly enjoyed the time he came up with his ending guitar solo, which occurred around midnight at Luxford House during a rare moment when the group were up for recording.{{sfn|Nursery Cryme|2007|loc=29:42\u201330:25}}{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=55}}\n\n==Cover==\nThe album's sleeve was designed and illustrated by [[Paul Whitehead]] who had also designed the cover for ''Trespass'' and the band's next album, ''[[Foxtrot (album)|Foxtrot]]''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CpfMOEIZag4C&pg=PA15|page=15|title=Genesis and The Lamb Lies Down on Broadway|author=Kevin Holm-Hudson|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|date= 2008|isbn=9780754661474}}</ref> The cover depicts characters and scenes based on \"The Musical Box\" and Coxhill, the manor house with a croquet lawn, itself based on the Victorian home Gabriel grew up in.{{sfn|Macan|1997|pp=60\u201361}} When the group originally saw Whitehead's painting, they said it didn't look old enough, so he varnished it with honey which made it look like it was an antique from the 19th century. When originally released, the cover shocked some people, because of the severed heads pictured on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/cover-story-genesis-nursery-cryme|title=Out Of The Box: The Story Behind The Cover Of Genesis' \"Nursery Cryme\"|work=Louder Sound|first=Malcolm|last=Dome|date=12 November 2016|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe inner sleeve resembled an old photo album, with a panel for each song along with an illustrated picture.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=56}} Whitehead later picked his design for ''Nursery Cryme'' as his favourite of the three done for Genesis, noting: \"It just works very well with the music. It fits perfect. It's the right colour, the right vibe\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofgenesis.com/PaulWhitehead-interview.htm|title=Interviews \u2013 Paul Whitehead|publisher=World of Genesis|date=25 July 2001|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Nursery Cryme'' was released in November 1971.{{sfn|Welch|2011|p=31}} Charisma promoted the album less than ''Trespass'' since the company was busy with Lindisfarne's ''[[Fog on the Tyne]]''. The group felt discouraged by the general indifference from the record company, and believed songs like \"The Musical Box\" could have been as popular as \"[[Stairway to Heaven]]\", released at the same time.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=57}}\n\nThe album did not chart in the UK until May 1974, when it peaked at {{thinspace|No.| 39}},{{sfn|Genesis|2007|p=349}} and charted there again when reissued in 1984, reaching {{thinspace|No.| 68}}. Though the group still had a minor cult following at home, they started to achieve commercial and critical success in mainland Europe, with the album reaching No. 4 on the Italian charts.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=59}} The album continued to sell, and reached Silver certification by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] on 22 July 2013 for sales in excess of 60,000 copies.<ref name=bpi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx|title=Certified Awards: Enter \"Nursery Cryme\" in the search field and select \"Title\" and \"Exact Match\".|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom November 1971 to August 1972, Genesis toured to support the album which included further visits to Belgium, and Italy for the first time where they played to enthusiastic crowds.{{sfn|Genesis|2007|p=349}} During the tour Genesis recorded \"Happy the Man\", a non-album single, with \"Seven Stones\" from ''Nursery Cryme'' on its B-side.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|pp=61,249}} The group played a thirty-minute set on Belgian television to promote the album, which is the earliest surviving full broadcast of the group and has been repeated numerous times. Gabriel had yet to develop his on-stage costume attire and performed the show in a more straightforward frontman role.{{sfn|Bowler|Dray|1992|p=59}} It has been one of Genesis' most popular [[bootleg recording|bootlegs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/genesis-dvd-bootleg-mw0001344494|title=Genesis [DVD/Bootleg]|first=Bruce|last=Eder|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Album ratings\n| title = Retrospective professional reviews\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=nursery-cryme-r8165|pure_url=yes}} |title=Nursery Cryme \u2013 Genesis &#124; AllMusic |first=Stephen Thomas |last=Erlewine |website=AllMusic |year=2011 <!-- latest update --> |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev2Score = C\u2013<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: G|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=G&bk=70|accessdate=February 24, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Great Rock Discography]]''\n| rev4Score = 8/10<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev5 = [[Music Story]]\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev6 = ''[[MusicHound|MusicHound Rock]]''\n| rev6Score = 3/5<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A4517.htm|title=Genesis|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7      = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite book | author1= Nathan Brackett | author2= Christian David Hoard| title = The new Rolling Stone album guide | publisher = Simon & Schuster | page = 327 | location = New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-7432-0169-8 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&pg=PA327 }}</ref>\n}}\nCritical response to the album was mixed. Richard Cromelin of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' summarised that its \"main problem lies not in Genesis' concepts, which are, if nothing else, outrageously imaginative and lovably eccentric, nor with their musical structures\u2014long, involved, multi-movemented frameworks on which they hang their narratives\u2014nor even with their playing, which does get pretty lethargic at points. It's the godawful production, a murky, distant stew that at best bubbles quietly when what is desperately needed are the explosions of drums and guitars, the screaming of the organ, the abrasive rasp of vocal cords.\" He nonetheless remarked positively on some of the songs, and noted that he saw promise in the band.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/genesis/albums/album/304752/review/5940391/nursery_cryme |title=Genesis: Nursery Cryme : Music Reviews : Rolling Stone |first=Richard |last=Cromelin |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=26 October 1972 |accessdate=7 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430233653/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/genesis/albums/album/304752/review/5940391/nursery_cryme |archivedate=30 April 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In a full page advert published in ''Melody Maker'', keyboardist [[Keith Emerson]] wrote a positive summary: \"This is not the start for Genesis neither is it the end. No bullshit: Their new album really is incredible\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://thegenesisarchive.co.uk/melody-maker-keith-emerson-talks-about-nursery-cryme-20th-november/|title=Genesis \u2013 Nursery Cryme \u2013 Keith Emerson says...|magazine=Melody Maker|date=20 November 1971|via=The Genesis Archive|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref> ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic in a review compiled for ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981). Writing in sarcastic exclamations, he said of the record: \"[[minced oath|God's wounds]]! It's a 'rock' version of the myth of [[Hermaphroditus]]! In quotes cos the organist and the (mime-influenced) vocalist have the drummer a little confused! Or maybe it's just the invocation to [[Old King Cole]]!\"<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n\nRetrospective appraisals have been mildly positive. [[BBC Music]] praised the two new members of the band as fundamental to Genesis's artistic success, remarking \"Collins' snappy drums were augmented by his uncanny ability to sound not unlike Gabriel&nbsp;... Hackett's armoury of tapping and swell techniques really broadened the palette of the band, giving Tony Banks more room for his Delius-lite organ filigrees, not to mention their newly purchased Mellotron\", and gushed that \"Genesis had virtually invented their own genre, Edwardian rock\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/p4xm |title=BBC \u2013 Music \u2013 Review of Genesis \u2013 Nursery Cryme |first=Chris |last=Jones |publisher=BBC  |date=18 April 2007 |accessdate=25 July 2011}}</ref> Although [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] deemed the album highly uneven, he considered \"The Musical Box\" and \"The Return of the Giant Hogweed\" to be \"genuine masterpieces\", and concluded that even if the rest of the album \"isn't quite as compelling or quite as structured, it doesn't quite matter because these are the songs that showed what Genesis could do, and they still stand as pinnacles of what the band could achieve\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> [[Geddy Lee]] of [[Rush (band)|Rush]] included this album among his favourites in a list from an interview with ''[[The Quietus]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thequietus.com/articles/09210-rush-geddy-lee-interview-favourite-albums?page=5 |title= In The Mood: The Favourite Albums Of Rush's Geddy Lee |date= 29 June 2012<!-- 08:44-->}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs composed and arranged by [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]], [[Phil Collins]], [[Peter Gabriel]], [[Steve Hackett]], and [[Mike Rutherford]].<ref name=cas1052/>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Side one\n| title1          = [[The Musical Box (Genesis song)|The Musical Box]]\n| length1         = 10:25\n| title2          = For Absent Friends\n| length2         = 1:48\n| title3          = The Return of the Giant Hogweed\n| length3         = 8:09\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Side two\n| title1          = Seven Stones\n| length1         = 5:08\n| title2          = Harold the Barrel\n| length2         = 3:01\n| title3          = Harlequin\n| length3         = 2:56\n| title4          = The Fountain of Salmacis\n| length4         = 8:02\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's 1971 and 2007 liner notes.<ref name=cas1052/>\n\n'''Genesis'''\n*[[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]] \u2013 [[Hammond organ|organ]],  [[Mellotron]], [[piano]], [[electric piano]], [[Twelve-string guitar|12-string guitar]], [[backing vocals]]\n*[[Mike Rutherford]] \u2013 bass, [[bass pedal]]s, 12-string guitar, backing vocals\n*[[Peter Gabriel]] \u2013 lead voice, flute, oboe, bass drum, tambourine\n*[[Steve Hackett]] \u2013 electric guitar, 12-string guitar\n*[[Phil Collins]] \u2013 drums, voices, percussion, lead vocals on \"For Absent Friends\" <small>(uncredited)</small>\n\n'''Production'''\n*[[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]] \u2013 production\n*[[David Hentschel]] \u2013 assistant engineer\n*[[Mike Stone (record producer)|Mike Stone]] \u2013 [[tape op|tape jockey]]\n*[[Paul Whitehead]] \u2013 sleeve design\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n|{{Album chart|UK|39|artist=Genesis}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry |region=United Kingdom |artist=Genesis |title=Nursery Cryme |award=Silver |type=album |relyear=2009}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom |nosales=yes }}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Books===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=Genesis \u2013 A Biography|first=Dave|last=Bowler|first2=Bryan|last2=Dray|publisher=Sidgwick & Jackson|year=1992|isbn=978-0-283-06132-5|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/genesisbiography0000bowl_h5d4}}\n* {{cite book|title=Genesis: Chapter and Verse|first=Tony|last=Banks|first2=Phil|last2=Collins|first3=Peter|last3=Gabriel|first4=Steve|last4=Hackett|first5=Mike|last5=Rutherford|editor1-first=Philipp|editor1-last=Dodd|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|year=2007|isbn=978-0-297-84434-1|ref={{harvid|Genesis|2007}}}}\n* {{cite book|title=Opening the Musical Box \u2013 A Genesis Chronicle|first=Alan|last=Hewitt|publisher=Firefly Publishing|year=2001|isbn=978-0-946-71930-3|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/openingmusicalbo00hewi}}\n* {{cite book|last=Macan|first=Edward|title=Rocking the Classics: English Progressive Rock and the Counterculture|url=https://archive.org/details/rockingclassicse0000maca|url-access=registration|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=1997|isbn=978-0-195-09887-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Platts|first=Robin|title=Genesis: Inside & Out (1967\u20132000)|publisher=Collector's Guide Publishing|year=2001|isbn=978-1-896-52271-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rutherford|first=Mike|title=The Living Years|publisher=Hachette UK|year=2014|isbn=978-1-472-11035-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Welch|first=Chris|title=Genesis: The Complete Guide to Their Music|publisher=Omnibus Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0-857-12739-6|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===DVD media===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite video|people=Banks, Tony; Collins, Phil; Gabriel, Peter; Hackett, Steve; Rutherford, Mike|title=Genesis 1970\u20131975: Nursery Cryme|medium=DVD|date=10 November 2008|publisher=Virgin Records|id={{UPC|5099951968328}}|ref={{harvid|Nursery Cryme|2007}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.genesis-music.com/}}\n* {{Curlie|Arts/Music/Styles/R/Rock/Progressive/Bands_and_Artists/G/Genesis/}}\n\n{{Genesis|}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2014}}\n\n[[Category:1971 albums]]\n[[Category:Genesis (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Charisma Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Anthony (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Trident Studios]]\n